episodesByNumber.title: #1: Going Waaaay Back-
episodesByNumber.tease: We unearth the first national New Sounds program from 1986.

episodesByNumber.title: #2: Really Old New Sounds
episodesByNumber.tease: Kitaro (Silk Road), Herbie Mann with Minoru Muraoka (Gagaku & Beyond), Osamu Kitajima (Masterclass Samurai), David Bowie Brian Eno (Heroes), Oregon, Ben Tavera King (Border Crossings), The Bothy Band (The Best of...), Planxty (Words & Music), Lutunn Noz/Bernard Benoit (Celtic Music for Guitar), E.

episodesByNumber.title: #3: Unusual Suspects-
episodesByNumber.tease: Philip Glass performs Rubric.

episodesByNumber.title: #4: More Unusual Suspects-
episodesByNumber.tease: Music by Ransom Wilson (Reich, Glass, Becker), W.

episodesByNumber.title: #5: Program #005
episodesByNumber.tease: This December 5, 1986 episode of New Sounds looks at a wide swath of contemporary composers who have explored new ways of extending the musical possibilities of the human voice.

episodesByNumber.title: #6: New Music from Canada-
episodesByNumber.tease:
Music by Jean-Paul L'Heureux and Marc Laperle (Crepuscule/Dusk), Danna & Clement (A Gradual Awakening), Robert Daigneault (Electronic Music by Canadian Composers, vol 1.), Lubomyr Melnyk (The Song of Galadriel), 
The Glass Orchestra (Verrillon), Contrevent (Jeu de Paume), Conventum    (Recommended Records Sampler.)    .

episodesByNumber.title: #8: Old Wine in New Bottles-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear W.

episodesByNumber.title: #9: The Indian Influence-
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear Western contemporary music inspired or influenced by the music of India, including short interview segments with Ravi Shankar.

episodesByNumber.title: #10: Music with Computers-
episodesByNumber.tease: Music by David Behrman (On The Other Ocean), "Blue Gene Tyranny" (The Intermediary), Reed Holmes (Computer Music From The Outside in), Richard Teitelbaum (Blends/The Digital Pianos.)

episodesByNumber.title: #14: New Music from Germany-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Cluster & Eno, Deuter (Nirvana Road), Stephan Micus (Koan), Klaus Schulze (Dune), Hans Otte (Das Buch der Klange/The Book of Sounds), Tangerine Dream (Stratosfear), and Camera Obscura.

episodesByNumber.title: #15: Dreams-
episodesByNumber.tease: Let the montage begin with music by John Cage (Music for Keyboard, 1935-48) played by Jeanne Kirstein, and George Crumb (Lux Aeterna/Dream Sequence) performed by the Aeolian Chamber Players.

episodesByNumber.title: #16: The African Influence-
episodesByNumber.tease: Music by Touch (Ritual: Magnetic North), Jon Hassell & Brian Eno (Possible Musics), Penguin Cafe Orchestra, Egberto Gismonti (Sol Do Meio Dia), Francis Bebey (Akwaaba), Djurdjura, Obo Addy (Kukrudu), Peter Gabriel (Birdy), Talking Heads (Remain in Light), David Gilden (live performance --Kelfaba, Mamadou Masina), and Ali Jihad Racy (Ancient Egypt.) .

episodesByNumber.title: #17: Extending the Piano-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by La Monte Young (The Well Tuned Piano), Terry Riley (The Harp of New Albion), Michael Harrison (The Windham Hill Piano Sampler), Allaudin Mathieu (In The Wind), Stephen Scott (New Music for Bowed Piano), Elodie Lauten (Piano Works, Concerto for Piano and Orchestral Memory), William Duckworth (The Time Curve Preludes), Laraaji (live improvisation --Inside the piano) .

episodesByNumber.title: #18: New Music from the Northwest-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works from Kurt Riemann (Electronic Nightworks), K.

episodesByNumber.title: #19: Orchestral New Music -
episodesByNumber.tease: Music by Philip Glass (Mishima, Satyagraha), Keith Jarrett (Arbour Zena), Arvo Part (Tabula Rasa), and Kay Gardner (A Rainbow Path.)

episodesByNumber.title: #20: More Old New Sounds-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear several selections by the group Oregon, one of the first groups to blur and erase lines between jazz, classical and folk musics.

episodesByNumber.title: #21: Unusual Folksong Arrangments-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear arrangements from England, Ireland, France, Sweden, and the states of traditional folk tunes, performed by John Renbourn (The Lady & the Unicorn), The Bothy Band (Out of the Wind Into The Sun), An Triskell (Harpe Celtique), Alan Stivell (Renaissance of the Celtic Harp), Sandy Denny (Who Knows Where the Time Goes), Traffic (John Barleycorn Must Die), Andrew Cronshaw (The Great Dark Water), Bjorn Jison Lindh (Atlantis), Dave Pegg (The Cocktail Cowboy Goes It Alone), Malicorne (untitled - "La Blanche Biche") Marc Johnson (Bass Desires).

episodesByNumber.title: #22: Extending the Violin-
episodesByNumber.tease: For this From the Vaults program from 1986, it’s way back to the days of the “extended instruments” series on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #24: Minimalism: Second Generation-
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to Terry Riley's seminal work "In C," along with music from John Adams (Shaker Loops/Phrygian Gates), Paul Dresher (Night Songs/Channels Passing), David Borden (Anatidae), Mikel Rouse (A Walk In The Woods), Zeitgeist (Zephyr), and Peter Michael Hamel.

episodesByNumber.title: #25: New Sounds of Ancient Music-
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, there's music by Guiot de Dijon (Troubadours & Trouveres), John Renbourn (The Lady and the Unicorn), Shirley Collins with David Munrow (Amaranth), Hildegard von Bingen (A Feather On the Breath of God), Lou Harrison (3 Pieces for Gamelan/String Quartet Set), John Renbourn Group (A Maid in Bedlam), Armenie: Chant Liturgiques du Moyen-Age.

episodesByNumber.title: #26: More Minimalism-
episodesByNumber.tease: With music by Daniel Lentz (On the Leopard Altar), Ingram Marshall (Fog Tropes/Gradual Requiem), Philip Glass/Robert Moran (private tape/Relache: "Juniper Variations"), Lucia Hwong (House of Sleeping Beauties), Stomu Yamashita (Sea and Sky).

episodesByNumber.title: #27: New Music from France-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Pierre Bensusan (II, Musique), Alain Markusfeld (Contemporus), Bernard Xolotl (Procession), Art Zoyd (Phase IV), and Jean-Michel Jarre (Zoolook.)

episodesByNumber.title: #29: Extending the Voice, Part 2-
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the chants of Tibetan Buddhism (Tantras of Gyuto), David Hykes and the Harmonic Choir (Harmonic Meetings), Herbie Mann (Gagaku & Beyond), Niorin Ni Rianin (Caoineadh na Maighdine), Meredith Monk (Dolmen Music), Laurie Anderson (Mr.

episodesByNumber.title: #30: The Art of Acoustic Guitar-
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, listen to Celtic music for guitar, along with works by Ben Tavera King, Robbie Basho, William Ackerman, Bill Connors, Gino D'Auri, Jukka Tolonen, and Brij Bhushan Kabra.

episodesByNumber.title: #31: Extending the Guitar-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Terje Rypdal (After the Rain), Brian Eno (Before and After Science), Budd/Bowen (Cold Blue Sampler), Fripp and Eno (Evening Star), Paul Dresher (Dark Blue Circumstance), Maciunas Ensemble (Music for Everyman), Bill Frisell (In Line), Glenn Branca (Symphony #3: Gloria.) .

episodesByNumber.title: #32: Philip Aaberg-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Philip Aaberg in conversation and performance on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #33: Songs of Technology-
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program is a collection of works for taped voices, computer-sampled voices, processed voices, and singing computer.

episodesByNumber.title: #34: New Music from the Midwest-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Tim Story, Steve Tibbetts, Ellipsis, and the Minnesota-based Zeitgest.

episodesByNumber.title: #35: Vaults: Gavin Bryars
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds From the Vaults time-warps back nearly twenty years for the first WNYC studio visit from English composer Gavin Bryars.

episodesByNumber.title: #37: Place, Show-
episodesByNumber.tease: Musical Depictions is the theme of this New Sounds program, where we'll hear new music describing a specific locale, like Alcatraz, or someplace in winter.

episodesByNumber.title: #38: Still More Old New Sounds-
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to "A Maze With Grace," music by Thomas Albert, as played by Relache from a live performance, plus music by Donald Sosin ("Cindy") and Arvo Part (Tabula Rasa.) And Margaret Leng Tan plays music by Somei Satoh.

episodesByNumber.title: #39: New Sounds in Film Music, Part 1-
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to possibly familiar works by the likes of Mike Oldfield (Tubular Bells), Walter/Wendy Carlos (A Clockwork Orange/The Shining), Ravi Shankar (Chappaqua, Gandhi), Philip Glass (Koyaahisqatsi), and Michael Hedges/Philip Aaberg (The Shape of the Land.)  Plus, Peter Gabriel's score to the film Birdy.

episodesByNumber.title: #40: Spacey Electronic Music-
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to some electronic music centered around the theme of the heavens, planets, and the like.

episodesByNumber.title: #41: Musica Elettronica Viva-
episodesByNumber.tease: Three composers Alvin Curran, Frederic Rzewski, and Richard Teitelbaum collaborated together back in the mid-60's, when in Rome.

episodesByNumber.title: #42: World Music in 1987-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that combines influences from India, Indonesia, Japan, Central America, and North Africa - all in one show.

episodesByNumber.title: #43: Music for Invented Instruments-
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music by Gayle Young (According to the Moon), Michael Sterns (Morning/Jewel), Glass Orchestra (Verrillon), Stephen Scott (New Music for Bowed Piano), Stephan Micus (Wings Over Water), Elodie Lauten (The Death of Don Juan), Robert Grawi (Pieces for Gravikord.) .

episodesByNumber.title: #44: Piano with Unusual Instruments-
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music for piano and Tibetan Singing Bowls from French composer Alain Kremski, works by John Surman like "Sunday Morning" (Such Winters of Memory), and an excerpt from "Holding Pattern" (Withholding Pattern).

episodesByNumber.title: #45: New Music From Poland--
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear live performance of music from composer, singer and multi-instrumentalist Mieczyslaw Litwinski on this New Sounds program, along with Henrky Gorecki's Symphony of Sorrowful Songs, as well as the uncategorizable electro-acoustic blend of the Orchestra of the Eighth Day.

episodesByNumber.title: #46: Electroacoustic Music-
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to Film Music from trumpter and synthesizer player Mark Isham, along with music from Enya, Eithne Ni Bhraonain, David Bedford, Eberhard Schoener, Richard Vimal, Pepe Maina, and Neuronium.

episodesByNumber.title: #47: The Third Stream-
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, hear music by Oregon (Music of Another Present Era), Miles Davis (Circle In The Round), Jon Hassell (Power Spot), Art Ensemble of Chicago (The Third Decade), and Stephan Micus (Koan.) .

episodesByNumber.title: #48: New From the South, #48-
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to music from Jack Tamul ("the Parthenon"), Jonn Serrie (Starmoods), John McCutcheon (Winter Solstice), Beausoleil (Parlez-nous a boire), Alvin Batiste (Musique d'Afrique Nouvell Orleans), Delay Tactics (Any Questions?), Michael Hunt (Reflections), and Martin E.

episodesByNumber.title: #49: The First New Sounds Live at Merkin Hall
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear excerpts from the very first New Sounds Live in September 1986 at Merkin Hall including "Scenes," pieces for theatre, dance, and film, by violinist/composer Michael Galasso.

episodesByNumber.title: #50: Prepared Pieces-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Ralph Towner (Blue Sun), Anthony Phillips (Private Parts and Pieces I and II), Malcolm Dalglish (Jogging The Memory), and Laraaji (live zither improvisations.)

episodesByNumber.title: #51: Unusual Folksong Arrangments-
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to unusual renderings of folksongs, some from Greece, France, and elsewhere on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #52: Songbirdsongs-
episodesByNumber.tease:
Hear music for the birds on this revived New Sounds from Olivier Messiaen (Catalogues des Oiseaux), John Adams (Songbirdsongs), Philip Aaberg (High Plains), Paul Winter (Canyon), Einojuhani Rautavaasra (Cantus Arcticus: Concerto for Birds and Orchestra), Daniel Goode (The Thursh from Upper Dunakyn), Eberhard Schoener (Sky Music/Mountain Music.)

episodesByNumber.title: #53: New Music from Japan-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some new music from Japan on this New Sounds program, including music from Yas-Kaz (Jomonsho), Ryuichi Sakamoto (PianoOne, Esperanto), Osamu Kitajima (The Source), Scott/Yuize/Yamamoto (Music for Zen Meditation, excerpt), Interior (Interior), Kitaro (Tunhuang), Tosha Suiho (The Four Seasons In Kyoto.) .

episodesByNumber.title: #54: New Music from California-
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from so-called "California school" composers John Adams (Light Over Water), Morton Subotnick (The Key to Songs), Harold Budd (Marty Walker/Clarinet, Lovely Thunder), Ingram Marshall (Cold Blue Sampler), and Rick Cox (Cold Blue Sampler.) .

episodesByNumber.title: #55: Extending the Accordion-
episodesByNumber.tease: This 1987 New Sounds program features music for the extended accordion, (and that family of instruments.) Listen to Dino Saluzzi and his bandoneon, from the classic 1985 ECM recording, “Once upon a time, far away in the south.” Plus, there’s Pauline Oliveros’ haunting accordion over a pulsing drone, and new music from “New York's master of the squeeze,” Guy Klucevsek.

episodesByNumber.title: #56: A Conversation with Keith Jarrett-
episodesByNumber.tease: John visited pianist Keith Jarrett back in 1987 - not in the usual confines of the WNYC studios, but on Jarrett's front porch near the Delaware River in New Jersey.

episodesByNumber.title: #57:  - Live from Merkin Hall II
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear performances of music from French guitarist Dan Ar Bras, and the electrified cellist Tom McVeety, recorded live at Merkin Concert Hall in 1986.

episodesByNumber.title: #58:   - On Presuming to be Modern
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to music by Larry Fast, Wendy Carlos, Film Music by Mark Isham, and music from Philip Perkins.

episodesByNumber.title: #59:   - Film Music
episodesByNumber.tease: In this second part of a series on New Sounds, listen to film music from Vangelis, Terry Riley's "No Man's Land," Mark Isham, Nino Rota's "Amarcord" arranged by Bill Frisell, Ennio Morricone's "The Big Gundown" arranged by John Zorn, and Gary Sloan's "Nightraid." .

episodesByNumber.title: #60:   - World Music, Part 3
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music by Stephen Coughlin, Lothlorien, Popol Vuh, and Eberhard Schoener on this New Sounds.  Plus, listen to works by Paul Dresher, and Frank Perry.

episodesByNumber.title: #61:   - New Music from South America
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to New Music from South America, including works from Atahualpa Yupanqui, Inti-Illimani, Sergio Cervetti, Egberto Gismonti, and Nana Vasconcelos, Una Ramos, William Ackerman, Bola Sete, and the Tango King Astor Piazzola.

episodesByNumber.title: #63: Music from New England
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from New England on this New Sounds program, including works from Lar Duggan (The Lake Studies), Pat Metheny (New Chatauqua, Watercolors), Gary Burton & Chick Corea (Duet), Do'A (Ancient Beauty), Michael Carnes (Composers in Red Sneakers), and Paul Lehrman (The Celtic Macintosh).

episodesByNumber.title: #64:   - Extending the Voice, Part 3
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, it's the third in the "Extending the Voice" series of programs.

episodesByNumber.title: #66:   - G.I. Gurdjieff
episodesByNumber.tease: Even though the Armenian composer, mystic, and philosopher G.I.

episodesByNumber.title: #67:   - Electronic Instruments
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from Morton Subotnick and Olivier Messiaen on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #68: # 68 - : Codona
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear African, Asian, and other indigenous musics in the cooperative trio known as Codona, made up of multi-instrumentalist Collin Walcott, trumpeter Don Cherry, and percussionist Nana Vasconcelos.

episodesByNumber.title: #69: New Sounds #69-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Peter Michael Hamel (Organum), Steve Reich (Tehillim), Arvo Part (Tabula Rasa), Constance Demby (Novus Magnificat), Daniel Lentz (On the Leopard Altar, Missa Umbrarum), Niorin Ni Riain (Caoineadh na Maighdine.) .

episodesByNumber.title: #70: New Sounds #70 -
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some pop music from around the world on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #71: New Sounds #71 -
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to this exclusive interview in Wendy Carlos' studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #72: New Sounds #72 -
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds the Undead, listen to a show from August of 1987, featuring music by Randall Meyers (ERA /Indian Impressinos), Alex de Grassi (Altiplano), Zaikir Hussain with John McLaughlin (Making Music), Nels Cline/Eric Von Essen (elegies), and Robert Fripp and The League of Crafty Guitarists.

episodesByNumber.title: #73:   - Michael Hedges and Michael Manring
episodesByNumber.tease: The incredibly gifted and astonishingly original guitarist Michael Hedges left the planet much too soon in 1997.

episodesByNumber.title: #74:   - Satyagraha
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to a suite of excerpts from the opera by Philip Glass about the early career of Mohandas K.

episodesByNumber.title: #75: Looking Back
episodesByNumber.tease: This program features traditional styles of music including performances and works from: John Fahey (Of Rivers and Religion, Railroads I), George Winston (Ballads and Blues 1972), Mac Rebennack (Dr.

episodesByNumber.title: #76: Zeitgeist-Live
episodesByNumber.tease: Zeitgeist (live performances from Stokes' "Susquehannas," Thesisen's "Marbles," Rzewski's "Wails," and Bowers' "Pattern Study #2").

episodesByNumber.title: #78: New Sounds Live from Merkin Concert Hall IV
episodesByNumber.tease: Live performences from Merkin Concert Hall by Richard Pierce Milner ("Rolling Sea," "A Funny Man With..."), and Daniel Lentz Ensemble ("Time's Trick," "Wild Turkeys," "The Crack In The Bell").

episodesByNumber.title: #79: New Music for Brass
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear snappy brass from David Byrne's Music for The Knee Plays, Lester Bowie's Brass Fantasy, the 29th Street Saxophone Quartet, and Lenny Pickett on this New Sounds from 1987.

episodesByNumber.title: #80:   - New Music from India
episodesByNumber.tease: There's new music from India on this New Sounds program.
Hear music by Juan Martin and Mark Isham, Mark Isham and Art Lande, Art Lande, and music from the album "Skylight" featuring Art Lande, Paul McCandless, and David Samuels.

episodesByNumber.title: #82:   - Hal Willner Presents
episodesByNumber.tease: The eclectic and original producer/curator Hal Willner is the subject of this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #83:   - The Kronos Quartet
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music performed by the Kronos Quartet on this edition of New Sounds, with music by Philip Tlass, Jon Hassell, Bill Evans, Alan Dorsey, Kevin Volans, and Terry Riley.

episodesByNumber.title: #84:  - Penguin Cafe Orchestra
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program features the music of Simon Jeffes and his idiosyncratic ensemble.

episodesByNumber.title: #85:   - Music Downtown
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear from the crop of "downtown" musicians on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #86:  - Film Music Part 3
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music for film on this New Sounds program, including works by Michael Nyman from The Fraughtsman's Contract, Schonherz & Scott, Micheal Stearns, Ry Cooder's Paris, Texas, Brian Eno's score for Apollo and music from Caravaggio by Simon Fisher-Turner.

episodesByNumber.title: #87:  - Crammed Discs
episodesByNumber.tease: The Belgian label Crammed Discs started in 1981 as an extension of Aksak Maboul (Marc Hollander's & Vincent Kenis' band): combining & recycling all kind of musical styles -from electronic to classical- incorporating fake jazz, cultural collisions involving African & Balkan music, minimalism, and inviting musicians from various horizons to collaborate.

episodesByNumber.title: #88:  - Mikel Rouse Broken Consort
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, the Mikel Rouse Broken Consort performs music from A Lincoln Portrait, and other works in progress, live in the studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #89: Nuevo Flamenco
episodesByNumber.tease: A program of music featuring Pepe Habichuela (A Maneli), David Allen (Carmen: Fandangos In Space), Gino D'Auri (Passion Play), Ben Tavera King (Border Crossings), Larry Coryell (European Impressions), Ancient Future (Quiet Fire), and Luis Paniagua (De Magico Acuerdo).

episodesByNumber.title: #90: New Music from Southeastern Europe
episodesByNumber.tease: A collection of intricate music coming from the exotic countries in Southeastern Europe.

episodesByNumber.title: #91: New Sounds Live from Merkin Concert Hall
episodesByNumber.tease: Eugene Friesen, Glen Velez and Paul Sullivan on cello, percussion and piano perform live in Merkin Concert Hall.

episodesByNumber.title: #93: New Music for Dance
episodesByNumber.tease: The court dances of Medival France come to life in the music of Arbeau's Orchesographie, Paul Dresher (Nightsongs/Channel Passing), David Van Tieghem (Safety in Numbers), Peter Gordon/The Love of Life Orchestra (Secret Pastures), Yas-Kaz (Jomonsho), Robert Lloyd (Feral), Billy Larkin and Chris Dahlgren (ekimi), and Bill Obrecht ("Valentine").

episodesByNumber.title: #94: The Feeling of Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from Keith Jarrett (Book of Ways), String Trio of NY (Natural Balance), Paul Horn (China), Zakir Hussain (Making Music), Frank Zappa (Sleepdirt), Anthony Phillips (Private Parts & Pieces Vol.

episodesByNumber.title: #95:   - The Portable Composer
episodesByNumber.tease: Electronic music computers and processing gear have advanced to the point tha live performances are happening more frequently.

episodesByNumber.title: #96:   - New Music from Ireland
episodesByNumber.tease: There's more to contemporary Irish music than jigs and reels.

episodesByNumber.title: #97:   - Live from Merkin Concert Hall
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds concerts held at New York's Merkin Hall.

episodesByNumber.title: #98:   - Sacred Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Years before Eastern European composers like Henryk Gorecki and Arvo Pärt ascended the Billboard charts with their sublime, "mystical minimalist" compositions, John Schaefer was unearthing examples of this spiritual style.

episodesByNumber.title: #99:   - New Music from Italy
episodesByNumber.tease: Frank Zappa plays Francesco Zappa, and it's no joke.

episodesByNumber.title: #100:   - Phil and Will
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds listen to music from Philip Aaberg and William Ackerman.

episodesByNumber.title: #101:  - Beyond Graceland
episodesByNumber.tease: Paul Simon's hit album "Graceland" introduced the music of South Africa, especially the vocal group Ladysmith Black Mambazo, to a mainstream America audience.

episodesByNumber.title: #102: Basically Bach-
episodesByNumber.tease: A program of Bach's music, interpreted by various new music artists-featuring Bach works played on marimba and violin (by Marimolin), on guitar and fiddle (Darol Anger & Mike Marshall), synthesizer (Wendy Carlos), jazz trio (Jacques Loussuer), and many others.

episodesByNumber.title: #103: Music From Central Asia-
episodesByNumber.tease: The music of Tibet, Kashmir and the Mevlevi dervishes appears side by side with Western works using Central Asian instruments.

episodesByNumber.title: #104: Some Folks Singing-
episodesByNumber.tease: Joan Baez teams with Peter (PDQ Bach) Schickele for a moving song based on a text by e.e.

episodesByNumber.title: #105: Live from Merkin Concert Hall-
episodesByNumber.tease: From Merkin Concert Hall, in New York City, One Alternative performs their original works for oboe and two classical guitars.

episodesByNumber.title: #107: World Music, Part 4-
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from around the world continues with the Penguin Cafe Ocrchestra ("Cutting Branches"), Glen Velez ("Sweet Season"), Tor Dietrichson ("Minarets"), Peter Gordon ("Kora Music"), Alex de Grassi ("Doubek"), Ancient Future ("Mountain Song"), R.

episodesByNumber.title: #109: Border Crossings-
episodesByNumber.tease: Ben Tavera King's album "Border Crossings" is freely mixed with jazz, flamenco, and Tex-Mex styles.

episodesByNumber.title: #110: New Music from Japan, Part 2-
episodesByNumber.tease: A program of Japanese works that range from quasi-traditional flute solos to electronic ensembles with a very Western sound.

episodesByNumber.title: #112: New Acoustic Music-
episodesByNumber.tease: The Turtle Island String Quartet's concert performance on last week's program was one of the best examples of a branch of new music known simple as "New Acoustic Music." It combines American bluegrass, jazz, and folk styles with elements of classical or ethnic music.

episodesByNumber.title: #113: A Privet Reel-
episodesByNumber.tease: A program culled from some of the live performances recorded over the years in the New Sounds studios.

episodesByNumber.title: #114: New Music for Bass-
episodesByNumber.tease: Often thought of as simply a supporting instrument, the bass (in both acoustic and electric versions) is a versatile tool in the right hands.

episodesByNumber.title: #115: Meredith Monk-
episodesByNumber.tease: One of today's most complete artists, Monk is a composer, performer, film maker, choreographer, and most importantly, the developer of a series of unusual vocal techniques that form the basis for her work.

episodesByNumber.title: #116: Lounge Lizards-
episodesByNumber.tease: The Lounge Lizards, from New York and Jamaaladeen Tacuma, a Philadelphia  bassist, create music that's often thought of as a weird hybrid form of jazz.

episodesByNumber.title: #117: New Music from Hungary-
episodesByNumber.tease: Hungary is sometimes thought to be the least artistically confined country in the Eastern bloc.

episodesByNumber.title: #118: Live from Merkin Concert Hall-
episodesByNumber.tease: Another program of live music from the stage of Merkin Hall in New York.

episodesByNumber.title: #119: New Music with Cello-
episodesByNumber.tease: A collection of works for ensembles that include at least one cello (and, in one case, twelve of them); both orchestral cellos and more experimental electric cellos will be featured.

episodesByNumber.title: #120: Oregon-
episodesByNumber.tease: Guitarist Ralph Towner, bassist Glen Moore, and reed player Paul McCandless take us through some of the recordings by one of America's primiere new music groups, Oregon.

episodesByNumber.title: #121: Akhnaten-

episodesByNumber.tease: It's another in the Theme & Variations series on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #426: With Henry Butler, In-Studio
episodesByNumber.tease: Pianist and singer Henry Butler is one of the leading lights of the New Orleans music scene, known for his raw-edge blues, soulful R & B, and instrumental jazz sounds. He plays in-studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #427: Vaults: Harry Partch Instruments
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, it's an hour of rareties From the Vaults with the Harry Partch instruments.

episodesByNumber.title: #429: Vaults: Najma Akhtar
episodesByNumber.tease: For this 1990 New Sounds from the Vaults, Najma Akhtar, the UK-based singer, presents selections from her then brand-new CD, Qareeb.

episodesByNumber.title: #444: Program #444
episodesByNumber.tease: Brazilian singer-songwriter Caetano Veloso first visited the WNYC studio back in 1990 on New Sounds, just after Nonesuch had released his album, “Estrangeiro.”  In this “From the Vaults” show, subtitled “Beyond the Bossa Nova,” Veloso talks about how everyone in Brazil has a guitar (and claims that many may play better than he does.) He introduces his songs and performs live, including a special tribute to David Byrne with an arrangement of Byrne's tune, “Nothing But Flowers.”  Also, there’s more Brazilian music, mostly by guitarists, including works from Egberto Gismonti, Oscar Castro-Neves, and Toninho Hora with Pat Metheny.

episodesByNumber.title: #449: From the Vaults: La Monte Young
#459: Vaults: Bill Ruyle
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, we unearth a 1990 vaults show with percussionist/composer Bill Ruyle, featuring new music for dance and much more, during this week of banging and crashing with favorite percussionists.

episodesByNumber.title: #487: Vaults: A Koto Armada
episodesByNumber.tease: From a live performance recorded in the WNYC studios in 1990, the Kazue Sawai Koto Ensemble - a veritable koto armada - performs a new work, "Homura" by Tadao Sawai.

episodesByNumber.title: #533: Vaults: Glenn Branca
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds from the Vaults show, we visit with the fearless leader of numerous guitar armies, composer Glenn Branca.

episodesByNumber.title: #547: Vaults: Hijaz Mustapha
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, Hijaz Mustapha, the founder of the 3 Mustaphas 3, visited the WNYC studios for this 1990 program, (our last From the Vaults program in the series.)   The witty ringleader of the London-based world music band talks in an indeterminate accent about his music and the traditions around the world that he’s stolen from.

episodesByNumber.title: #610 - With Kronos Quartet's David Harrington, Vaults:
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear an hour of music by the Kronos Quartet, presented by founding violinist David Harrington, recorded during a studio visit back in 1991.

episodesByNumber.title: #626: Vaults: Korean Treasures
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from Korea is the focus of this 1991 New Sounds program From the Vaults.

episodesByNumber.title: #639: Foday Musa Suso
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds from the Vaults, we’ve unearthed a 1991 program with the Gambian-born, Mandingo griot Foday Musa Suso.

episodesByNumber.title: #652: With The Hilliard Ensemble, From the Vaults,
episodesByNumber.tease: In this show from Spring of 1991, vocal quartet The Hilliard Ensemble performs both contemporary and medieval works, in-studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #665: With John Fahey, In-Studio
episodesByNumber.tease: The legendary guitarist, composer, and founder of Takoma Records, John Fahey (1939-2001), visited the studio for this May 9, 1991 episode of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #686: From the Vaults: Ali Akbar Khan
episodesByNumber.tease: The late great classical Indian sarod master Ali Akbar Khan came to the U.S.A.

episodesByNumber.title: #691: From the Vaults: Annabouboula
episodesByNumber.tease: For this trip down memory lane, New Sounds explores the sounds of "Greek blues," or rebetiko, and the American music it inspired, with the NY band Annabouboula.

episodesByNumber.title: #741: Vaults: Robert Fripp
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, dig into a "Vaults" show with Robert Fripp from 1991, upon the release of a 4-CD King Crimson boxed set.

episodesByNumber.title: #747: Vaults: Mickey Hart
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds From the Vaults, we begin a 5-part series called "primarily percussion," - it's a week of banging and crashing with some favorite percussionists.

episodesByNumber.title: #797: Vaults: Live Horns and Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: From a New Sounds Live concert at Town Hall first broadcast in 1992, hear music from Bach to rock, with stops at jazz, surf music in between, as well as some serious funk horn-playing on this From the Vaults edition of the show.

episodesByNumber.title: #825: Vaults: Trilok Gurtu
episodesByNumber.tease: Our New Sounds From the Vaults series wraps up tonight, after our week of banging and crashing with favorite percussionists.

episodesByNumber.title: #867: From the Vaults: David Darling
episodesByNumber.tease: The American cellist/composer David Darling presents music from his recordings for the ECM record label and plays live in the WNYC studio for this 1992 From the Vaults show.

episodesByNumber.title: #877: Vaults: New Sounds in Frankfurt
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to performances from the Women of the Calabash, a trio of women who drum, dance and sing, on this New Sounds program from the vaults.

episodesByNumber.title: #879: Vaults: Aashish Khan
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds From the Vaults, we go back to 1992 for a live performance by sarod virtuoso Aashish Khan.

episodesByNumber.title: #882: From the Vaults: Carl Stone
episodesByNumber.tease: Carl Stone, the pioneering composer in the fields of electroacoustic and computer music, visits the studio for this New Sounds From the Vaults.

episodesByNumber.title: #885: Vaults: Samite of Uganda
episodesByNumber.tease: Spend another night in the vaults on this New Sounds, with a program from November of 1992, featuring Samite of Uganda.

episodesByNumber.title: #928: Vaults: Zap Mama
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, we dig up another vaults show, featuring a playful live a capella performance by the women of the “Afropean” group Zap Mama from 1993.

episodesByNumber.title: #929: From the Vaults: Francis Bebey
episodesByNumber.tease: In this 1993 show from the archives, Cameroonian guitarist, novelist, singer, flutist, percussionist, and musicologist Francis Bebey performs in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #935: Vaults: Glass & Moran
episodesByNumber.tease: Bach, Handel and Scarlatti walk into a bar - and they have a drinkdown smackup fight about whose music rocks harder...or well - something like that.

episodesByNumber.title: #953: Variations on Witchi-Tai-To
episodesByNumber.tease: It's another one in the Theme and Variations series, where we listen to arrangements of a certain piece. This show revolves around a traditional religious peyote chant, "Witchi Tai To."

episodesByNumber.title: #959: Vaults: With Sheila Chandra
episodesByNumber.tease: The Anglo-Indian singer Sheila Chandra began as a popular TV star with a hit song, but developed an interest in early music, world music, and the role of women in traditional music.

episodesByNumber.title: #981: Vaults: Two-fer
episodesByNumber.tease: Two bandleaders joined John Schaefer for this December 1993 From the Vaults show: John Lurie and Bachir Attar.

episodesByNumber.title: #985: Vaults: Indonesian Gamelan
episodesByNumber.tease: Up on this New Sounds From the Vaults is live music performed by The Royal Court Gamelan of Solo, Indonesia.

episodesByNumber.title: #997: With Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan and Party, In-Studio
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear ecstatic Sufi prayer music by the great Qawwali singer from Pakistan, Nusrat Fateh Ali Kahn (1948-1997), as performed live, in-studio from 1993.

episodesByNumber.title: #999: From the Vaults: Stewart Copeland
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds From the Vaults, listen to a 1993 program with drummer and composer Stewart Copeland.

episodesByNumber.title: #1009: Vaults: New Sounds in Norway
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds show From the Vaults, we uncork a show from 1994.

episodesByNumber.title: #1018: Vaults: Max Roach & Uptown String Quartet
episodesByNumber.tease: Legendary drummer Max Roach plays his 4-part inventions for drum kit, and Maxine Roach with the Uptown String Quartet play their infectious blend of jazz, funk and new music.

episodesByNumber.title: #1042: Vaults: Leo Kottke
episodesByNumber.tease: Guitarist Leo Kottke sat in with host John Schaefer for this April 1994 From the Vaults show.

episodesByNumber.title: #1044: John Cage: City Circus, Program II
#1047: John Cage: City Circus, Program III
#1049: John Cage: City Circus, Program IV
#1052: John Cage: City Circus, Program V
#1053: John Cage: City Circus, Program VI
#1054: John Cage: City Circus, Program VII
#1055: John Cage: City Circus, Program VIII
#1056: John Cage: City Circus, Program IX
#1057: John Cage: City Circus, Program X
#1058: John Cage: City Circus, Program XI
#1059: John Cage: City Circus, Program XII
#1067: Vaults: New Orleans in Brooklyn
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear shout, party and stomp sets from both the Rebirth Brass Band and the Wild Magnolias recorded live back at the 1994 World Music Festival held at the BAM Opera House.

episodesByNumber.title: #1084: Program #1084
episodesByNumber.tease: Arguably the most popular song in our Theme and Variations series has gone by several names, "Wimoweh," or the doo-wop hit, "The Lion Sleeps Tonight." Here it is from the 2003 reboot.

episodesByNumber.title: #1101: From the Vaults: Black Umfolosi
episodesByNumber.tease: Black Umfolosi, the Zimbabwean vocal ensemble (and dance troupe), performs traditional and original works from Zimbabwe in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #1108: From the Vaults: Officium Live
episodesByNumber.tease: The renowned Hilliard Ensemble and saxophonist Jan Garbarek had a worldwide hit with their recording of medieval works called “Officium.” Tonight on this From the Vaults show from 1994, they introduce excerpts from the CD and perform some additional works in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #1169: Vaults: Gyuto Monks of Tibet
episodesByNumber.tease: The Gyuto Monks of Tibet together with their "spokesperson," composer Philip Glass, visit the WNYC studio for this 1995 New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #1170: From the Vaults: Huun-Huur-Tu
episodesByNumber.tease: In this 1995 New Sounds From the Vaults, the Tuvan throat singers known as Huun-Huur-Tu, perform in-studio. Plus, music by Sainko, and the slightly menacing sounds of Yat-Kha.

episodesByNumber.title: #1187: From the Vaults: Joseph Spence Tribute
episodesByNumber.tease: It's a birthday tribute to Joseph Spence for this New Sounds From the Vaults.

episodesByNumber.title: #1221: From the Vaults: World of Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, we raid the vaults for some new music for kantele, tanbur, hardingfele, hackbrett, mandolin, and other exotic strings.

episodesByNumber.title: #1277: From the Vaults: Hans Otte
episodesByNumber.tease: For this 1996 show From the Vaults, German composer Hans Otte plays excerpts from his best-known work, "The Book of Sounds," on the WNYC piano, and discusses his Zen-like approach to music.

episodesByNumber.title: #1293: From the Vaults - For the Kids
episodesByNumber.tease: This "From the Vaults" show is from the New Sounds Live concert series, which originally aired on June 20, 1996, and featured live performances recorded from the stage of the BAM Opera House.

episodesByNumber.title: #1311: From the Vaults: the Duduk
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds from the Vaults presentation on New Sounds, we transport you back to 1996 for a show with music for the Armenian oboe-like instrument called the duduk.

episodesByNumber.title: #1364: From the Vaults: Paolo Braganca
episodesByNumber.tease: For this 1997 From the Vaults edition of New Sounds, Paolo Braganca, the Portuguese fado singer and composer visits the studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #1375: From the Vaults: Lou Harrison
episodesByNumber.tease: The late Lou Harrison, one of America's most enduring and original composers, discusses his long career and presents his most recent works, from a 1997 show.

episodesByNumber.title: #1410: Vaults: More New Sounds Live
episodesByNumber.tease: This June 1997 New Sounds From the Vaults show is taken from three different performances from the New Sounds Live concert series.

episodesByNumber.title: #1430: From the Vaults: Dino Saluzzi
episodesByNumber.tease: In another installment of our From the Vaults series, the gifted Argentine bandoneon player and composer Dino Saluzzi presents music from the release "Cite de la musique" and performs live with guitar accompaniment in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #1440: From the Vaults: the "Gogs"
episodesByNumber.tease: Since 1995, the Gogmagogs have made it their business to combine dynamic movement with virtuosic string playing in a theatre setting.

episodesByNumber.title: #1474: The Spirit of Rumi, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: We'll listen to texts by the great 13th century poet and mystic Jalal ad-Din Rumi, poetry that is nearly music, as incorporated into ritual music of the Mawlawiyah order of the Whirling Dervishes, a sect founded by Rumi.

episodesByNumber.title: #1475: The Spirit of Rumi, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of the New Sounds, we spotlight the Polish singer and multi-instrumentalist Mieczyslaw Litwinksi.

episodesByNumber.title: #1557: Hiroshima Remembered
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music to mark the 70th anniversary of the bombing of Hiroshima, including a work by Raphael Mostel written for the lantern-floating ceremony on the Ota River in Hiroshima,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #1579: Einojuhani Rautavaara, In Memorium
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by the Finnish composer Einojuhani Rautavaara, who died on July 27, 2016, including his concerto for orchestra and birds on tape, "Cantus Arcticus," "Angel of Light,"  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #1587: Mostly Electronic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Mostly electronic music is on the menu for this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #1594: From the Vaults: World Mysticism
episodesByNumber.tease: For this 1999 New Sounds from the Vaults, hear mystic fiddle music from Baluchistan along with Hassan Hakmoun, who plays Gnawa trance music from Morocco.

episodesByNumber.title: #1595: Program #1595
episodesByNumber.tease: Works for electric guitar by Fripp & Eno, Glenn Branca, Bill Frisell, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #1626: From the Vaults: Yuri Yunakov
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear live music in the studio by Bulgarian sax player, composer and band leader Yuri Yunakov on this 1999 From the Vaults program.

episodesByNumber.title: #1649: From the Vaults: Taraf de Haidouks
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds show From the Vaults from 1999, features the renowned Gypsy band Taraf de Haidouks, performing live in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #1657: Vaults:  Lux Vivens
episodesByNumber.tease: As part of a week of New Sounds Live performances from the WNYC Archives, listen to Jocelyn Montgomery (Miranda Sex Garden) singing the music of the abbess Hildegard von Bingen, recorded live at the World Financial Center's Wintergarden.

episodesByNumber.title: #1691: Vaults: Oregon live
episodesByNumber.tease: Pianist Christopher O’Riley debuts a WNYC-commissioned work by Ralph Towner; and Towner’s band Oregon star in this edition of New Sounds from the vaults, recorded live at Miller Theater from a 1999 performance.

episodesByNumber.title: #1765: Legong: Silent Film Score
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, the Clubfoot Orchestra and Gamelan Sekar Jaya play Richard Marriott's new score to the "rediscovered" silent film Legong: Dance of the Virgins.

episodesByNumber.title: #1829: Program #1829
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from the 2000 edition of the annual Fez Festival of World Sacred Music is featured on tonight's New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #1830: Program #1830
episodesByNumber.tease: The Fez Festival of World Sacred Music takes place each June in the imperial city of Morroco, and brings together many of the world's sacred music traditions, from Sufi, Islamic, medieval Christian and Sephardic expressions to African-American gospel.

episodesByNumber.title: #1831: Program #1831
episodesByNumber.tease: Dramatically set in the largest extant medieval city in the world, the Fez Festival of World Sacred Music is one of the world's most unique and enterprising musical events.

episodesByNumber.title: #1832: Program #1832
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds' week-long retrospective of the Fez Festival of World Sacred Music continues with a program recorded at the First-Century ruins of Volubilis in the Moroccan plains.

episodesByNumber.title: #1833: Program #1833
episodesByNumber.tease: Continuing with New Sounds's week-long retrospective of the annual Fez Festival of World Sacred Music in Morocco, we hear live performances from the festival's 2000 edition.

episodesByNumber.title: #1834: Program #1834
episodesByNumber.tease: From the 2000 edition of the Fez Festival of World Sacred Music, New Sounds presents a concert recording of Moroccan-born Haim Louk (pictured), a rabbi, cantor and world-recognized singer who is especially known for taking Sephardi chants and the old Andalusian music sung in both Hebrew and Arabic.

episodesByNumber.title: #1858: Program #1858
episodesByNumber.tease: A tribute to Michael Hedges.

episodesByNumber.title: #1859: Program #1859
episodesByNumber.tease: The New Sounds Live tribute to Michael Hedges continues.

episodesByNumber.title: #1934: Program #1934
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from the circle of near-contemporaries and colleagues from the ex-Soviet lands, often referred to as "mystical minimalists," is the topic of this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #1961: Program #1961
episodesByNumber.tease: More music from the 2001 Fez Festival of World Sacred Music, recorded live on location in Fez, Morocco is presented tonight on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #1986: Program #1986
episodesByNumber.tease: A few years ago, WNYC Radio commissioned and premiered Richard Einhorn’s “Carnival of Miracles”.

episodesByNumber.title: #2035: Program #2035
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works by Julia Wolfe for Ensemble Sospeso and the Talujon Percussion Quartet, performed at Miller Theatre.

episodesByNumber.title: #2079: Program #2079
episodesByNumber.tease: New Music from Spain highlights this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2083: Program #2083
episodesByNumber.tease: Steve Reich's "Different Trains" (1988) has often been regarded as the composer's masterpiece.

episodesByNumber.title: #2091: Guitar Tribute: Jerry Garcia
episodesByNumber.tease: Merkin Concert Hall's portion of the 2002 New Sounds Live/New York Guitar Festival began with a sold-out tribute to two Rock guitar legends: Jerry Garcia and George Harrison.

episodesByNumber.title: #2092: Guitar Tribute: John Fahey
episodesByNumber.tease: From the 92nd Street Y's portion of the 2002 New Sounds Live/New York Guitar Festival, Leo Kottke headlines a tribute to John Fahey (1939-2001), one of acoustic music's influential innovators and eccentrics.

episodesByNumber.title: #2093: Guitar Tribute: George Harrison
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds continues its revisiting of the 2002 New York Guitar Festival with a tribute to the late George Harrison, recorded live at Merkin Hall.

episodesByNumber.title: #2094: Bach, Brazil, and Beyond
episodesByNumber.tease: Guitarist Andy Summers, a veteran of '80s supergroup the Police, and Brazilian acoustic master Victor Biglione have been performing as a duo for more than five years.

episodesByNumber.title: #2095: Guitar Fesitval: World Blues
episodesByNumber.tease: Uptown and Downtown, the New Sounds Live/New York Guitar Festival 2002 covered plenty of fertile ground, musical and otherwise.

episodesByNumber.title: #2142: All Aboard
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music for mass transit on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2144: Children's Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s an hour of music not necessarily for children’s listening, but music written for their voices on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2145: Unusual Opera And More
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds hear excerpts from Robert Ashley's experimental opera, Celestial Excursions, which had its U.S.

episodesByNumber.title: #2146: Sonic Splice Essays
episodesByNumber.tease: DJ Spooky's release “Optometry” is a vast sonic essay that merges DJ culture seamlessly with jazz, ambient, and other styles.

episodesByNumber.title: #2148: Program #2148
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again.

episodesByNumber.title: #2149: Steady State Music
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, hear "steady state music." No, it's not related to the obscure astronomical theory of galaxies, but rather music that displays a sense of suspension, stillness, with textures that evolve and are always in the process of a slow change.

episodesByNumber.title: #2150: Just Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: For the past two decades, the guitarist John Schneider has performed almost exclusively on the well-tempered guitar which uses different patterns of fretting according to the key or tuning system required.

episodesByNumber.title: #2151: Near Eastern Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, we sample songs of the Near East, from those of the early Christians to the Crusades to modern times.

episodesByNumber.title: #2152: Electric Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: On this episode of New Sounds, hear electric violin music by Daniel Bernard Roumain.

episodesByNumber.title: #2153: Music Toys
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer, inventor, and professor at the MIT Media Lab, Tod Machover has spent much of the last three years in his Media Lab studio developing a set of computerized instruments called Music Toys (including Music Shapers and Beatbugs) that aim to engage children with music - but without the need for all those darned piano lessons.

episodesByNumber.title: #2154: Music for Zithers
episodesByNumber.tease: The term zither is also used generically for various instruments, including the dulcimer, the psaltery, and several Asian instruments.

episodesByNumber.title: #2155: Koto and Shakuhachi
episodesByNumber.tease: Classical music of Japan is performed live in the WNYC studio on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2158: Never Failed Me Yet
episodesByNumber.tease: Gavin Bryars' "Jesus' Blood Never Failed Me Yet," is a late minimalist piece for orchestra and tape that has had an almost legendary effect on its audiences.

episodesByNumber.title: #2159: New British Music
episodesByNumber.tease: The exciting young British composer and co-founder of the rock group The Divine Comedy, Joby Talbot joins John Schaefer on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2160: Program #2160
episodesByNumber.tease:
John Schaefer once again picks through the bucketloads of CDs that have flooded his office this Spring to find a sampling of new releases worthy of showcasing in tonight's program
