episodesByNumber.title: #2161: Global Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Unusual vocal works from far-flung locations take center stage on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2162: Experimental Instruments
episodesByNumber.tease: Experimental Musical Instruments is an organization devoted to interesting and unusual musical instruments of all sorts.

episodesByNumber.title: #2163: Americana, Old & New
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, take a fresh look at traditional American music with Jorma Kaukonen and Joel Harrison, who reinterpret songs by the Rev.

episodesByNumber.title: #2164: Inspired by India & Indonesia
episodesByNumber.tease: The history of Western fascination in the traditions of the far East has long been laced with overtones of colonialism and condescension.

episodesByNumber.title: #2166: New Music from Estonia
episodesByNumber.tease: In what seems like an ever-growing number of composers from the tiny Baltic country of Estonia to win a following in the West, a few composers stand out from the pack.

episodesByNumber.title: #2167: Remixes & Arrangements
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds presents a program of unusual arrangements of pre-existing works.

episodesByNumber.title: #2168: Inspired by Bach
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds explores contemporary works inspired by the string music of J.S.

episodesByNumber.title: #2169: Indian Dance Music Unplugged
episodesByNumber.tease: Take Indian classical music, add some sampled dance beats, overlay the Bollywood string section, and you get a feel for Karsh Kale's new CD - "Liberation".

episodesByNumber.title: #2170: Electric & Acoustic Mixed
episodesByNumber.tease: There's a wide variety of works for mixed electric and acoustic ensembles on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2171: Program #2171
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again and the midpoint of the year: the recordings flooding into John Schaefer's inbox haven't let up.

episodesByNumber.title: #2173: Near Eastern Sounds
episodesByNumber.tease: Western fascination with Asia has come in many forms, and more often than not it is accompanied by a whiff of colonialism or imperialism.

episodesByNumber.title: #2174: Silk Road Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from the Silk Road, the ancient Chinese trade route, is featured on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2175: New Music From Brazil
episodesByNumber.tease: It often seems that only the most stereotypical forms of Brazilian music ever come to the attention of the public: the quiet, cool sounds of bossa nova and its many offshoots.

episodesByNumber.title: #2176: Swiss Violinist Paul Giger
episodesByNumber.tease: Swiss violinist Paul Giger's ECM disc "O Ignis" finds him in the distinguished company of the Estonian Philharmonic Chamber Choir under Tõnu Kaljuste, performing arrangements of pieces by Hildegarde von Bingen and the monks of St.

episodesByNumber.title: #2177: Classics Declassified
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, spend an hour sorting through the twisted wreckage of classical music after various new music bands have played it.

episodesByNumber.title: #2178: World Percussion
episodesByNumber.tease: Music for world percussion takes center stage on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2179: Music with Voices on Tape
episodesByNumber.tease: Steve Reich's seminal tape work "It's Gonna Rain" came about largely by accident.

episodesByNumber.title: #2180: Trio Mediæval Live
episodesByNumber.tease: Trio Mediæval is a Norwegian ensemble, three women who, as you might guess from the name, sing music from the 13th and 14th centuries.

episodesByNumber.title: #2181: Streetwalker And More
episodesByNumber.tease: To celebrate its 15th anniversary, Bang on a Can mounted a weekend of concerts at Symphony Space last summer.

episodesByNumber.title: #2182: Guitar Harvest
episodesByNumber.tease: The New York Guitar Festival goes to great lengths to examine the multiple personalities of the guitar, through live concerts (broadcast in recent years as part of WNYC's New Sounds Live), workshops, and educational outreach.

episodesByNumber.title: #2183: Diverse Things
episodesByNumber.tease: British composer Joby Talbot studied with Simon Bainbridge and Robert Saxton before he joined Neil Hannon in The Divine Comedy in 1993.

episodesByNumber.title: #2184: Balkan-Klezmer Connections
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, hear music from a Southeast European-style supergroup called the Balkan playboys, along with a Klezmer record from Yale Strom and his band Hot Pastrami.

episodesByNumber.title: #2186: Chamber Rock
episodesByNumber.tease: The term "chamber rock" may seem like an oxymoron, but in fact it represents an entire strain of the contemporary music scene.

episodesByNumber.title: #2187: New Choral Music
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, host John Schaefer focuses on unusual choral works by a wide-ranging assortment of international composers.

episodesByNumber.title: #2188: David Sylvian's Blemish
episodesByNumber.tease: David Sylvian’s CD, “Blemish” was recorded at his home studio and is a raw minimal work of shimmering bleakness.

episodesByNumber.title: #2189: A Private Reel
episodesByNumber.tease: This installment of New Sounds is the latest in the ongoing series called “A Private Reel,” where we dig into some of the live recordings made here in our WNYC studios.

episodesByNumber.title: #2190: New Orchestral Music
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to some new music involving orchestra, including works by the jazz/new music ensemble Oregon and rock singer Jon Lord (Deep Purple).

episodesByNumber.title: #2191: Hot Tin Hat
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the San Francisco-based Tin Hat Trio, and their blend of tango, bluegrass, contemporary classical, and Eastern European folk traditions on this installment of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2192: Unusual Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s an hour of unusual songs on this episode of New Sounds, including works from the Czech vocalist/violinist Iva Bittova.

episodesByNumber.title: #2193: The New Surf Guitar
episodesByNumber.tease: Wipeout! The unique sound of "surf" guitar was based on the combination of big band beat and Middle Eastern melodies, played at a manic gallop and drenched with lashings of reverb.

episodesByNumber.title: #2195: Phoning It In
episodesByNumber.tease: From dial tones to busy signals, phone messages and disconnects, as well as the conversations in between, listen to a number of works about the telephone, or even with the telephone as the instrument on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2196: New Music from Mexico
episodesByNumber.tease: The unpredictable and adventurous Mexican band Café Tacuba takes top billing on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2197: Program #2197
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2198: African Cross-cultural Music
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s African music from Russia, Italy, England, and, of course, Africa on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2199: Eastern European Roots
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music by the Klezmatics on this installment of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2200: Worldbeat Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Algeria-born and San Francisco-based DJ Cheb I Sabbah’s musical reinventions have included Sufi devotionals, ragas, and even Indian film music layered into trancey warped swirls of drones fused with innovative percussion patterns.

episodesByNumber.title: #2203: Unusual Soundtracks
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s Isadora Duncan Award-winning music tonight on New Sounds - a work by San Francisco based composer, performer and bandleader Beth Custer, called “What the Body Knows”, from her "Maverick Strain" score.

episodesByNumber.title: #2204: Indian Light Classical
episodesByNumber.tease: An Indian music sampler of folk-based and "light classical" fare is served up on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2205: Medieval/Modern Music Connections
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds explores the connections between medieval and modern music with music from the British Isles and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #2207: Eurofolk
episodesByNumber.tease: We're serving up a pretty kettle of goulash on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2208: Musical Machines
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s desert music of a sort on this New Sounds program by California-based composer (and painter) Carolyn Yarnell.

episodesByNumber.title: #2209: A Jazz/Medieval Mass
episodesByNumber.tease: (ONLINE ONLY) Hear a reworking of a medieval mass by the Orlando Consort and the modern jazz quartet Perfect Houseplants, along with music from Jan Garbarek  &  the Hilliard Ensemble.

episodesByNumber.title: #2210: Hearing Solar Winds Reissued
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, David Hykes joins John Schaefer in the studio to celebrate the CD reissue of the groundbreaking work "Hearing Solar Winds".

episodesByNumber.title: #2211: New Sounds for Halloween
episodesByNumber.tease: Spooky stuff is what’s in store on this New Sounds program for Halloween, with an hour of musical ghost stories, portraits of vampires, and spiritual encounters.

episodesByNumber.title: #2212: New, Unusual Pop Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Coming up on this edition of the show, we're serving up pop songs – New Sounds-style.

episodesByNumber.title: #2215: Unusual Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to an hour of quirky or nocturnal songs on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2216: Piano Works
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, hear the prepared piano - an instrument defined entirely by muting by the attachment of certain objects to the strings of the piano, nuts, bolts, felt, rubber - with selections from John Cage’s Sonatas and Interludes for Prepared Piano.

episodesByNumber.title: #2217: Program #2217
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some outrageous works for saxophone on this New Sounds program, including the Lounge Lizards’ “Bob the Bob” which creeps up on you backwards and then runs into some serious rhythms.

episodesByNumber.title: #2218: New Music from the Netherlands
episodesByNumber.tease: Dutch composer Louis Andriessen is fond of hard instrumental edges and combinations of rhythmic styles – Stravinsky’s driving vigor and Minimalism’s lulling repetitions are often found in his music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2219: Electroacoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Experience the shimmering crystal textures of rolling soundscape from the “recovering rock drummer” and Alaska-based composer John Luther Adams.

episodesByNumber.title: #2220: Virtual Reality Inventions
episodesByNumber.tease: The man who created "virtual reality," composer, inventor, computer scientist, visual artist, and author Jaron Lanier, returns to New York with new recordings for conventional and invented instruments on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2221: Intercontinentals
episodesByNumber.tease: Bill Frisell is John Schaefer’s guest in the studio on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2223: The "California School"
episodesByNumber.tease: Was there really a California school of new music in the late 70s and early 80s? We'll hear works by John Adams, Ingram Marshall, Peter Garland, Chas Smith, Paul Dresher, and other composers whose music suggests that the question might not have a simple answer.

episodesByNumber.title: #2224: Bang on a Tank
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear melodious beatings on this New Sounds program, as featured in different works by Lou Harrison, Steve Reich, and Aaron J.

episodesByNumber.title: #2225: C'Mon Baby, Light My Oil Lamp
episodesByNumber.tease: John Tavener’s “The Bridegroom” is an ecstatic, mystical piece imbued with slow-moving harmonies and radiant vocal textures.

episodesByNumber.title: #2226: Jazz-Funk Rendezvous
episodesByNumber.tease: Written for and premiered by the Bang On A Can All-Stars, Steve Martland’s “Horses Of Instruction” is a fierce and frantic piece for a 11-piece varied band, anchored by a drummer.

episodesByNumber.title: #2227: Lute and Lucas
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, John Schaefer welcomes Dutch ten-string Renaissance lute player Josef van Wissem, along with guitarist Gary Lucas, the NYC-based musician well known from his days with Captain Beefheart and the Magic Band.

episodesByNumber.title: #2228: For the Birds
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works that incorporate taped natural sounds on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2229: From Russia With Love
episodesByNumber.tease: The groundbreaking Dmitri Pokrovsky Ensemble, continuing the work of the late musicologist/singer Dmitri Pokrovsky(1944-1996), performs live in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #2230: New Music for Hanukkah
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music for Hanukkah, featuring the Klezmatics, the Abayudaya project of Jewish music from Uganda, music by accordionist Ted Reichman, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #2231: In Between Beatings
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the premiere performance of Alaska-based John Luther Adams’ new piece called "The Mathematics of Resonant Bodies," for solo percussion and computer-processed sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2235: Sardinian Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Small-group polyphonic singing in Sardinia, rooted in the pastoral world of the Italian island, is a rich tradition dating back thousands of years.

episodesByNumber.title: #2236: Ambient Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Trying to explain “ambient music” might be pretty tricky, but here goes: “ambient” can suggest music of little or no rhythm, with background sounds and effects as foreground music, as in the spacey and beautiful works by Brian Eno.

episodesByNumber.title: #2237: The "M" Word
episodesByNumber.tease: Minimalism just can't seem to sever its connection to rock and jazz, and on this edition of New Sounds, we'll hear the influence of minimalism as felt in the jazz world.

episodesByNumber.title: #2238: Music, Murder, Infamy
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, the criminal mind is put on the music stand.

episodesByNumber.title: #2239: What's Up Tiger Lillies?
episodesByNumber.tease: The Tiger Lillies, a UK-based “freak-cabaret trio”, sometimes perform in full clown make-up or with members dressed as pigs.

episodesByNumber.title: #2240: Festival in the Desert
episodesByNumber.tease: Every year in Mali just outside of Timbuktu, the annual Festival in the Desert is held, celebrating the music and culture of the nomadic Tuareg people of the Sahara.

episodesByNumber.title: #2241: Celestial Clanging
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series at the World Financial Center recorded this past December, hear the world premiere of Aaron Jay Kernis' Concerto for Toy Piano and Chamber Orchestra, a WNYC commission.

episodesByNumber.title: #2243: 1000 Years of Popular Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Modern troubadour and Fairport Convention founding member Richard Thompson performs a bellyful of unusual songs, both widely known mega-pop-hits and obscure work-songs on his latest release, "1000 Years of Popular Music." His choices run the gamut from old English rounds, to a snippet from a Gilbert and Sullivan musical, to Lennon-McCartney, Prince, and er- Brittany? Hear selections from Thompson's new live album on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2244: Music from Egypt
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear percussionist Mahmoud Fadl along with master drummers Mohammed "Kallo" Sobhi and Magdi Berbish, as well as music from the legendary Hasaballah Brass Band, the one and only brass band in Egypt.

episodesByNumber.title: #2245: Songs From Brazil &
episodesByNumber.tease: Sink into the rich voices and lush arrangements of this New Sounds program with music from Brazil, Portugal, and the Cape Verde Islands.

episodesByNumber.title: #2246: New Music for Cello
episodesByNumber.tease: New music for cello is the focus of this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2247: Serbian Soul and Hot Grooves
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, there's plenty of new music from the Balkans.

episodesByNumber.title: #2248: 4 Views of the Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: New music for piano is offered up on this edition of New Sounds, which features several “minimalist” pieces, including music by Dutch composer Simeon Ten Holt, whose music relies not only on repetition, but also an absence of time.

episodesByNumber.title: #2249: Zippo Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer Phil Kline visits the studio for this edition of New Sounds to talk about his timely new CD, "Zippo Songs: Airs of War and Lunacy", music set to “poems” inscribed on army-issue Zippo lighters by GIs in Vietnam.

episodesByNumber.title: #2250: New Sounds Live Highlights
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts, the east coast new music ensemble Alarm Will Sound plays a classic Steve Reich piece - Music For Mallet Instruments, Voices, And Organ.

episodesByNumber.title: #2251: Let It Slide
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts, hear music for slide guitar by four different artists, recorded live at Merkin Hall at the New York Guitar Festival in February of 2004.

episodesByNumber.title: #2252: What is an Ocarina?
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear flutes of all shapes and sizes on this installment of New Sounds, including recorders, pan pipes, and ocarinas.

episodesByNumber.title: #2253: But Is It Jazz?
episodesByNumber.tease: It’s music of a jazz sort on this New Sounds program featuring uncategorizable music by Australia’s trio The Necks.

episodesByNumber.title: #2255: Ragas and Sagas
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, hear a collaboration between Pakistanis and Norwegians from an exotic CD called Ragas and Sagas, featuring saxophonist Jan Garbarek’s improvising saxophone, along with voice, sarangi, and tabla.

episodesByNumber.title: #2256: Frisell Trio Scores
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts, hear new music for silent films by Bill Frisell and his trio, recorded this past January at the World Financial Center's Winter Garden.

episodesByNumber.title: #2257: Music for Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: Anton Batagov is a young Russian artist, both keyboard player and composer.

episodesByNumber.title: #2258: World Music from Mali To New Guinea
episodesByNumber.tease: One of Afghanistan's best-known female singers, Ustad Farida Mahwash, trained with classical masters, and now lives in exile in California.

episodesByNumber.title: #2259: Laurie Anderson & Ethel
episodesByNumber.tease: From New Sounds Live at Merkin Hall recorded in late February 2004, Laurie Anderson performs new works for voice, violin, and keyboard.

episodesByNumber.title: #2260: Double-Bass Upfront
episodesByNumber.tease: Whether it’s a jazz player standing isolated at the back of a stage, or a small army of players standing to one side of the orchestra, often too close to the brass section, double-bass players don’t often get the props they deserve for holding the line.

episodesByNumber.title: #2261: Microtonal Music
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds episode, Johnny Reinhard, the composer and director of the annual American Festival of Microtonal Music, presents live recordings from the most recent edition of the festival.

episodesByNumber.title: #2262: Early Music and the Folk Revival
episodesByNumber.tease: The English folk revival and medieval music scenes overlapped in the 1960s and 70s, resulting in a distinctive approach to early music that continues to this day.

episodesByNumber.title: #2263: Strange Arrangements
episodesByNumber.tease: This edition of New Sounds is given over to unusual arrangements of three "minimalist" classics.

episodesByNumber.title: #2264: A World of Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to highlights from the New Sounds Live/New York Guitar Festival's biannual Guitar Marathon at the 92nd Street Y.

episodesByNumber.title: #2265: Guitars, More Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, hear highlights from the New Sounds Live/New York Guitar Festival's biannual Guitar Marathon at the 92nd Street Y, Part 2 of 3.

episodesByNumber.title: #2266: Guitar Marathon
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to highlights from the New Sounds Live/New York Guitar Festival's biannual Guitar Marathon at the 92nd Street Y, Part 3 of 3.

episodesByNumber.title: #2267: Wayfaring Stranger
episodesByNumber.tease: It's been a long time since the last episode of New Sounds took on the idea of theme and variations, but here comes a program on the tune "Wayfaring Stranger".

episodesByNumber.title: #2269: Jimi Hendrix of Tabla
episodesByNumber.tease: Indian percussionist, composer, jazz player, and British-Asian underground mentor Trilok Gurtu visits with John Schaefer and introduces material from his latest recording for this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2270: New Music for a Silent Film
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts at the World Financial Center, the Milwaukee-based new music group Present Music plays a new score to the early Hitchcock silent film “The Lodger.” English composer Joby Talbot provided the original score and plays keyboards along with Present Music in the eerie accompaniment to this film on Jack the Ripper.

episodesByNumber.title: #2271: Music Inspired by Southeast Asia
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the snaking vocal harmonies of Papua New Guinea and rhythms of Indonesian gamelan music, along with Indian vocal techniques on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2272: Innovative Deviations
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, there's a load of new music for guitar.

episodesByNumber.title: #2273: Eurofolk Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Borrowing from other musical traditions is the focus of this program of Eurofolk on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2274: Live from Merkin Hall
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, hear more highlights from past seasons of New Sounds Live concert series at Merkin Hall.

episodesByNumber.title: #2275: From the Kitchen Archives
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program, titled "New Sound New York", is a special sampler of music celebrating the 25th anniversary of The Kitchen’s landmark concert New Music New York.

episodesByNumber.title: #2277: 'Twas Brillig
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds in Wonderland.

episodesByNumber.title: #2278: Mali Cool
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s West African music made with instruments and musicians from Mali on this edition of New Sounds, subtitled “Mali Cool.” “MALIcool” is also the title of the latest collaboration by veteran jazz trombonist Roswell Rudd and kora player Toumani Diabate.

episodesByNumber.title: #2280: Dutch Master
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s music by contemporary Dutch master Louis Andriessen on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2281: Persian Masters and More
episodesByNumber.tease: On this episode of New Sounds, Persian kemanche (spike-fiddle) master Kayhan Kalhor and his ensemble join John Schaefer in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #2282: Jazz Plus...
episodesByNumber.tease: Jazz plus trip-hop, jazz plus musical theatre, and even jazz plus funk, rock, electronica, pop, and everything else are offered up on this New Sounds program, “Jazz Plus.” Hear music from Club D’elf, who mix trip-hop and electronica with their improvisational jazz.

episodesByNumber.title: #2283: The "Classical" Frank Zappa
episodesByNumber.tease: Frank Zappa came to music by Edgar Varèse in his teens and was, according to Pierre Boulez, “hypnotized by [music of] Edgar Varèse.” The influence of this music was not so much that Zappa became a follower of Varèse, but that it stimulated his ambitions to become a composer.

episodesByNumber.title: #2284: Musical Leftovers
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, there’s more music on this program from the biannual New York Guitar Festival Guitar Marathon, featuring works by global slide guitarist Bob Brozman, Brazilian guitar great Vinicius Cantuaria, and African guitarist and griot Abdoulaye Diabate joined by guitarist, journalist and radio personality Banning Eyre.

episodesByNumber.title: #2285: Celtic Call and Response
episodesByNumber.tease: Susan McKeown and friends join John Schaefer for this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2286: Songs & Choros
episodesByNumber.tease: Choro is a musical style which first emerged in the 1870s.

episodesByNumber.title: #2287: A Private Reel
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, it’s another installment of the “Private Reel” series of shows, exclusive live performances from the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #2290: Lullabies From the "Axis of Evil"
episodesByNumber.tease: In his 2002 State of the Union address, President Bush singled out Iran, Iraq, and North Korea and their allies as part of an "axis of evil." In response to this branding, the Norwegian Eric Hillestade traveled to Iraq, Palestine, Iran and North Korea to record lullabies mothers sang to their children.

episodesByNumber.title: #2291: Gagaku and Beyond
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s music inspired by the courts and gardens of imperial Japan on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2292: New Versions of Old Folk Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: The English folk song Scarborough Fair dates back to late medieval times, when the seaside resort of Scarborough was an important venue for tradesmen from all over England.

episodesByNumber.title: #2293: Music in Suspended Time
episodesByNumber.tease: Forget about the space-time continuum on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2294: Choral Works
episodesByNumber.tease: The visionary collaboration between Polish film director Krzysztof Kieslowski and composer Zbigniew Preisner was cut short in 1995 when the director had a heart attack and died.

episodesByNumber.title: #2295: Hi Tech, Lo Tech, (New Tech,) No Tech
episodesByNumber.tease: It’s a New Sounds for the Dr.

episodesByNumber.title: #2296: New Music From California
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program is devoted to new music from California, with some brand-new Cold Blue recordings along with recent moody piano musings from Harold Budd.

episodesByNumber.title: #2297: Live Qawwali Music
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, hear the Qawwali music of Farid Ayaz Qawwal.

episodesByNumber.title: #2298: Young People’s Guide to Astronomy
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program, “The Young People’s Guide to Astronomy,” features works that take astronomical phenomena and translate them into music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2299: Songs of Melancholy
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, hear some pairings of words and music, with settings of poetry, songs of unrequited love, and melancholy.

episodesByNumber.title: #2300: Gamelan Music, East And West
episodesByNumber.tease: From the Javanese, “gamel,” meaning “hammer,” or “to strike," gamelan is a group of instruments meant to be played together, including tuned metallophones, various gongs, flutes, drums and other percussion.

episodesByNumber.title: #2301: Hard Times
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear another of the “Theme and Variations” programs on this New Sounds, where the theme this time is “Hard Times Come Again No More.” It’s simple – take a single piece of music and explore what a number of musicians have done with it, through arrangements, deconstructions, and revisions of the original theme.

episodesByNumber.title: #2303: Machine Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works played by real people but inspired by the sounds of machinery on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2304: Youssou N'Dour's "Egypt"
episodesByNumber.tease: Mbalax is a Senegalese blend of African, Caribbean and pop rhythms; take a base of griot percussion, praise-music, and story-telling, and add western guitars and keyboards.

episodesByNumber.title: #2305: Music from the Bay Area
episodesByNumber.tease: California composer Terry Riley’s seminal “In C,” launched the concept form of interlocking repetitive patterns otherwise known as “minimalism.” There are unavoidable comparisons to Riley when talking of music by other Californians working in the San Francisco Bay area, another of whom we’ll hear on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2306: New Music From Poland
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear New Music from Poland on this edition of New Sounds, with the achingly beautiful work of Henryk Gorecki.

episodesByNumber.title: #2308: World Music
episodesByNumber.tease: The singer, percussionist, dancer and actress Alessandra Belloni joins John Schaefer in the studio to perform a particularly irresistible tarantella with a blend of Brazilian accordion and percussion coupled with Italian traditional singing and chitarra.

episodesByNumber.title: #2309: If It's Broke, Don't Fix It
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music for ruined pianos and beat-up guitars on this New Sounds program, subtitled, "If It's Broke, Don't Fix It." Listen to Victoria Jordanova's Requiem for Bosnia, where the piano is strummed, beaten, and otherwise serves as a entire battery of percussion instruments.

episodesByNumber.title: #2310: Balkan Gypsy Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music under the Balkan & Gypsy influence on this New Sounds Program, featuring music by the gypsy/klezmer/folk/jazz band Les Yeux Noir.

episodesByNumber.title: #2311: Sufi Traveler
episodesByNumber.tease: West Meets Near East on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2312: North, South, East, West
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds faces the music in all directions, North, South, East, and West on this program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2313: Unusual Guitar Works
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, hear inventive music from the Los Angeles Guitar Quartet, with selections from the new CD, "Guitar Heroes."   Embracing their roots- both individually and collectively- the quartet pays tribute to jazz, bluegrass, rock and flamenco guitarists who have influenced and inspired them.

episodesByNumber.title: #2314: Program #2314
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time again for the monthly program of new releases.

episodesByNumber.title: #2316: A Musical Calendar
episodesByNumber.tease: Thirty days hath September, April, June...

episodesByNumber.title: #2317: "Concrete" Music
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s industrial strength "Concrete" music on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2318: British Folk Stories
episodesByNumber.tease: Ballads and laments "Drop, drop slow tears" on this edition of New Sounds, with an updated take on classic folksong tradition from the British Isles.

episodesByNumber.title: #2320: New Sounds of "Jazz Piano"
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, we have a new look at “jazz piano,” with the focus on innovators like Jason Moran, Matthew Shipp and the Bad Plus.

episodesByNumber.title: #2321: Quirky Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: This edition of New Sounds offers up songs by the band One Ring Zero, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #2322: Sharp Wire
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear duo music from London on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2328: September New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2329: Thai Elephants on Parade
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear traditional Thai music, Beethoven’s Pastoral Symphony, and even Hank Williams, all played by elephants: Prathida, Luuk Kob, Luuk Khang, JoJo, Phangkhawt, and Phumpuang.

episodesByNumber.title: #2330: Cross-Continental Fruits
episodesByNumber.tease: Hold on to your passport, for this New Sounds is a whirlwind tour of Scandinavian, Chinese, Arabic and English music traditions - and that’s just on “Ochre,” a collaboration between electric zither master Andrew Cronshaw and Syrian qanun and oud virtuoso Abdullah Chhadeh.

episodesByNumber.title: #2331: World Out Of Tune
episodesByNumber.tease: World Out of Tune festival composer Jon Catler stops by the studio to present works by festival composers; La Monte Young, Elodie Lauten, Neil Haverstick and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #2332: Lines of Choral Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Choral Music of various shapes and sizes is what’s in store for this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2333: Where's the Party?
episodesByNumber.tease: There's party-oriented music pumping from all corners of the globe on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2334: Chamber Jazz and Tokyo Road
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to tracks from "Book of Silk" by the Tin Hat Trio (Mark Orton, Carla Kihlstedt and Rob Burger) on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2335: Talbot Grab Bag
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer, orchestral arranger, keyboard player, and occasional oboe and cor anglais performer Joby Talbot has many irons in the fire.

episodesByNumber.title: #2336: With Pino Forastiere
episodesByNumber.tease: Guitarist and composer Dominic Frasca is opening the ultimate boutique performance space in Chelsea, where the music (rather than the booze, burlesque or meat market scene) takes center stage – The Monkey.

episodesByNumber.title: #2337: October New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: John Schaefer once again picks through the bucketloads of CDs that have flooded his office this Fall to find a sampling of new releases worthy of showcasing in tonight's New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2338: Zippo Songs Live
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live Concert Series, it's a sociopolitical blowout show.

episodesByNumber.title: #2339: Lit Rock
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, the band One Ring Zero presents its “author project,” with readings and lyrics (and some performances) by authors Rick Moody, Paul Auster, and Siri Hustvedt.

episodesByNumber.title: #2340: Jazz Inflections
episodesByNumber.tease: Pianist Larry Karush’s roots embrace jazz, 20th century Western classical music, African-based percussion, and the music of North India.

episodesByNumber.title: #2341: In Praise of Dreams
episodesByNumber.tease: New works from Europe make up the backbone of this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2342: Ethiopiques
episodesByNumber.tease: A series of reissues of Ethiopian pop music of the 60s and 70s, called “Ethiopiques,” has renewed interest in this super-groovy style.

episodesByNumber.title: #2343: Music for Adapted Guitar
episodesByNumber.tease: Works by composers who started with guitars, began altering their instruments, and ended up with a whole new sound world are the focus of this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2344: William Duckworth
episodesByNumber.tease: Often referred to as the first “post-minimalist” composer, William Duckworth has created works for solo instruments, large ensembles, and even the internet, as in his 5-year, ongoing piece “Cathedral.”  "Cathedral" is one of the first interactive, continuous works of music and art designed specifically for the World Wide Web by Duckworth and media artist Nora Farrell.

episodesByNumber.title: #2345: Revisiting New Sounds
episodesByNumber.tease: What year is this, anyway? On this edition of the program, hear electronically-altered music from some of the composers who were part of the nightly New Sounds diet back in the mid-1980s, and who are now going strong again.

episodesByNumber.title: #2346: Radical Jewish Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Radical Jewish Music might encompass Klezmer, Sephardic folk songs, and even the infamous '50s easy listening album "Bagels and Bongos," or anything in the tradition of, or inspired by all of these.

episodesByNumber.title: #2347: ...And You Can Trance To It
episodesByNumber.tease: Trance jazz from two groove-based piano trios is in store on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2348: Mali Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Mali is a country of contrasts, and music there is no exception.

episodesByNumber.title: #2349: November 2004 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2350: I Lost a Sock
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music written for early music specialists and ensembles on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2351: Global Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear global voices singing on tonight’s New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2352: Noise and Space Continuum
episodesByNumber.tease: Hold on to your samplers, for on this edition of New Sounds, you’ll hear something from one of Annie Gosfield’s crazy new pieces incorporating satellite sounds, static, machine noise and microtonality.

episodesByNumber.title: #2353: Music From Italy
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some works based on old Italian regional traditions on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2354: Middle Eastern Masters
episodesByNumber.tease: Ali Akbar Moradi, the acknowledged master of the Kurdish lute, or  tanbur, performs in the WNYC studio on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2355: Oh Captain, My Captain
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, experience Fast ’N’ Bulbous: The Captain Beefheart Project.

episodesByNumber.title: #2356: Soundcheck Revue
episodesByNumber.tease: On this installment of New Sounds, hear live in-studio performances from WNYC’s afternoon program “Soundcheck.”  There’s music from the Tin Hat Trio, and their blend of tango, bluegrass, contemporary classical, and Eastern European folk traditions.

episodesByNumber.title: #2357: Messiah Remix
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, hear compositions ranging from tuneful electronica to craggy modernism, from moody ambience to unbounded joy - all united by the theme of Messiah, George Frederic Handel's 1742 masterpiece of spiritual rebirth.

episodesByNumber.title: #2358: Sacred Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s a collection of ecumenical works that span the world’s great spiritual traditions on this New Sounds Program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2359: It's Beginning To Look A Lot Like...
episodesByNumber.tease: On this program, celebrate the holiday season with a program of seasonal music, New Sounds style.

episodesByNumber.title: #2361: New Sounds Live Is Early
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, take a look back at excerpts from the early years, 1986-1996.

episodesByNumber.title: #2362: Schaefer's Top Ten of 2004
episodesByNumber.tease: On this special episode of New Sounds, John Schaefer presents his annual, highly subjective, completely opinionated list of the ten best new-music releases of 2004.

episodesByNumber.title: #2363: Listener Poll 2004 Results
episodesByNumber.tease: Here's the rebuttal to last night’s program where the listeners weigh in on the best new music releases of 2004.

episodesByNumber.title: #2364: Electric Ethel
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live Concert Series, we present the second half of last fall’s sociopolitical blowout show.

episodesByNumber.title: #2365: Post-Rock Instrumentals
episodesByNumber.tease: With roots in indie rock, and a combination of experimentation and unclassifiable sounds that fuse ambient, jazz, and minimalist chamber music together, “Post-Rock” music tends to subvert many elements associated with rock and roll.

episodesByNumber.title: #2366: Ethio Jazz Live
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, the Either Orchestra, the Massachusetts-based brass band, plays arrangements of classic Ethiopian pop music, with special guest Mulatu Astatqe, one of the leaders of the Ethiopian pop scene in the late 60s/early 70s.

episodesByNumber.title: #2367: Virtual Cathedral
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, William Duckworth and The Cathedral Band play music on real and virtual instruments from Duckworth's enormous, 5-year multimedia web-based piece Cathedral.

episodesByNumber.title: #2368: Electro-Acoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, there are works by and for Canadian composer and guitar player Tim Brady.

episodesByNumber.title: #2369: Flamenco Festival
episodesByNumber.tease: Palestinian oud player Simon Shaheen and Flamenco guitarist Gerardo Nunez perform in the WNYC studio on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2370: Musical Storytime
episodesByNumber.tease: Gather round, for on this edition of New Sounds, it's time for some musical storytelling.

episodesByNumber.title: #2372: String Quartet Plus
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to the Kronos Quartet play music by the Azerbaijani composer Franghiz Ali-Zadeh.

episodesByNumber.title: #2373: Funky Brassy Party
episodesByNumber.tease: It’s Friday and that means brassy, funky party music, New Sounds-style on this edition of the show.

episodesByNumber.title: #2374: Eastern Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Experience the distinctive rich choral music from the Balkan and Slavic regions of Eastern Europe on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2375: Thrash Klezmer Mish-Mosh
episodesByNumber.tease: Prepare for some incredibly relentless fun on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2376: American Eccentrics
episodesByNumber.tease: As part of WNYC’s American Music Festival on this edition of New Sounds, there's music from American eccentric Harry Partch, who among other things, was a composer, instrument-maker, musical dramatist, sometime hobo, piano teacher, and grape-picker.

episodesByNumber.title: #2377: Unconventional Works for Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, there’s music from Azerbaijani composer Franghiz Ali-Zadeh, who fuses characteristics of traditional Azerbaijani music with modern Western techniques in her “Music for Piano.”   Not incidentally, she is also known as a pianist who first brought the music of John Cage, Arnold Schoenberg and George Crumb to Azerbaijan.

episodesByNumber.title: #2378: American Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s music by Ingram Marshall on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2379: Japan: 1000 Years of Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Dip into a new collection of 1000 years of Music from Japan on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2380: Worms And Specks
episodesByNumber.tease: “America's multi-mediatrix” Laurie Anderson visits the studio on this edition of New Sounds to talk about and sample from her latest work, The End of the Moon.

episodesByNumber.title: #2382: Commissioned for the People
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts at Merkin Hall, the Bang on a Can All-Stars perform two newly-commissioned works and a new music classic with special guest Philip Glass.

episodesByNumber.title: #2383: Commissioned by the People
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts at Merkin Hall, the Bang on a Can All-Stars perform a newly-commissioned work, revisit one of their first commissioned pieces, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #2384: Lullaby and Goodnight
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, take a tour of the globe with lullabies from around the world.

episodesByNumber.title: #2385: Plundering the Archives
episodesByNumber.tease: We’ll be mining the New Sounds Live archives on this edition of New Sounds with performances going all the way back to the 1980’s, featuring pianist, composer and arranger Mark Kirkostas.

episodesByNumber.title: #2386: Harmonic Meditations
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, there's music by David Hykes, founder of the Harmonic Choir and a leading proponent of Asian-inspired “overtone chant.” Hykes presents his new cd “Harmonic Meditations,” which includes music for Khyentse Norbu’s film “Travellers and Magicians,” set in the tiny Buddhist kingdom of Bhutan.

episodesByNumber.title: #2387: Phantom of the Opera
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live/Silent Film series at the World Financial Center, The Clubfoot Orchestra plays a new score by Richard Marriott for the Lon Chaney silent film “Phantom of the Opera.”  Lon Chaney’s phantom is the quintessential horror film demon – both touching and terrifying, while Marriott's music underlies the mysterious phantom who is mad with love for Christine.

episodesByNumber.title: #2388: Turntablist Guitarist
episodesByNumber.tease: The digital, digitized, and digitally refracted guitar-based music of Andre LaFosse is on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2389: Acoustic Ambient Music
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, there’s brand new music from the composer and founder of the recently revived Cold Blue Music label, Jim Fox.

episodesByNumber.title: #2390: Battleship Potemkin
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live/Silent Film series at the World Financial Center, The Clubfoot Orchestra plays a new score by Richard Marriott for Sergei Eisenstein’s famous silent film “Battleship Potemkin.” One of the most renowned films of the century, "Potemkin" contains one of the best-known sequences in cinema’s entire history – the harrowing fall of a baby carriage down the Odessa steps.

episodesByNumber.title: #2391: Infectious Beat
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program is an hour of dance music inspired by klezmer, Balkan and gypsy music, featuring the Klezmatics’s new CD “Brother Moses Smote The Water.” This incredible live CD, with special guests Joshua Nelson and Kathryn Farmer, captures the New York-based klezmer band taking on the mantle of a fire-and-brimstone gospel group, with deep drinks of soul and blues.

episodesByNumber.title: #2392: Modern Jazz Pop Chamber Rock
episodesByNumber.tease: The Four Bags, with trombone, accordion, guitar and clarinet or saxophone, are an adventure into chamber music by way of modern jazz, rock and pop.

episodesByNumber.title: #2393: Live Crafty Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to an in-studio performance by the group Zum, an international guitar ensemble consisting of members of Robert Fripp’s League of Crafty Guitarists.

episodesByNumber.title: #2395: You're From Where?
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, look forward to unexpected collaborations across the continents, from Podjama & Saraswati, the Euro-jazz and Balinese gamelan project to Baka Beyond, the African-Celtic crossover band inspired by the music of a pygmy community in West Africa.

episodesByNumber.title: #2396: Spiritual Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some new works for violins and other strings that draw from medieval sacred chant as a source of inspiration on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2397: Song of Realization
episodesByNumber.tease: Minnesota guitarist Steve Tibbetts faces east once again on his most recent release, Selwa, a follow-up to his 1997 collaboration with the Tibetan Buddhist nun Chöying Drolma.

episodesByNumber.title: #2398: Luscinia’s Lullaby
episodesByNumber.tease: Canadian vocalist and composer Laurel MacDonald visits the studio for this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2399: Music for Multiples
episodesByNumber.tease: What’s better than music for accordion?  Music for 4 or 5 accordions, of course!  On this New Sounds, hear musical works for small armies of one kind of instrument - clarinets, guitars, pianos, and accordions, among others.

episodesByNumber.title: #2400: Music from West Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s music from West Africa on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2401: A Private Reel
episodesByNumber.tease: It’s another in the series of programs on New Sounds called “A Private Reel,” featuring live performances from the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #2402: Sacred Music, Irish and Otherwise
episodesByNumber.tease: The name Anuna derives from the ancient Irish name "An Uaithne," which collectively describes the three ancient types of Celtic music; lullaby, happy song, and lament  (Suantrai, Geantrai and Goltrai, respectively.)  This Irish group, who were the original “Riverdance” choir, blend Middle English, Scots Gaelic, Irish, Breton, Medieval Irish, Latin, and Greek choral music together in tunes ranging from folk songs to newly composed music based on ancient texts.

episodesByNumber.title: #2403: American Roots
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, there’s music by master guitarist Brandon Ross, a versatile musician who has worked with the likes of Henry Threadgill, Butch Morris, Oliver Lake, and Cassandra Wilson.

episodesByNumber.title: #2404: Radiohead Revisited
episodesByNumber.tease: The English rock band Radiohead has attracted an unusual amount of attention from other-than-rock musicians.

episodesByNumber.title: #2405: More Lullabies
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds programs offers more lullabies – a whole hour of nocturnal works by Meredith Monk, Natacha Atlas, Taj Mahal, Harold Budd, and many others.

episodesByNumber.title: #2407: Nordic Soundscapes
episodesByNumber.tease: Experience the sparse beauty of the Tord Gustavsen trio on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2408: Digital Dervish
episodesByNumber.tease: With one foot in Montréal, and one foot dancing and lingering in his native Turkey, the 21st century dervish Mercan Dede has taken the electronic groove and beats out of the DJ booth and melded them to traditional instruments like the darbouka, santur, and ney.

episodesByNumber.title: #2409: Hammers and Sticks
episodesByNumber.tease: It’s an action-packed hour of beatings on this edition of New Sounds with music for pianos, marimbas, and pianos together with marimbas.

episodesByNumber.title: #2410: Musical Storytellers
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, read the titles and guess the theme of the show.

episodesByNumber.title: #2411: New Music for Cello
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to an hour of new music for cello, including music from cellist David Darling and The Wulu Bunun, an aboriginal tribe living in Taiwan.

episodesByNumber.title: #2412: Songs for The Moon
episodesByNumber.tease: To celebrate the lunar landing's 50th, hear songs to the moon, about the moon, and higher than the moon from Schoenberg to Pink Floyd, Savina Yannatou, John Cale, and Susana Baca.

episodesByNumber.title: #2413: Reimaginings
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to an hour of unusual covers of popular songs.

episodesByNumber.title: #2414: New Sounds Live, More Early Years
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from the early years of concert recordings on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2415: Klezmer-Core, Balkan Bangers and More
episodesByNumber.tease: It’s New Sounds party music on this program with high-energy Balkan and Slavic big band music played by Americans.

episodesByNumber.title: #2416: Cross-Cultural World Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear many different cross-cultural collaborations on this New Sounds program like the joyous, energetic music made by the Bang on a Can All-Stars together with composer and virtuoso of the Burmese pat waing, Kyaw Kyaw Naing.

episodesByNumber.title: #2417: Splintered "Totalist" Music

episodesByNumber.title: #2418: Romanian Fantasies
episodesByNumber.tease: Tabla master Zakir Hussain has proclaimed that "without Romanies the musical history of our planet would be completely different."  He compares Romanies to bees who fly all over the planet and then mix together the "pollen" they have gathered from its musical "flowers", regardless of anything besides musical perfection.

episodesByNumber.title: #2419: May 2005 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for our monthly program of new releases.

episodesByNumber.title: #2420: Radiance
episodesByNumber.tease: Keith Jarrett once said that “the best improvisations I know of are always made when you have no ideas.

episodesByNumber.title: #2421: Ashes and Snow
episodesByNumber.tease: Ashes and Snow, the photography/film exhibition by Gregory Colbert, has continued its worldwide migration since its Venice, Italy premiere in 2002.

episodesByNumber.title: #2422: Daniel Lanois and Belladonna
episodesByNumber.tease: Daniel Lanois, the guitarist, singer, songwriter and award-winning uber-producer (Peter Gabriel, U2, Bob Dylan, Dashboard Confessional)visits the studio for this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2423: What's Up with Gavin Bryars
episodesByNumber.tease: English composer Gavin Bryars first made his musical reputation as an improvisational jazz bassist in the mid-sixties, but he abandoned improv to work for a time in the United States with John Cage.

episodesByNumber.title: #2424: World Trance Music
episodesByNumber.tease: It’s an hour of world dance music and ecstatic trance on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2425: Banana/ Dump Truck
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer, Princeton University professor, and unrepentant electric guitarist Steven Mackey visits the WNYC studios for this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2426: Early New Sounds Live
episodesByNumber.tease: For more than 20 years, New Sounds has been presenting new and unusual music from inside and outside the WNYC studios.

episodesByNumber.title: #2427: Under the Traditional Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, hear western music based on and infused with Middle Eastern influences.

episodesByNumber.title: #2428: Beyond Words
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to vocal music without texts, from  the sort of angelic minimalism of Mary Jane Leach to the jazzical vocals of Bobby McFerrin.

episodesByNumber.title: #2429: Egghead Van Halen
episodesByNumber.tease: “You can excite an audience, you can anger an audience, you can even scare an audience, just don't bore an audience."  This is the operating philosophy of guitarist, composer, and presenter Dominic Frasca.

episodesByNumber.title: #2430: New Music from Australia
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, prepare for music from the land of Oz – Australia, that is.

episodesByNumber.title: #2431: An Hour of Björk
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear an hour of music by the elfin Icelandic singer and songwriter Björk on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2432: June 2005 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: Oh bliss!  We love it when new mail it comes into the New Sounds office.

episodesByNumber.title: #2433: Two by Two
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program offers several combinations of twos, with music from Mali, Jewish-Arab music, Balinese-influenced percussion music, and jazz trombone together with African kora.

episodesByNumber.title: #2434: Music of Former Yugoslavia
episodesByNumber.tease: Yugoslavia, which is now Serbia and Montenegro, was a former kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes, and encompassed a sprawling region that included the former republics of Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia-Slavonia, Macedonia, and the autonomous provinces of Kosovo and Vojvodina, along with Dalmatia.

episodesByNumber.title: #2435: New Sounds Live
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear highlights from several New Sounds Live concerts recorded in the late 1980's and early 1990's.

episodesByNumber.title: #2437: Works on Film
episodesByNumber.tease: Music involving film and filmmakers is the focus of this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2438: Percussion Paintings
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to works for percussion ensemble that depict natural phenomena, including meteor showers, animals, and others on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2439: Sundanese Gamelan Pop
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s gamelan music from Sunda, the western third of the island of Java in Indonesia, on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2440: New Music Bands, 80’s Style
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, prepare for an ‘80s show of entirely different constructions.

episodesByNumber.title: #2441: World Music From the 80's
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some works combining the sounds of world music traditions with electronics on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2442: New Music for Flute
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, the focus is on the flute.

episodesByNumber.title: #2443: Music & Technology
episodesByNumber.tease: There are some early instances of electronic and electroacoustic music on this New Sounds program, as we continue to mine the vast motherlode of riches from the early years of New Sounds Live performances.

episodesByNumber.title: #2444: Indian Vocals, Western Music
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds show, there’s music built around Indian vocals, from the pop style known as filmi to the centuries-old devotional and love poems known as ghazal.

episodesByNumber.title: #2445: July 2005 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2446: Choral Music
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program samples a bit of choral music, with works that draw upon the Odyssey and the ancient folk songs of Estonia to a work based on a portion of the life of Mohandas K.

episodesByNumber.title: #2447: August 2005 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2448: Music for Sport
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the pairing of music with sports on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2450: Global Pop
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, listen to the strains of global pop, including music by Holger Czukay, founding member and bass player of the influential Krautrock group Can.

episodesByNumber.title: #2451: In the Moment
episodesByNumber.tease: Cécile Schott, working under the moniker "Colleen," has crafted elegant, barely-there compositions on her latest release, “The Golden Morning Breaks.” On this edition of New Sounds, sample from some of these textured soundscapes of muted moods and ethereal melodies.

episodesByNumber.title: #2452: Technical Arrangements
episodesByNumber.tease: Up on this New Sounds program, dig into the latest from the new music ensemble Alarm Will Sound.

episodesByNumber.title: #2453: Worldwide Overtones
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer and vocalist Joan La Barbara can approximate ranges of sound from a chanting monk to the cry of a fallen bird.

episodesByNumber.title: #2454: Striking Violins
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the latest from violinist and composer Michael Galasso, whose previous projects, especially his collaborative work with director Robert Wilson and Wong Kar-wai ("In The Mood for Love,") made lasting impressions in film and theatre music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2455: Music Without Borders
episodesByNumber.tease: A world of musical influences are fused together as the Bombay Dub Orchestra draws from ambient, western classical, Indian classical & light classical music and many other places.

episodesByNumber.title: #2457: Music and Film
episodesByNumber.tease: Film maker Bill Morrison and composer/pianist Philip Glass join us on this New Sounds program to chat about some of the music and films being produced for The Film Makers Cooperative.

episodesByNumber.title: #2458: Soundscapes
episodesByNumber.tease: Experience various soundscapes on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2459: September 2005 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the latest from composers Pete M. Wyer and Donnacha Dennehy, along with John Zorn's radical Jewish-indie-punk-jazz from a CD called "Masada Rock."

episodesByNumber.title: #2460: New Jewish Renaissance
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to music from the new Jewish Renaissance, including works from klezmer-revival musicians like the Klezmatics, and Andy Statman along with radical Jewish music from John Zorn, and world fusion from Wally Brill and Atzilut.

episodesByNumber.title: #2461: Sampling Don Cherry
episodesByNumber.tease: The great trumpeter, world music icon, jazz explorer, improviser, and part Choctaw Indian - Don Cherry - is no longer on the planet, but his work lives on in recordings.

episodesByNumber.title: #2462: Unusual as Folk
episodesByNumber.tease: "Triple-exile" composer Osvaldo Golijov brings together elements from his Eastern Europe roots, from his Jewish heritage, and from his native Argentina and melds them with Western classical traditions, and Mediterranean folklore.

episodesByNumber.title: #2463: What's Old Is New
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to two recordings by Steve Reich – a recent work, “You Are (Variations)” and a 1977 live performance from New York’s New Music venue The Kitchen.

episodesByNumber.title: #2464: Bamboo, Silk and Stone
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s new music for the zither from Korea, Japan, and China on this edition of New Sounds, with works by Mei Han & Barry Truax, David Bowie, and Korean-American komungo (Korean fourth century fretted board zither) virtuoso Jin Hi Kim.

episodesByNumber.title: #2465: New from the North
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program explores new works coming out of Scandinavia, with some music based in folk traditions, and played by bands who share several different members.

episodesByNumber.title: #2466: Baltic Musical States
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Eastern Europe and The Baltics on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2467: Bottoms Up!
episodesByNumber.tease: Telepathically tight and musically adventurous, the members of the Bad Plus test the limits of what an acoustic bass-drums-piano band can do.

episodesByNumber.title: #2468: World Tour
episodesByNumber.tease: From frenetic crazy Bulgarian wedding music to the blown-out amplified sounds of thumb pianos, feast your ears on a smorgasbord of world music for this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2469: October 2005 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's the most wonderful time of the month - new releases! On this New Sounds program, listen to the pick of the piles.

episodesByNumber.title: #2470: Breaking Ice
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works for chamber rock ensembles, like the English band Icebreaker and the Bang on a Can All-Stars on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2471: Force of Her Fortieth
episodesByNumber.tease: Hailed as “one of America’s Coolest Composers,” vocal innovator, filmmaker and director/choreographer Meredith Monk has opened the eyes and ears of countless artists and performers.

episodesByNumber.title: #2472: Assassin Reverie
episodesByNumber.tease: Like the Energizer Bunny, some of the groundbreaking composers of the 1960s are still breaking ground today.

episodesByNumber.title: #2473: (Near) East Meets West
episodesByNumber.tease: Take a new look at medieval music as the British a capella group The King's Singers and Middle Eastern early music specialists, Sarband team up to perform sacred music by 17th century composer Ali Ufki.

episodesByNumber.title: #2474: Cello Multiples
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some music for multiple cellos, acoustic and electric, looped and layered on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2475: Buoyant Afro-pop
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds is serving up Afro-pop and Afro-groove music on this program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2476: "Art House" Film Scores
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to exquisite scores written not for blockbuster feature films but for smaller, "art-house" movies.

episodesByNumber.title: #2477: Purcell Maneuvers
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, we’ll hear music inspired by composer Henry Purcell (1659-1695), including the singing alien camp theatrics of Klaus Nomi.

episodesByNumber.title: #2478: New Music from Switzerland
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, expect the occasional alphorn – but no yodeling.

episodesByNumber.title: #2479: Music for Multiples
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, experience an hour of music for multiples of the same instrument.

episodesByNumber.title: #2480: Must Haves: Traditional Music
episodesByNumber.tease: On the eve of WNYC's third annual Must Have Festival, John Schaefer offers a guide to traditional music for this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2481: Must Haves: World Music
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds throws its cap back into the Must Have Festival ring (before the horses are out of the gate for the third annual event), with another night of recommended recordings, this time in the "world music" vein.

episodesByNumber.title: #2482: Must Haves: Contemporary Classical
episodesByNumber.tease: In advance of our third annual Must Have Festival, listen to some recommended contemporary classical music on tonight's program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2483: New Releases November 2005
episodesByNumber.tease: John Schaefer picks through the bucketloads of CDs that have flooded his office this fall to find a sampling of new releases worthy of showcasing in tonight's New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2484: Meredith Monk Live
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts at World Financial Center, a celebration of the 40th anniversary season of vocalist/composer Meredith Monk.

episodesByNumber.title: #2485: New Music Soundtracks
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds tackles film music for this program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2486: Chant Wars
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, listen to medieval chant and its contemporary descendants with music from the groups Sequentia, Chanticleer, Trio Medieval, The Mediaeval Baebes, and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #2487: String Quartet Plus
episodesByNumber.tease: Music for string quartet takes over this New Sounds program with help from additional musical and non-musical sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2488: Meredith Monk Live II
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series at the World Financial Center, hear the second half of a two-part tribute to vocalist/composer Meredith Monk, concluding her 40th anniversary season.

episodesByNumber.title: #2489: Winter Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Almost no one’s favorite season, and yet it has inspired lots of evocative new music, including works by Aulis Sallinen, Wendy Carlos, Glen Moore, Edgar Meyer, and Dino Saluzzi.

episodesByNumber.title: #2490: New English Pastoral
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s music in the English “pastoral” tradition on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2491: December 2005 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: John Schaefer once again picks through the bucketloads of CDs that have flooded his office to find a sampling of new releases worthy of showcasing on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2492: Schaefer's Top 10 of 2005
episodesByNumber.tease: On this special episode of New Sounds, John Schaefer presents his annual, highly subjective, completely opinionated list of the ten best new-music releases of 2005.

episodesByNumber.title: #2493: Listener Poll 2005 Results
episodesByNumber.tease: Here's the rebuttal to last night’s program where the listeners weigh in on the best new music releases of 2005.

episodesByNumber.title: #2494: Twittering Machines
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, experience music driven by a relentless pulse.

episodesByNumber.title: #2495: New York Guitar Festival Sampler
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to highlights from the biannual New York Guitar Festival Marathon, including performances from Bill Frisell and Greg Leisz (on electric and lap steel guitar, respectively) and Brazilian music from the Assad Brothers.

episodesByNumber.title: #2496:  The Indonesian Reach
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some traditional and pop music from Indonesia, and the music it’s inspired on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2497: Mostly Acoustic Indie Chamber
episodesByNumber.tease: Can you imagine a show where you hear violas, french horn, trumpet, bassoon, stand-up bass, organ, guitars, drums, xylophone, steelpan, accordion and typewriter all together in the same hour-long program? Well, just give a listen to the adventurous music of several hard-to-describe jazz/classical/experimental/post-rock ensembles on this New Sounds show.

episodesByNumber.title: #2498: Ryuichi Sakamoto
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, listen to the many musical sides of Ryuichi Sakamoto, whose birthday is today.

episodesByNumber.title: #2499: Cross-Cultural Sampler
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds offers some cross-cultural music spanning the traditions of several different continents on this program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2500: New Music from Spain
episodesByNumber.tease: Mainly new music from Spain fills this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2501 “Rock Me Amadeus,” Part 1, Mostly Mozart (Fringe) Festival :
episodesByNumber.tease: There's Mozart-based fringe music by German electronic pioneer Edgar Froese (Tangerine Dream), American computer music wiz Carl Stone, and Edgar Meyer riffing on Mozartian structure.

episodesByNumber.title: #2502 “Rock Me Amadeus,” Part 2, Mostly Mozart (Fringe) Festival :
episodesByNumber.tease: As part of our week-long Mostly Mozart fringe festival, hear music by influential Dutch composer Louis Andriessen, "nuclear polka" band Brave Combo and jazz pianist Dave Brubeck.

episodesByNumber.title: #2503: "Rock Me Amadeus," part 3, Mostly Mozart (Fringe) Festival -
episodesByNumber.tease: The Mostly Mozart fringe festival continues with music from vocalist Bobby McFerrin and pianist Chick Corea, English composer Michael Nyman and computer music by American Larry Austin.

episodesByNumber.title: #2504: New Celtic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, there’s a helping of Celtic music from the non-compromising traditional band Altan, named after the deep and mysterious lake behind Errigal Mountain in Donegal.

episodesByNumber.title: #2505: January 2006 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again: the recordings flooding into John Schaefer's inbox haven't let up.

episodesByNumber.title: #2506: Gotham - a Filmic Symphony
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, Listen to Michael Gordon’s “Gotham,” a filmic symphony in collaboration with filmmaker Bill Morrison.

episodesByNumber.title: #2507: Primarily Percussion
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, drink in some music where the drummers get the spotlight, like the debut recording from Afro-Cuban All-Star percussionist Miguel 'Anga' Diaz.

episodesByNumber.title: #2508: New Music from Germany
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to Ensemble Modern playing music of Frank Zappa, Haindling’s updated Bavarian folkmusic, Duo Sonare playing Mike Oldfield’s “Tubular Bells,” and more on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2509: Solo Sessions
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, pianist/composer Matthew Shipp presents music from his latest album of nu-jazz, “One.” His first collection of original solo material in nearly a decade, (his last solo outing was a record of standards, not his own works), Shipp gleefully explores and savors where the music might take him, rather than resorting to pianistic pyrotechnics.

episodesByNumber.title: #2510: The Modern Medieval
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some new music that looks back – way back – on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2511: Unconventional String Quartets
episodesByNumber.tease: Over the years, New Sounds Live has played host to some truly remarkable performances that never saw the light of day as commercial recordings.

episodesByNumber.title: #2512: Wu Man And Friends
episodesByNumber.tease: On her recent release, “Wu Man And Friends” the Chinese pipa (lute) virtuoso Wu Man teams up with musicians representing East African, Slavic, and Appalachian traditions.

episodesByNumber.title: #2513: Live Bang on a Can
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds show, experience The Bang On A Can All-Stars, in concert.

episodesByNumber.title: #2514: Not Exactly "Jazz"
episodesByNumber.tease: What if you can’t quite call it “jazz”? Well, then it’ll probably end up on this New Sounds program, which is chock full of music that is jazzy, but not “jazz.” There’s music from the Benevento Russo Duo, two soul mates who take keyboards and drums and bring them to looser, scruffier, and funkier heights of rock-influenced chamber jazz.

episodesByNumber.title: #2515: Guitar Marathon 2006
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, there’s new music from the New York Guitar Festival Marathon 2006 at the 92nd Street Y, “450 Years of Spanish Guitar.” Listen to three newly commissioned world-premiere compositions — all inspired by Spanish themes: "Los Cambios Quedan Igual," by Gyan Riley for classical guitar; Variations on “La Follia” by Dominic Frasca, for guitar and laptop; and “Memorial” by Bryce Dessner, for guitar, viola, and percussion.

episodesByNumber.title: #2516: New Releases February 2006
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2518: "Voices of Light" Live
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts at World Financial Center, listen to the Richard Einhorn oratorio “Voices of Light” - music written to accompany the great silent film “The Passion of Joan of Arc.” Ensemble Sospeso, Anonymous 4, the New Amsterdam Chorus, and vocal soloists, led by conducter David Hattner perform at the WFC’s Winter Garden.

episodesByNumber.title: #2519: Mellits, the "Post-Minimalist"
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds episode, listen to “Brick” by Marc Mellits.
