episodesByNumber.title: #2521: Unusual Prayer Settings
episodesByNumber.tease: Experience some unusual prayer settings on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2522: A Brazilian Experiment
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music by a Brazilian original, the multi-instrumentalist and composer (and eccentric) Hermeto Pascoal, who blurs barriers between jazz, improvisation, folkloric, ethnic, Brazilian music, tone and noise.

episodesByNumber.title: #2523: New Early Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample some new music for lutes, baroque guitars, and other early instruments on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2524: Abrahamic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to music that celebrates the common roots of Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.

episodesByNumber.title: #2525: Blues Fallin' Down Like Rain, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear excerpts from the NY Guitar Festival concert series, featuring reinterpretations of classic blues by Mississippi John Hurt, Skip James, Elizabeth Cotten, and Charlie Patton.

episodesByNumber.title: #2526: Mingus and Monk
episodesByNumber.tease: Explore the music Charles Mingus and Thelonious Monk, New Sounds-style.

episodesByNumber.title: #2527: Bang on a Can PCF Concert 2006
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, the Bang on a Can All-Stars play works commissioned for them through the People's Commissioning Fund.

episodesByNumber.title: #2528: Blues Fallin' Down Like Rain, part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear more excerpts from the NY Guitar Festival concert series, reinterpretations of classic blues by Mississippi John Hurt, Skip James, Elizabeth Cotten, and Charlie Patton.

episodesByNumber.title: #2529: New Releases March 2006
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for our monthly program of new releases.

episodesByNumber.title: #2530: Loungey Latin Jazz
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample some Latin/lounge/jazz-tinged music for this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2531: New Choral Works
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer Eric Whitacre purports to be influenced by Depeche Mode, Bjork and seventies prog rock as much as he is by Bartok, Barber and Monteverdi.

episodesByNumber.title: #2532: Mobile, Solo Kotche
episodesByNumber.tease: The percussionist Glenn Kotche, best known as the drummer for the band Wilco, joins host John Schaefer for a tour through his new solo CD "Mobile," on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2533: Music from East Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: It’s a musical journey through an overlooked part of Africa, with excerpts from the Ethiopiques series, the new Zanzibara series, and recordings by Nursery Boys, Samite, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #2534: Blues Fallin' Down Like Rain, part 3
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear still more excerpts from the NY Guitar Festival concert series, reinterpretations of classic blues by Mississippi John Hurt, Skip James, Elizabeth Cotten, and Charlie Patton.

episodesByNumber.title: #2535: New York-based Ensembles
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, tenor saxophonist Paul Shapiro stops by to present tracks from his latest exuberant release, “It’s in the Twilight” (another in John Zorn’s Radical Jewish Culture series.) The record is full of playful interactions that might be best described as Cuban-Jewish Blue Note soul that jumps, jives, and swings, while somehow merging the secular and the spiritual throughout.

episodesByNumber.title: #2536: Indigenous Shrinking World
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, sample some music whose instrumentation, tuning, and blend of styles reflects the collision of East and West, old and new, composed and improvised.

episodesByNumber.title: #2537: Story Ballads
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, gather round for some story ballads, old and new.

episodesByNumber.title: #2538: Downtown Gamelan
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the clangorous sounds of gamelan-inspired music from New York’s "downtown" scene on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2540: Computer Music
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, it’s a sampling of computer music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2541: April 2006 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2542: Central Asian Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to central Asian voices on this New Sounds program, where we’ll feature the recent album by Tibetan refugee singer and composer Yungchen Lhamo - AMA.

episodesByNumber.title: #2543: Andalusian Origins
episodesByNumber.tease: Jewish/Algerian pianist and composer Maurice El Medioni, Grandmaster of Raï (once called the “Rubén Gonzaléz of the Maghreb”), teamed up with Cuban/Klezmer super-drummer Roberto Rodriguez on a new record for a combustible blend of Arabic, African, Jewish, and Latin elements.

episodesByNumber.title: #2544: World Post-Minimalism
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, sample some post-minimalism from around the world.

episodesByNumber.title: #2545: American Fiddle
episodesByNumber.tease: Violinist and composer Darol Anger, a founder of the Turtle Island String Quartet, joins us to talk about his current group, The Republic of Strings.

episodesByNumber.title: #2546: Afro-pop-a-go-go
episodesByNumber.tease: Take a sampling of some of the latest Afro-pop releases on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2547: New Sounds Rocks
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, listen to strange covers of rock songs by David Bowie, The Pixies, and Elliott Smith, featuring (among others) Brazilian singer Seu Jorge, the jazz trio The Bad Plus, classical pianist Christopher O'Riley, and downtown trombonist Curtis Hasselbring.

episodesByNumber.title: #2548: Six-String Riley
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, Gyan Riley joins us in the studio to present recent works and sneak peeks at in-progress studio recordings.

episodesByNumber.title: #2549: European Minimalism
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to “zen-funk” a sort of “ritual groove” from Nik Bartsch’s Ronin, insistent with its propulsive interlocking rhythms and demanding constant attention, rather than mind-wandering meditation.

episodesByNumber.title: #2550: Odd Ambient Post-Rock
episodesByNumber.tease: “Post-Rock” is a catch-all term used to describe music that subverts many elements associated with indie rock, yet works in elements of jazz, minimalist chamber music, experimental and ambient music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2551: Zithered
episodesByNumber.tease: Was that an acoustic guitar?  A harp?  Well, for this New Sounds, everything comes from the zither (and digital delays) when the Austrian bassoonist/composer Christof Dienz performs live in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #2552: New Music for Thumb Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: Nearly ubiquitous in sub-Saharan Africa, the thumb piano (also known as mbira, kalimba, sanza, and other regional names) has both a musical and spiritual legacy.

episodesByNumber.title: #2553: New for May 2006
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time again for the monthly program of new releases.

episodesByNumber.title: #2554: Electro-Acoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, we’ll dip into the new collection of works by Eve Beglarian, from a CD called “Tell the Birds,” which deals with texts, from such disparate writers as William Blake, Polish poet Czeslaw Milosz, and American poets Linda Norton and Stanley Kunitz.

episodesByNumber.title: #2555: Almost Jazz
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to some idiosyncratic almost-jazz from America, Australia, and beyond, including some new music by the Catholics.

episodesByNumber.title: #2556: The Eno Connection
episodesByNumber.tease: Brian Eno, who rose to prominence as the boa-modeling, liberally rouged keyboardist for '70s glam band Roxy Music, has long experimented with dismantled pop structures and toyed with sound, credited by some as having invented "ambient" music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2557: Cross-cultural Music
episodesByNumber.tease: (ONLINE ONLY) There's new music from Turkey, like the film soundtrack of "Crossing The Bridge," music by digital dervish Mercan Dede  &  groove-based experimental music by Club D'Elf.

episodesByNumber.title: #2558: BOAC Marathon 2006 Highlights, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to highlights from the 2006 Bang on a Can Marathon, recorded live at the World Financial Center.

episodesByNumber.title: #2559: BOAC Marathon 2006 Highlights, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to highlights from the 2006 Bang on a Can Marathon, recorded live at the World Financial Center.

episodesByNumber.title: #2560: BOAC Marathon 2006 Highlights, Part 3
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to highlights from the 2006 Bang on a Can Marathon, recorded live at the World Financial Center.

episodesByNumber.title: #2561: All Strung Up
episodesByNumber.tease: Up on this New Sounds program is a wide net of guitar music, from the Japanese/Argentine trio Zum to the neo-folk of Glenn Jones; along with the elegant compositions of Ralph Towner to the Persian-rooted guitar of Lily Afshar.

episodesByNumber.title: #2562: 'Round Midnight
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to an hour of reinterpretations and deconstructions of Thelonius Monk’s classic song, 'Round Midnight on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2563: New Sounds Live Post-rocks
episodesByNumber.tease: Bassoon rock.

episodesByNumber.title: #2564: June 2006 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: We love it when new mail it comes into the New Sounds office.

episodesByNumber.title: #2566: Drawing From Hindu Scriptures
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, listen to Western Music inspired by Hindu scriptures, including works by Benjamin Verdery, Douglas J.

episodesByNumber.title: #2567: Slavic Rocker Gets Serious
episodesByNumber.tease: Goran Bregovic, guitarist and composer, was a rock hero in the former Yugoslavia with his band Bijelo Dugme (White Button.) When he tired of that, he moved on to film scores, making incredible music to accompany the films of Emir Kusturica (Time of the Gypsies, Arizona Dream, Undreground.) Bregovic has written for Iggy Pop, Ofra Haza, and Cesaria Evora, to name a few.

episodesByNumber.title: #2568: Solo Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, hear some solo works for plucked and hammered strings by the likes of pianists Eleanor Sandresky and Robin Holcomb, and avant-garde harpist Hélène Breschand.

episodesByNumber.title: #2569: New Sounds Live Post-rocks Part II
episodesByNumber.tease: Bassoon rock.

episodesByNumber.title: #2570: Slightly Eccentric Journey
episodesByNumber.tease: Michael Brook, the longtime electric guitarist, producer, instrument builder, inspired collaborator and composer joins us for this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2571: New Music from South Asia
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, experience gamelan pop from Indonesia, by Uun Budiman and the Jugala Gamelan Orchestra.

episodesByNumber.title: #2572: New English Choral Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Up on this New Sounds program, hear some new choral music representing three different generations of English choral composers, including the recently premiered work "Path of Miracles" by Joby Talbot.

episodesByNumber.title: #2573: New Irish Folk
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds is devoted to new music from the Irish folk tradition, including music by the late Mícheál O Domhnaill.

episodesByNumber.title: #2575: New Releases July 2006
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2577: New Releases August 2006
episodesByNumber.tease: John Schaefer once again picks through the bucketloads of CDs that have flooded his office to find a sampling of new releases worthy of showcasing on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2580: Almost Jazz
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds show, sample some recent recordings of works that stretch the definitions of jazz.

episodesByNumber.title: #2581: More Ambient Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Ambient music can be music of little or no rhythm, with background sounds and effects as foreground music, perhaps bringing to mind works by Brian Eno.

episodesByNumber.title: #2582: New Music from Argentina
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to a bunch of new music from Argentina on this New Sounds show, including singer/songwriter Gabriela’s unique combination of Argentine folk music and jazz.

episodesByNumber.title: #2583: World Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the dangerous heat of Hazmat Modine, together with Tuvan throat singer Huun-Huur-Tu as we administer a dose of cross-cultural world music on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2584: Joys & Desires
episodesByNumber.tease: Experience “high torque” ensemble music with the "Joys and Desires" from in-and-out-of-jazz drummer/composer John Hollenbeck.

episodesByNumber.title: #2585: A World of Prayer
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the convergence of Christian and Muslim holy texts on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2586: Instrumental Crossovers
episodesByNumber.tease: On this edition of New Sounds, the string quartet Ethel plays "Nepomuk’s Dances" by Marcelo Zarvos from their recent release "Light."  It's a work with a Latin-American flavor, snappy crisp pizzicatos, fiery fast passages and a (literally) foot-stomping final movement.

episodesByNumber.title: #2587: Kind of Afroblues
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to the blues that kind of wander someplace else.

episodesByNumber.title: #2588: The End of Cinematics
episodesByNumber.tease: PROGRAM # 2588, with Mikel Rouse First aired on Thurs.

episodesByNumber.title: #2589: New Releases Sept. 2006
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2590: Steve Reich @ 70
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, we take a look back at the career of composer Steve Reich on the occasion of his 70th birthday.

episodesByNumber.title: #2591: American Primitive
episodesByNumber.tease: “American Primitive,” the guitar-style associated with the late John Fahey, blends folk, blues, classical and Eastern music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2592: New Music for the Concert Hall
episodesByNumber.tease: The Warp Record label’s glitch-tronica and the avant brow-furrowing sounds of contemporary musical heavyweights lock horns in a symphonic smack-down for this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2593: Eye of the Frog
episodesByNumber.tease: Take an orchestra, add Hawaiian guitar, electric piano, Tang dynasty poetry, and a liberal helping of virtuosity on the bass clarinet, and you’ll have “Frog’s Eye,” the latest release from clarinetist/composer Evan Ziporyn.

episodesByNumber.title: #2594: New Music from Japan
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds offers a sampling of new music from Japan, with music for the koto (Japanese zither), biwa, Shomyo choir, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #2596: AllSteel String Quartets
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer and guitarist John King joins host John Schaefer on this edition of New Sounds to present his release, "AllSteel."  Earthy and blues-based, King’s music is intense, hard driving and at times breathtakingly beautiful.

episodesByNumber.title: #2597: Eric Whitacre's Cloudburst
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, the young American composer Eric Whitacre joins host John Schaefer to present music from his record “Cloudburst.”  His recorded music output so far is mostly dazzling unaccompanied vocal writing, where Whitacre’s original compositional voice is immediately obvious, in that he’s assimilated everything from prog rock to Mozart and Copland.

episodesByNumber.title: #2598: Music of the World
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, we’ll hear some women’s voices in world music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2599: Stephen Scott's New York Drones
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, the creator of the “bowed piano ensemble,” Stephen Scott, presents new music for bowed, plucked, hammered, and occasionally keyboard-driven piano.

episodesByNumber.title: #2600: October 2006 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2601: Musical Meditation
episodesByNumber.tease: “All of us have impermanence in common,” according to Meredith Monk.

episodesByNumber.title: #2602: Hornucopia
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to plenty of horns on this New Sounds program, including tunes by likes of the big-band progressive/experimental “downtown” Microscopic Septet from a brand new set of reissue CDs.

episodesByNumber.title: #2603: John the Revelator
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, it's a conversation with Phil Kline, the composer of the gripping and eloquent Zippo Songs, and the mobile, boombox-based holiday piece Unsilent Night.

episodesByNumber.title: #2604: Grim Musical Fairytales
episodesByNumber.tease: Operating under his band-pen name, “The Gothic Archies,” singer/songwriter Stephin Merritt released a compilation of theme songs called "The Tragic Treasury," one written for each of the 13 volumes of Lemony Snicket's "Series of Unfortunate Events" book series, plus a depressingly upbeat band theme song as well.

episodesByNumber.title: #2605: Remix-a-thon
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds lays down the new music remixes for this program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2606: Harmonic Presence
episodesByNumber.tease: Vocalist, composer, and overtone-singing pioneer David Hykes joins us on this New Sounds to preview new works for harmonic singing.

episodesByNumber.title: #2607: Barely Baroque
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear new arrangements of 17th and 18th century music, including J.S.

episodesByNumber.title: #2608: The Orchestra Rocks
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to Joby Talbot’s remarkable orchestrations of songs by The White Stripes - "Aluminium" - on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2609: A World in New York
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, three great women’s voices in World Music – all based in New York.

episodesByNumber.title: #2610: yes is a pleasant country
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to several different new music settings of poems by E.E.

episodesByNumber.title: #2611: New Music for Solo Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: There’s new music for solo piano by the likes of Seth Kaufman, whose piano sound draws on the dramatic gorges of the Finger lakes area of upstate New York, as well as New Orleans.

episodesByNumber.title: #2612: November 2006 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for John Schaefer to carefully separate the wheat from the chaff for this penultimate new releases show for this year.

episodesByNumber.title: #2613: John the Revelator, Live
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts at the World Financial Center, listen to the world premiere of “John the Revelator,” a mass for the 21st century by Phil Kline, and featuring the early music vocal group Lionheart and the electric string quartet Ethel.

episodesByNumber.title: #2614: New Sounds of Americana
episodesByNumber.tease: It's a liberal dose of Americana for this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2615: Tin Hat, the Quintet
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, we dip into Tin Hat's “The Sad Machinery of Spring."  The Tin Hat Trio has contracted (founding member Rob Burger left in 2004) and expanded again (its new members are Ben Goldberg, Zeena Parkins, and Ara Anderson) to become Tin Hat, a quintet that lives somewhere between composition and improvisation with one foot in jazz, and another in classical.

episodesByNumber.title: #2616: New Sounds of Old  Americana
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to old Americana recordings woven into tapestries of new music on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2617: New American Gamelan
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds brings new American music for Indonesian gamelan.

episodesByNumber.title: #2618: Near East New Music
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, sample some music from the Near East.

episodesByNumber.title: #2619: “Post-Production”
episodesByNumber.tease: Written for New Sounds Live, Irish composer Daniel Figgis’ “Post-Production” is his first major work in the United States and a world premiere.

episodesByNumber.title: #2620: New Music from the UK
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some new music from the UK on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2621: Christmas with John Fahey
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to Christmas music from the late guitarist John Fahey.

episodesByNumber.title: #2622: December 2006 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: John Schaefer picks through the bucketloads of CDs that have flooded his office to find a sampling of new releases worthy of showcasing in tonight's New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2624: Two by Two II
episodesByNumber.tease: There's a lot of music for unusual duos on this edition of New Sounds, including music from the gypsy-esque acoustic indie madness of A Hawk and a Hacksaw.

episodesByNumber.title: #2627: The 2006 New Sounds Top 10
episodesByNumber.tease: On this special episode of New Sounds, John Schaefer presents his annual, highly subjective, completely opinionated list of the ten best new-music releases of 2006.

episodesByNumber.title: #2628: The 2006 Listener Poll Show
episodesByNumber.tease: Here's the rebuttal to last night’s program where the listeners weigh in on the best new music releases of 2006.

episodesByNumber.title: #2633: Classical Perspectives
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, we'll have new look at the old masters – from Uri Caine's inventive and improvisatory take on Mozart, to the Kamikaze Ground Crew making sense of Karlheinz Stockhausen.

episodesByNumber.title: #2635: All Over the Musical Map (Encore Edition)
#2636: Philip Glass - A Private Reel
episodesByNumber.tease: Today, Philip Glass turns 70 - and to celebrate, this New Sounds program is full of music by the pioneering American composer.

episodesByNumber.title: #2637: Drumworld
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds offers music for an iron-smelting party alongside the ethereal breezes of bowed and rubbed percussion.

episodesByNumber.title: #2638: Global Pop
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the Caribbean-infused music - with a bit of French and West African roots for good measure - by Andy Palacio and the Garifuna Collective on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2639: Totally Tubular
episodesByNumber.tease: When you force air through a tube, sound results – whether that tube is an Australian didjeridoo, a length of plastic hose, a toy whirly, or the human throat.

episodesByNumber.title: #2640: New Music for Silent Films: Blackmail
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live/Silent Film series, the Alloy Orchestra performs their score to the Alfred Hitchcock movie "Blackmail" on keyboards, clarinet, accordion, percussion, and their famed “rack of junk,” at the World Financial Center.

episodesByNumber.title: #2642: Mardi Gras Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Today is Mardi Gras, and to celebrate, here's an hour of music inspired by the brass bands and Mardi Gras bands of New Orleans.

episodesByNumber.title: #2643: New Eastern Orthodox Singing
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to new choral music from Eastern Europe, or based on Eastern Orthodox singing on this edition of New Sounds, including John Tavener's Out of the Night, a gentle, simple setting for tenor and viola of the single word Alleluia.

episodesByNumber.title: #2644: New Music for Silent Films: The Eagle, The General
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live/Silent Film series, the Alloy Orchestra performs new music for the silent films “The Eagle” and “The General,” on keyboards, clarinet, accordion, percussion, and their famed “ton of junk,” at the World Financial Center.

episodesByNumber.title: #2645: New Acoustic Guitar
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to balmy fingerstyle guitar shapes and patterns from South African guitarist Guy Buttery on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2646: February 2007 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's the end of the month round-up.

episodesByNumber.title: #2647: Chatter and Soundscapes
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Paul Lansky's hiphop-inspired 'chatter' piece, on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2648: Music, Nature, and Technology
episodesByNumber.tease: "There is music in nature and nature in music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2649: New Music for Dance
episodesByNumber.tease: Originally presented as a multimedia dance piece choreographed by Art Bridgman and Myrna Packer, Ken Field's "Under the Skin" is an extended suite of pulsing studies for multiple saxophones, acoustic and electric bass, drums, and percussion.

episodesByNumber.title: #2650: 20-String Slinger
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music for the 20-string koto on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2651: New Jazz or Nu-Jazz?
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds asks the question and hears the answer from a variety of duos and trios.

episodesByNumber.title: #2652: The Bushy-Wushy Rag
episodesByNumber.tease: Phillip K.

episodesByNumber.title: #2653: Sidewalk Saints
episodesByNumber.tease: Slide guitarist Ben Bowen King resurrects a forgotten tradition of American Gospel guitarists of the deep South on this New Sounds program as we listen to music from his most recent release "Sidewalk Saints."  King is able to use his "gospel slide guitar" to 'preach' and 'wail in soulful beauty,' transporting you back to a lost chapter in American music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2654: The Doctor Is In
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer Nick Didkovsky, whose works range from his avant-rock band Doctor Nerve to electronically-altered chamber music, performs live music for laptop in the WNYC studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #2655: Border-Bashing Combinations
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to border-bashing world music from unlikely combinations of styles and places.

episodesByNumber.title: #2656: 2007 People's Commissioning Fund, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: From New Sounds Live, the Bang On A Can All-Stars perform with legendary vocalist/composer Meredith Monk, onstage at Merkin Hall.

episodesByNumber.title: #2657: Music for Women's Voices and Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by the ethereal and precise Trio Medieval on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2658: By the People, 2007
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, the Bang On A Can All-Stars perform world premieres of three new works commissioned by the people.

episodesByNumber.title: #2659: New Releases March 2007
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2660: Music from Ireland
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to jaw-dropping works by accordion wiz Niall Vallely, and music from the groundbreaking 70s Celtic Folk supergroup Planxty.

episodesByNumber.title: #2661: Opening the Chamber Music
episodesByNumber.tease: The distinctive and riveting saxophonist Ornette Coleman (arguably the pioneer of the free jazz movement), continuously defies categorization.

episodesByNumber.title: #2662: Trio Mediaeval Live
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts at Merkin Hall, listen to Norway’s Trio Mediaeval perform a set of early music, alongside contemporary works written for them, and arrangements of Nordic folksong.

episodesByNumber.title: #2663: Crash on in, Live!
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts at Merkin Hall, Irish composer Donnacha Dennehy presents the American debut of the large electro-acoustic Crash Ensemble,in a piece that also uses tradition Irish sean nos singing; plus a work for piano and live electronics.

episodesByNumber.title: #2664: Guitar Hero
episodesByNumber.tease: No, not the game.

episodesByNumber.title: #2665: Classics Remixed
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, DJ technology meets the concert hall as Miguel Kertsman remixes music from Mahler’s Symphony No.

episodesByNumber.title: #2666: New Music from Holland
episodesByNumber.tease: Home to one of Europe’s most active new music scenes, the small country of Holland has produced some big names in the music world.

episodesByNumber.title: #2667: Mostly Acoustic Impressions
episodesByNumber.tease: Curran's electroacoustic classic, "Songs and Views from the Magnetic Garden" combines chanting, singing, the bells of Rome, the lapping of the ocean, and many other sounds, to create something of an impressionist cast.

episodesByNumber.title: #2668: Inbetween Lines
episodesByNumber.tease: For this program, hear some electroacoustic ensemble music that falls between conventional lines of musical categories, always a good thing on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2669: Beats and Loops
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to music by Rich O’Meara and Richard McCandless for percussion and electronics.

episodesByNumber.title: #2670: West Africa Unwired
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some acoustic music from an area now known largely for its electric Afropop on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2671: April 2007 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for our monthly program of new releases.

episodesByNumber.title: #2672: Beyond Kronos
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, hear music by other West Coast new music ensembles.

episodesByNumber.title: #2674: Tango, New Sounds-style
episodesByNumber.tease: Tangos, both alleged and apparent, from the likes of Jocelyn Pook, the Penguin Café Orchestra, and Pete M Wyer.

episodesByNumber.title: #2675: On Earth, Peace
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to some choral music, including “On Earth, Peace,” a new mass by the choir Chanticleer featuring music by five different composers of different faiths.

episodesByNumber.title: #2676: Classical Musicians Rock It
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, classical pianist Christopher O’Riley plays the music of folk-rocker Nick Drake and classical guitarist Benjamin Verdery plays the music of Jimi Hendrix.

episodesByNumber.title: #2677: Mighty Winds
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the clarinet textures and eerie cello of Erik Friedlander's recent release Prowl, along with other arresting combinations of instruments like kora, saxophone and Slovenian music, all artfully woven together from Igor Leonardi.

episodesByNumber.title: #2678: Give the Drummer Some More
episodesByNumber.tease: Drummer/composers take center stage in music on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2679: New Folk Routes
episodesByNumber.tease: Names like "freak folk" and "folktronica" have been used to try to describe yet another generation of musicians falling under the sway of the British tradition of murder ballads, broadsides, and the like.

episodesByNumber.title: #2681: Turn up that Cello
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, hear music for processed, looped, and electrified cellos.

episodesByNumber.title: #2682: Cherchez la femme
episodesByNumber.tease: Contrary to the origins of the phrase, this New Sounds program showcases works celebrating the female voice.

episodesByNumber.title: #2683: World of Choral Music
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to choral music from around the world.

episodesByNumber.title: #2684: May 2007 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's the most wonderful time of the month - new releases! On this New Sounds program, listen to the pick of the piles.

episodesByNumber.title: #2685: Music With Narration
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, there's an hour of offbeat words and music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2686: World Music and Then Some
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, we'll hear from Nawal, a singer from the Comoros Islands, whose acoustic-accompanied songs and trance-inducing chants draw from her Sufi heritage and Indian Ocean island rhythms.

episodesByNumber.title: #2687: Music for Large Ensembles
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to some large-scale works by Lou Harrison and John Adams, among others.

episodesByNumber.title: #2688: Unexpected covers
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program is chock full of unexpected cover songs, including arrangements by classical pianist Christopher O'Riley and cellist Christopher Rex doing Radiohead's "Pyramid Song." Also, listen as Angelique Kidjo turns Ravel's "Bolero" into an Afropop song while The Persuasions offer a new take on the songs of U2.

episodesByNumber.title: #2689: Electronic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Irish composer Linda Buckley summons both electronic and acoustic forces and her works to date have used organ and multi-channel tape, prepared piano and Javanese Gamelan, among others.

episodesByNumber.title: #2690: Global Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear two living legends of the guitar playing world, John Williams and John Etheridge in a collaboration running the gamut from Bach to African folk music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2692: Kamikaze Ground Crew & Members
episodesByNumber.tease: Up on this New Sounds, there's brand new music from one of New York's all-star music groups - the Kamikaze Ground Crew.

episodesByNumber.title: #2694: New Releases June 2007
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2695: Roger Marsh 's Pierrot Lunaire
episodesByNumber.tease: English composer Roger Marsh has taken the cycle of poems known as "Pierrot Lunaire" - originally set by Arnold Schoenberg in a controversial, landmark work in the early 20th century - and created a new, extended set of songs based on these fevered, surreal poems.

episodesByNumber.title: #2696: Post Chamber Rock
episodesByNumber.tease: Brooklyn-based Slow Six makes new electroacoustic music with amplified violins, viola, cello, electric guitars, fender rhodes, piano, and software instruments and it's hard to describe:  Post-rock, post-chamber?  Hear some of their new record, "Nor'easter" on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2697: New Music from North Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, listen to works from Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, and Egypt, featuring Les Musiciens de Nil.

episodesByNumber.title: #2698: Cello Songs and Interludes
episodesByNumber.tease: Beginning with Nick Drake's haunting "Cello Song," we'll move on to songs by Donna McKevitt and Arthur Russell on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2699: New Music From the UK
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, hear works by violist/composer Jocelyn Pook, and her sometime collaborator composer, pianist and bandleader Jeremy Peyton-Jones.

episodesByNumber.title: #2700: Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, there's new music from Gaudi & Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan.

episodesByNumber.title: #2701: The Cloud of Unknowing
episodesByNumber.tease: The anonymous monk who penned "The Cloud of Unknowing, " a 14th century work of Christian mysticism, could not possibly have known that 700 years later, his work would be inspiring new music.

episodesByNumber.title: #2703: Bang on a Can 2007 Marathon
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from the 2007 version of the annual Bang On A Can Marathon.

episodesByNumber.title: #2704: Bang on a Can 2007 Marathon, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from the 2007 version of the annual Bang On A Can Marathon.

episodesByNumber.title: #2705: Bang on a Can 2007 Marathon, Part 3
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from the 2007 version of the annual Bang On A Can Marathon.

episodesByNumber.title: #2706: New Releases, July 2007
episodesByNumber.tease: It's the end of the month round-up.

episodesByNumber.title: #2707: Bang On A Can Marathon 2007, Extras
episodesByNumber.tease: From the 2007 Bang on a Can Marathon recorded live at the World Financial Center, hear David M Gordon's "Friction Systems," along with Marcello Zarvos' work "Arrival and Memory" on this edition of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2709: New Releases August 2007
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2710: 25 Years and Counting
episodesByNumber.tease: Laurie Anderson's unique and original "Big Science," a blend of smart sung-spoken lyrics and unsettling textures of music, came out of nowhere in 1982, with its skewed pop and minimalist themes teasing at the surreal and absurd.

episodesByNumber.title: #2711: Female Voice And Ensemble
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear some works for classical ensembles and the female voice.

episodesByNumber.title: #2712: Silence, Night and Dreams
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, listen to the latest work by Zbigniew Preisner called "Silence, Night and Dreams," featuring Madredeus singer Teresa Salgueiro.

episodesByNumber.title: #2713: Electronics Plus One
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds program, there's music from 5-string slinging Caryn Lin, who loops her electric violin into haunting and ethereal works.

episodesByNumber.title: #2714: Arabesques
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, take a taste of some Western works with a Near-Eastern tinge, including music from the likes of Berlin's jazz-rock-pop-classical band, 17 Hippies.

episodesByNumber.title: #2715: Brazil : a Classical Approach
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the sounds of Brazil as refracted through a classical lens on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2716: Extending the Folksong
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, we'll test the limits of the folksong tradition.

episodesByNumber.title: #2717: Hybrid Ensembles
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, sample some works by a few hybrid ensembles, including music from the Durham, NC based composers' collective Pulsoptional.

episodesByNumber.title: #2718: September 2007 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: It's that time of the month again for the new releases show on New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2719: Downtown, Everything's Waiting for You
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to some “downtown” versions of ska, folk, country, jazz, chamber music and blues.

episodesByNumber.title: #2720: Big Works, Big Ideas
episodesByNumber.tease: Relatively small excerpts from relatively large-scale works fill this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2721: Music for Prepared Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: Popularized by John Cage to approximate the sound of a percussion orchestra, the prepared piano has been used by composers like Arvo Pärt, Mikel Rouse, and of course Cage himself.

episodesByNumber.title: #2723: Revelation: Music Meet Math
episodesByNumber.tease: Guest Michael Harrison presents "Revelation," a major work for piano in the alternate tuning system known as "just intonation."  Today, rather than referring to a specific historical tuning, "just intonation" represents an almost infinite variety of tunings which are based upon the principles of whole number ratios.

episodesByNumber.title: #2724: Volans: a Committed Modernist
episodesByNumber.tease: Kevin Volans studied with Karlheinz Stockhausen and Mauricio Kagel in Cologne and later became Stockhausen’s teaching assistant.

episodesByNumber.title: #2725: Keyboard Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to an hour of keyboard music for this New Sounds Program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2726: New Americans: China
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, part of the New Americans series, we focus on foreign-born artists from China.

episodesByNumber.title: #2727: Classics Revisited
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to New Sounds-style reworkings of classical pieces on this program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2728: Poetry and Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Poetry and music trip merrily together off into the sunset on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2729: New Americans: Africa

episodesByNumber.tease: Asian Fusion is not just a cuisine.

episodesByNumber.title: #2732: New Americans: Eastern Europe
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a brand new release from Kitka, the all-women's ensemble who specialize in Balkan music (in collaboration with the Ukrainian-born singer and composer Mariana Sadovska).

episodesByNumber.title: #2733: Songs From Around the World
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by La Mar Enfortuna, the Sephardic side project of legendary noir rock group Elysian Fields, as they explore lost or forgotten music from the 11th to the 16th century, with exotic melodies and instruments.

episodesByNumber.title: #2734: New Music from West Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music from the Tuareg band Tinariwen on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2735: Tibetan Buddhist-Based Film Scores
episodesByNumber.tease: Western film scores built around the sounds of Tibetan Buddhism, including “Kundun” by Philip Glass and “Fate of the Lhapa” by William Susman are featured on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #2736: New Americans V: The Far East
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Kyaw Kyaw Naing, the master of the pat waing (a traditional Burmese drum-circle instrument).

episodesByNumber.title: #2737: Electroacoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen for some electroacoustic music on this edition of the show by none other than So Percussion, the tube, block, and pipe-beating quartet of drummers, from their latest "Amid the Noise."  Plus, hear a work from Martin Bresnick, his "Fantasia on a Theme by Willie Dixon."  The marimba player on said recording, Jason Treuting, happens to be a founding member of So Percussion.

episodesByNumber.title: #2738: Bang a Gong
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample some of the music of New Zealand composer/entertainer Gareth Farr on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2739: "Extended" Chamber Music
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds takes a broad view of chamber music on this program, where we’ll hear from the percussionist Susie Ibarra on kulintang (Filippino gongs related to Indonesian gamelan), as well as animal sounds recorded on the island of Bali, together with a string quartet.

episodesByNumber.title: #2740: European Keyboard-based Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some recent releases of keyboard-based ensemble pieces with electronics on this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #2741: New Americans: Latin America
episodesByNumber.tease: We focus on works from Latin America, including music by Argentinian-born Osvaldo Golijov.

episodesByNumber.tease: Hear traditional and contemporary holiday songs from the Arab Christian, Irish folk, and Medieval European traditions.

episodesByNumber.title: #2750: World Music with Horns
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some Jewish-Cuban jazz with horns from "Odessa/Havana" by   trumpeter, composer and long-time leader of the Flying Bulgar Klezmer Band David Buchbinder along with music that celebrates the the elusive Jewish community of Cuba by Roberto Rodriguez.

episodesByNumber.title: #2751: Concert Works From the Clubs
episodesByNumber.tease: Tim Brady and the five member Brisbane, Australia-based group Topology share a passion for the intimacy and immediacy of small ensemble music and getting on stage and playing it like there’s no tomorrow.

episodesByNumber.title: #2752: New Soundtracks
episodesByNumber.tease: For the score to “The Kite Runner,” Spanish composer Alberto Iglesias drew inspiration from Afghan music, while drawing a bit on Pakistani and Persian music as well, bringing in an Iranian zither here, a wailing electric guitar there, and the haunting vocals of Iran-born, U.S.-based singer Sussan Deyhim.

episodesByNumber.title: #2753: The 2007 New Sounds Top 10
episodesByNumber.tease: On this special episode of New Sounds, John Schaefer presents his annual, highly subjective, completely opinionated list of the ten best new-music releases of 2007.

episodesByNumber.tease: Here's the rebuttal to last night’s program where the listeners weigh in on the best new music releases of 2007.

episodesByNumber.title: #2755: Chamber-Rock
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some Chamber-rock from the Nels Cline Singers (an instrumental group), whose record "Draw Breath" features San Francisco Bay Area rhythm section aces Devin Hoff on acoustic bass and Scott Amendola on drumset, percussion, and live electronics/loops/treatments.

episodesByNumber.title: #2756: Indo-Electronica
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, there’s music that marries the grooves of modern electronica to traditional songs and dances of India.

episodesByNumber.title: #2757: New Americans: The Middle East
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Israeli-born musicians like composer Anat Fort and cellist Maya Beiser, and Palestinian-born oud player Simon Shaheen.

episodesByNumber.title: #2758: O Berimbau
episodesByNumber.tease: (ONLINE ONLY) Hear new music for the berimbau, a single-string, bow-shaped percussion from Brazil, in works by Nana Vasconcelos, Cyro Baptista, Celso Fonseca, Ramiro Musotto,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #2759: Voices Only
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to a capella singing from the Armenian-American trio Zulal (their name means "clear water") from their release called "Notes to a Crane." We’ll hear selections from that, along with medieval ballads from England, France and Norway sung by the Norwegian early music group, Trio Medieval.

episodesByNumber.title: #2760: African Blues
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program is all about bluesy music from the continent that invented it - Africa.

episodesByNumber.title: #2761: Music for Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: On this program, we’ll hear music by avant-cellist Rufus Cappadocia, whose five-string electric cello asks, “bass, how low can you go?” by extending the cello’s low end, and creates new sounds through amplification.

episodesByNumber.title: #3326: As the World Drones
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to an hour of music built atop a drone, with music from Ergo, to traditional music of Georgia, to the medieval music of Hildegard von Bingen.

episodesByNumber.title: #3327: Live from Ecstatic Music 2012: Dan Deacon, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, we'll listen to some highlights from the 2012 Ecstatic Music Festival, featuring music by electronic rocker  &  composer Dan Deacon. (Part 1 of 2).

episodesByNumber.title: #3328: Live from Ecstatic Music 2012: Dan Deacon, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to part two of the New Sounds Live/Ecstatic Music Festival concert with Dan Deacon from 2012, complete with classical instrument dance party set to a wooden block click track.

episodesByNumber.title: #3329: Extended Covers
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear new compositions that take as their starting point pre-existing pieces of music, like music based on works by Thelonious Monk or David Bowie.

episodesByNumber.title: #3330: Devotional Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to devotional songs from the late great Qawwali singer Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan, as well as music recorded at a South Indian temple complex where both Muslims and Hindus pray.

episodesByNumber.title: #3331: Bang on a Can at 25
episodesByNumber.tease: For more than 25 years, Bang on a Can has been a force in new music. The three co-founders join this New Sounds to celebrate a quarter-century of "Big Beautiful Dark and Scary."

episodesByNumber.title: #3333: Global Guitars & Things
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, sample a globetrotting set of acoustic music with guitar as the starting point, with music by Stephane Wrembel, Ablaye Cissoko, and Wu Man.

episodesByNumber.title: #3334: Blast the Horns
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to the blistering horns of party bands from the world over, with Afro-pop from Ghanaian highlife veteran Ebo Taylor to the Chicago-based Mucca Pazza.

episodesByNumber.title: #3335: Motion and Stasis
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds explores music that plays with ideas of texture, drone and space. Hear music by composer/drummer Erland Dahlen and music for large sheets of metal, called steel cellos.

episodesByNumber.title: #3336: Poetry Set to Music, I
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program, the first of a two-part series, explores poetry in song, including Appalachian blues music recorded by Martha Redbone set to works of William Blake, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3337: Poetry Set to Music, II
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds is part 2 of a series of poetry set to music, not limited to English-language poets.  Hear texts by Persian poet/mystic Rumi set by Philip Glass and Pablo Neruda poems.

episodesByNumber.title: #3338: "Glitch" Music
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program explores the impact that the subgenre known as "glitch" music has had on the new music world.  Listen to Daniel Wohl's piece, "Glitch," and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3339: Recent Chamber & Concert Works
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds offers music from a few of the eight member Common Sense Composers Collective (San Francisco/New York City-based) and music by Canadian composer and guitarist Tim Brady.

episodesByNumber.title: #3340: Music For Opposable Thumbs
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to an hour of music involving the thumb piano for this New Sounds program, from a gentle song by Arthur Russell, interpreted by Jens Lekman to the Kronos Quartet,and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3341: European Postminimalism
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear loads of European music from composers responding to American minimalism, including music from Swiss composer Nik Bartsch's Ronin, and Italy's Ludovico Einaudi.

episodesByNumber.title: #3342: Music Out of Time
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music made on old instruments, and older music in positively modern settings on this New Sounds, like vocal group Orlando Consort with jazz rockers Perfect Houseplants,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3343: Thinking Big
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear songwriters take ambitious ideas and go for the orchestral  &  operatic on this New Sounds show, with music from songwriter, producer, performer  &  composer Jherek Bischoff  &  others.

episodesByNumber.title: #3344: Ambient Electroacoustic Works
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, sample some recent ambient electro-acoustic music from the likes of New Jersey-based composer Frances White, Canadian producer Loscil (Scott Morgan), and Fazio.

episodesByNumber.title: #3346: Glass-y Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear fragile and glassy music on this New Sounds program, including low-fi, 1-bit electronic music by New York-based composer Tristan Perich, and Michael Hearst of One Ring Zero.

episodesByNumber.title: #3347: On a Large Scale
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds show, hear large-scale works, including a chamber poem by Dylan Mattingly depicting Amelia Earhart's final flight, a jazz/flamenco suite by Alexis Cuadrado  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3348: "Underground" Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music made in or about the underground – catacombs, cisterns, cellars- on this New Sounds. Hear works by Ken Field, Paul Dresher, and Q2 Music's own Hannis Brown.

episodesByNumber.title: #3349: From the North
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, head to the north with music from Scandinavian composers, and works from Iceland.

episodesByNumber.title: #3350: Meetings of Two Tectonic Plates
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to some of the remarkable and unexpected collaboration between concert violinist/improviser Hilary Hahn  &  the German composer/keyboard player, Hauschka.

episodesByNumber.title: #3351: World Music Mixtures
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program mixes it up with a traditional Macedonian folksong performed by Polish band with African name – Dikanda, and some Balkan brass band music from Boban Markovic.

episodesByNumber.title: #3353: Voices and Soundscapes
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from the duo, White Canvas, whose world of sound moves between song, avant-garde and improvisation, with vocal lines over guitar-based soundscapes.

episodesByNumber.title: #3354: Afrofunk, Afrojazz & Afropop
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the Ghanaian-rooted Afrofunk band KonKoma, (now based in the U.K.), along with recent releases and/or reissues of music from South, East, and West Africa.

episodesByNumber.title: #3355: Piano Plus...
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear music from the duo Moon Ate the Dark, along with other music for piano and electronics.

episodesByNumber.title: #3356: Tangled Web of Fiddling
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to the shared musical territory between Celtic, Scandinavian, "early music,"  &  Appalachian fiddle music.

episodesByNumber.title: #3357: Global Collaborations
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds program highlights some unexpected global collaborations- including but not limited to- Uzbeki bluegrass, Mardi Gras marching bands with Argentinean tango flair,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3358: British Choral Works
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear choral works by three contemporary English composers on this New Sounds program, all of which invite comparisons between spiritual and mystical realms and that of reality on Earth.

episodesByNumber.title: #3359: Music Based on Earlier Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works based on earlier songs for this New Sounds, including Bernard Hoey's "I Am Petrified," based on Queen's "We Will Rock You," and music by Don Byron based on Marvin Gaye songs.

episodesByNumber.title: #3360: Reflections of China
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to music inspired by the image of the plum blossom, China, or variations on the plum blossom.

episodesByNumber.title: #3361: Hearing Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from composer John McGuire based on the sounds of one soprano voice (his wife) multiplied, refracted and superimposed to create a choral fantasia.

episodesByNumber.title: #3362: New Sounds of Gospel Trombone
episodesByNumber.tease: Dig into the instrumental gospel tradition, centered around the trombone, with music from the McCollough Sons of Thunder, Jacob Garchik, the Hypnotic Brass Ensemble and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3363: Musical Machines
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the insistent rhythms  &  repetitions of acoustic instruments on this New Sounds, with solo music by Kris Davis, music by Arnold Dreyblatt, Switzerland's Nik Bartsch,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3365: Post-Rock 101
episodesByNumber.tease: Explore music by some of the seminal post-rock bands on this edition of New Sounds, including music by the late guitarist/bassist Jason Noble (Rachel's,Young Scamels), among others.

episodesByNumber.title: #3366: John Barleycorn & Other Folksongs
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new versions of old English folksongs, with several dramatic takes of the traditional English song "John Barleycorn (Must Die),"plus the traditional song "Little Margaret,"  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3367: Guitars Plus
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to pieces combining guitar(s) and strings, including music by guitar virtuoso Kaki King that features the string quartet ETHEL, music from Bill Frisell,  &  NY-based Keeril Makan.

episodesByNumber.title: #3368: World Multiples
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a load of border-crossing collaborations for this New Sounds, including a danceable Bhangra tune by a Budapest-based Balkan brass band,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3369: Some Folks Singing
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some songs and the singers who sing them, including the record by Neneh Cherry and Scandinavian jazz trio, the Thing, and Tin Hat's settings of poetry by e.e. cummings.

episodesByNumber.title: #3370: Abstract Soundscapes
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to some abstract soundscapes from Poland, from Berlin via an Icelandic composer, and from Brooklyn-based musicians as well.

episodesByNumber.title: #3371: Unusual Jazz
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear tunes that are hard to pin down, and incorporate all sorts of jazz, like Les Rhinocéros' ambient jazz-rock, Artichaut orkestra, Portuguese folk-jazz by Carlos Bica, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3372: Score One for Dance
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample music from unusual dance scores on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #3374: Philip Glass: Music of Constant Change
#3375: New & Old Electronic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to electronic music both old and new from the now Hawaii-based K. Leime, as well as a electronic music, jazz and new music blend in a piece from Michael William Gilbert,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3376: Indonesian Inspiration
episodesByNumber.tease: This New Sounds brings music by Canadian composer Vivian Fung inspired Indonesian gamelan, along with other works by westerners that look to that archipelago's music.

episodesByNumber.title: #3377: Make the World Shake (Afropop, New & Old)
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to Congolese band Staff Benda Bilili, Senegalese singer Ablaye Thiossanea, a reissue from Nigerian Tunji Oyelana, and music from different parts of Africa.

episodesByNumber.title: #3378: Drones, Sometimes Words
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to acoustic drones, electronic drones, overtone singing  &  sometimes words, with music by New York-based composer Kitty Brazelton, the late William Duckworth, and Annie Gosfield.

episodesByNumber.title: #3379: Tuff Strum
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to "Cello Multitracks" by Gabriel Prokofiev. The four-part suite calls for nine cellos, as realized by the technologically skilled cellist Peter Gregson, (yep, on all nine parts.)

episodesByNumber.title: #3380: Music for Alternative Tunings
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works by American composer Mathew Rosenblum influenced in part by a love of Javanese music, Sonic Youth, and by the music of LaMonte Young on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #3381: Altered Sounds of Acoustic Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear acoustic guitar music that has been altered or augmented, either by splicing tape, via electronic sounds, or computer trickery of some kind, like Michael Hedges  &  Dominic Frasca.

episodesByNumber.title: #3382: Music That Revolves Around Poetry
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a new take on Vivaldi's The Four Seasons, with the composer's own poems in new settings by Uri Caine, sung in modern translation by Theo Bleckmann,  &  Korean poetry set by Sunny Kim.

episodesByNumber.title: #3383: New Sounds of Bluegrass & Americana
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music made by banjos, dulcimers, and other traditional Americana instruments, from Norwegian banjo player Stian Carstensen, hammered dulcimer player Dan Joseph,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3385: 1-bit Workout
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to Tristan Perich's 1-bit electronics together with Mariel Roberts' cello for a driving, hypnotic, and exhilarating work, "Formations." Plus, music from the classic "Dune" score.

episodesByNumber.title: #3386: John Cage: City Circus, Program XIII
#3387: Baroque Dance Forms
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to a suite of pieces by Caroline Shaw, a member of vocal ensemble Roomful of Teeth. Note: all the movements in her Pulitzer Prize-winning suite are named for baroque dance forms.

episodesByNumber.title: #3388: With Cellist Maya Beiser
episodesByNumber.tease: The innovative cellist Maya Beiser joins us in the studio to present selections from her collaborative record with Michael Harrison called "Time Loops."

episodesByNumber.title: #3389: Musical Delay Tactics
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music made with tape loops, digital loops, and/or digital delay, including works from Ingram Marshall  &  Moby, along with a dreamy guitarscape from Evan Caminiti  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3390: "Psychedelic Appalachia"
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear fingerstyle guitar music with a wash of drones - "Psychedelic Appalachia"- from steel string shredder Daniel Bachman. Plus, music by Matt Bauer, Fern Knight, and John Fahey.

episodesByNumber.title: #3391: African Roots
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to Afrobeat party-band Antibalas, modeled after the great Fela Kuti's Africa 70 band. Plus, music from South African trumpeter Hugh Masekela  &  pianist Abdullah Ibrahim,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3392: New York Indie Classical
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample music from many "indie classical" musicians and composers on this New Sounds, from people like Ted Hearne, Missy Mazzoli, and Christopher Cerrone, to name a few.

episodesByNumber.title: #3393: Light Works
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some electronic music by two German composers, both dealing with Light: Karlheinz Stockhausen's "Licht" and Hendrik Weber aka Pantha du Prince's Elements of Light.

episodesByNumber.title: #3394: After the Storm
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Carla Kihlstedt/Matthias Bossi, inspired by Bossi's mother's recollection of the Hurricane Carol's 1954 destruction, plus an excerpt from Ted Hearne's "Katrina Ballads."

episodesByNumber.title: #3395: The Minimalist Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some music that shows the influence of the repetitive musical language developed by Philip Glass, Steve Reich, Terry Riley, et al. – "Minimalism."

episodesByNumber.title: #3396: Orchestral Pop
episodesByNumber.tease: Orchestral pop in various guises, including music from the reclusive Scott Walker, from his release "Bish Bosch," where he uses the sounds of samurai swords and falling marbles.

episodesByNumber.title: #3397: When Words Don't Matter
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a hypnotic work of vocal layers from electronic duo Matmos, "Just Waves," based on their own telepathic experiments, music from Nico Muhly, Joan LaBarbara, Meredith Monk,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3398: Collaborative Producers
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by producers  &  composers, like L.A.-based electronic music producer Deru  &  English composer Joby Talbot, and Anglo-Ethiopian music by producer Dan Harper  &  Invisible System.

episodesByNumber.title: #3399: A Young Person's Guide to the Orchestra - and Tubular Bells
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some of Mike Oldfield's "Tubular Bells" where Vivian Stanshall formally announces each instrument as it joins the mix at the end of the piece, and more for this New Sounds.
tags: young person's guide to the orchestra

episodesByNumber.title: #3400: Traditional Folk Music Gone Global
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some contemporary works based on folk traditions of America, Albania,  &  Armenia, from composer Eve Beglarian, duduk master Djivan Gasparyan  &  Albanian-Swiss singer Elina Duni.

episodesByNumber.title: #3401: Drones
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music made with drones including lute player Jozef van Wissem in collaboration with Jim Jarmusch, music from Nico Muhly, and ambient music from Brian Eno.

episodesByNumber.title: #3403: Mostly Wordless Vocal Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear mostly wordless vocal pieces, from Philip Glass to Roomful of Teeth, and vocalist and tape loop manipulator, Juliana Barwick.

episodesByNumber.title: #3404: David Lang's "love fail"
episodesByNumber.tease: Using ancient and modern texts, excerpts from Wagner's Tristan und Isolde, and other sources, Lang retells a universal love story, both found and unfulfilled.

episodesByNumber.title: #3405: The Cajun Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Cajun music from Beausoleil, Last Forever, Darol Anger, Michael Doucet, Philip Aaberg, Penguin Café Orchestra, and the "Beasts of the Southern Wild soundtrack."

episodesByNumber.title: #3406: Another Side of the Trumpet
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the trumpet used in new, nontraditional ways on this episode of New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #3408: Strings and Drones
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, droning chords provide the foundation for improvisation, melody, and exploration from string instruments.

episodesByNumber.title: #3409: Where We Live
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from itsnotyouitsme, where Grey McMurray is the guitar-playing half and Caleb Burhans is the violin-playing half. Also, pieces from their independent projects and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3410: Recomposed by Max Richter: Vivaldi
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer Max Richter has taken apart Vivaldi's original set of violin concertos, "The Four Seasons," and reconfigured the components while reclaiming the work as a beautiful object.

episodesByNumber.title: #3411: Now is the Winter of our Discontent
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program listen to songs about winter, as we welcome spring from San Francisco-based finger-style guitarist Sean Smith to the minimalist cool of the Geoff Smith Band.

episodesByNumber.title: #3412: A Very New Sounds Christmas (Eve)
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music of the season from Respect Sextet, twisted songs by The Real Tuesday Weld  &  Sufjan Stevens, plus an arrangement of Sir John Tavener's "The Lamb," with the JACK Quartet.

episodesByNumber.title: #3415: Guy Klucevsek and Polka From the Fringe
episodesByNumber.tease: Accordionist and composer Guy Klucevsek stops by to chat about and listen to "Polka From the Fringe," 29 tracks for accordion by Klucevsek and 27 other composers.

episodesByNumber.title: #3416: Soldier Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer and founder of the new music group Newspeak, David T. Little, joins John Schaefer to present selections from his hour-long multimedia one-man opera, "Soldier Songs."

episodesByNumber.title: #3417: John Schaefer's Completely Opinionated Top Ten of 2012
#3418: The 2012 New Sounds Listener Poll Results
#3419: Electroacoustic Chamber Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to electro-acoustic chamber music, including double and triple-layered pianos from Tim Hecker, parapsychology-inspired music from Matmos, and music by Sylvain Chaveau.

episodesByNumber.title: #3420: Around the Globe in 59 Minutes
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to Bengali, Ethiopian, &  Senegalese music, plus sounds from around the world.  Punjabi wedding music meets New Orleans Brass bands in music of Brooklyn-based Red Baraat  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3421: Dramatic Works
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from Wires Under Tension, selections from Missy Mazzoli's dreamlike "pocket opera," along with music from the Paul Bailey Ensemble, and music by Philip Glass.

episodesByNumber.title: #3422: For Whom the Bells Toll
episodesByNumber.tease: From a multi-ton carillon to a tricycle bell, hear songs featuring bells or about bells, including music by Pantha du Prince  &  the Norwegian percussion ensemble Bell Laboratory,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3423: Art Songs: Opera, Dance & Others
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to unusual art songs from the likes of Mikel Rouse, Clogs, Corey Dargel, and Carla Kihlstedt  &  Matthias Bossi.

episodesByNumber.title: #3424: Multiple Motoric Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from Robert Fripp  &  his League of Crafty Guitarists, music from French guitar trio Philharmonie,  &  Steve Reich's "Electric Counterpoint," as performed by Pat Metheny.

episodesByNumber.title: #3425: Music for Viola
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new works for viola, viola  &  electronics,  &  viola d'amore, including music by Missy Mazzoli, "Tooth And Nail," which appears on violist Nadia Sirota's record, "Baroque."

episodesByNumber.title: #3427: Neither Pop Nor Art Song
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from Sarah Kirkland Snider from her gorgeous work, "Penelope," feat. Shara Worden, songs from David Sylvian, Evelyn Glennie featuring Bjork,  &  How to Destroy Angels.

episodesByNumber.title: #3428: New Sounds Live: Carla Kihlstedt & ICE
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the world premiere concert of violinist  &  vocalist Carla Kihlstedt's "At Night We Walk In Circles And Are Consumed by Fire," featuring ICE (International Contemporary Ensemble.)

episodesByNumber.title: #3429: With Bill Ryan & Billband Members
episodesByNumber.tease: Meet composer/conductor Bill Ryan, director of the Grand Valley State University (GVSU) New Music Group, who recorded Steve Reich's masterwork, "Music for 18 Musicians,"  &  his Billband.

episodesByNumber.title: #3430: New Music for Brass
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music for brass, some martial, some big band jazz, and music by David Byrne inspired by the Dirty Dozen Brass Band of New Orleans, and more on this New Sounds Program.

episodesByNumber.title: #3431: Frontiers of Flamenco
episodesByNumber.tease: In this episode of New Sounds, we'll look beyond flamenco, experiencing collisions of Indian classical music and flamenco, along with other flamenco blends.

episodesByNumber.title: #3432: Piano Impressions
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to works for piano, like a disquieting nocturne by Christopher Cerrone, performed by pianist/composer Timo Andres, chased by a work by Timo Andres himself,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3433: Atmospheric Percussion Works
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear concert music from New York luminary, Joseph Byrd, as performed by ACME, featuring Timo Andres, the looped hockety rhythms of the Portico Quartet  &  other percussive soundscapes.

episodesByNumber.title: #3434: Minimalism Meets English/Irish Folk Music
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds program, listen to music that is able to combine pattern music with folk music of the British Isles, both England and Ireland.

episodesByNumber.title: #3435: New Sounds Live with Clogs, Orchestra for the New Century
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live Concert Series, hear some new music by indie chamber band Clogs in trio form, along with music from the trio Causing a Tiger.

episodesByNumber.title: #3437: Musical Portraits of the English Landscape
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to musical portraits of rolling hills  &  little lanes of the English countryside,  &  the English fascination with landscape. Hear music by Brian Eno, Mike Oldfield,  &  Jocelyn Pook

episodesByNumber.title: #3438: Atmospheric Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to atmospheric songs with unusual textures  &  unexpected sounds from Brian Eno, Antony  &  the Johnsons, Irish singer Iarla Ó Lionáird, a murder ballad from Sam Amidon, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3439: A Musical Babel
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear unlikely cross-cultural music with “BabEl,” - oud & North African percussion by sax player Uri Gurvich, a Portuguese klezmer band, the Belgium-Burkina Faso Zita Swoon Group & more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3440: Electroacoustic: Going for Baroque
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear electroacoustic works featuring strings; viola, cello, and violin, featuring violist Nadia Sirota and chamber music by Anna Clyne involving a music box that plays "Sakura."

episodesByNumber.title: #3441: Electronic Places
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear electronic works from Iceland, Germany,  &  America, all about specific places: Copenhagen, Milan, Borodino, Moscow, the Okeefenokee Swamp,  &  an American piece about a French zoo.

episodesByNumber.title: #3442: Variations on Keith Jarrett's Koln Concert
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, we'll hear Jarrett's original Koln Concert, Trzcinsk's new interpretation, and other recent works based on the concert.

episodesByNumber.title: #3443:  Piano Grooves
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to a few groove-based pieces for piano and electronics, including recent music from Jace Clayton (aka DJ Rupture) and Dawn of Midi, who play entirely acoustic instruments.

episodesByNumber.title: #3444: Moody Works for Trumpet or Sax
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to moody nocturnal works that grow out of the jazz tradition like music by Wadada Leo Smith  &  a collaboration by Afro-Cuban pianist Omar Sosa  &  Italian trumpeter Paolo Fresu.

episodesByNumber.title: #3445: New Sounds Live: Bang on a Can PCF Concert 2013
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some of 2013 Bang on a Can People's Commissioning Fund Concert, part of the Ecstatic Music Festival. Hear works by Anna Clyne, Dan Deacon, Paula Matthusen  &  Johann Johannsson.
tags: bang on a can people's commissioning fund

episodesByNumber.title: #3446: Choral Music Without Words
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear choral works that make use of a choir for color and texture, from violinist and composer Timba Harris, vocal octet Roomful of Teeth, and the ensemble New York Polyphony.

episodesByNumber.title: #3447: New Sounds Live from Merkin Hall 2013
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works from the 2013 Ecstatic Music Festival at Merkin Hall, including "TREMS" by looping orchestrator Tyondai Braxton, with field recordings of slot machines made in Queens  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3449: Virtuosic Works for Winds and Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, sample virtuoso works for piano and/or saxophone, including duet music from saxophonist Charles Lloyd and pianist Jason Moran, music from Colin Stetson,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3450: Global Jewish Music
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music from unexpected places, like Cuban-Jewish music from Roberto Rodriguez, a DJ collaboration from Socalled, along with some Afrobeat-Jewish party music by Zion80,  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3451: Music from Sub-Saharan Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from Niger, Mali, Senegal and Uganda including selections from "Delicious Peace," a collection of songs by interfaith fair trade coffee farmers from Uganda  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3452:  European Electroacoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Music from a compilation of rare instrumental works by Irish composers and electronica artists/musicians such as Olafur Arnalds, Jocelyn Pook, and Nils Frahm.

episodesByNumber.title: #3453: New Sound of Early Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Take a new look at early music, with selections by the Luce Trio involving Indian Shruti box, saxophone, electric guitar  &  bass plus Gregorian chant remixed by New York Polyphony  &  more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3454: Brass Around the World
episodesByNumber.tease: Enjoy an hour of works for brass, from the 19 piece French band Bigre! and sample some of "Brooklyn Babylon" from Darcy James Argue's Secret Society, (only 17 pieces strong.)

episodesByNumber.title: #3455: Big Sounds, Small Ensembles
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to smaller groups who are capable of large expansive sounds, like music from Norwegian sax player  &  composer Marius Neset from a gorgeous folk-infused and jazzy opus, "Birds."

episodesByNumber.title: #3456: The Guitar as an African Instrument
episodesByNumber.tease: Maybe the guitar wasn't originally an African instrument, but it certainly has become one. Hear music from the late Cameroonian guitarist Francis Bebey, guitarist John Williams and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3458: Qawwali and Qawwali-based Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some Sufi devotional music, known as Qawwali, which is mostly Pakastani  &  usually sung by men. Listen to the late great Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan  &  Party in the WNYC studio from 1993.

episodesByNumber.title: #3459: Post-Minimalist Keyboard Works
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to keyboard-centric post-minimalist works by the likes of Daniel Wohl, film music by Clint Mansell, and a multi-part work by Nico Muhly from his "Drones" release.

episodesByNumber.title: #3460: African Crossover Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to musicians from Belgium, Switzerland, the U.K., and Italy working together with musicians living in Kenya, Senegal, Mali, Ethiopia and Burkina Faso.

episodesByNumber.title: #3461: Alone at My Wedding
episodesByNumber.tease: There's party music from the Balkans, Near East, and Central Asia - it's all here - from the frantic and sweaty pop that soundtracks celebrations in Egypt, to Punjabi wedding music.

episodesByNumber.title: #3463: Bowed String Multiples
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music for multiple layers of violin, of viola, and of cello on this New Sounds show, including music by cellist Zoe Keating.

episodesByNumber.title: #3464: Gamelan-Inspired Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some gamelan-influenced music, complete with interlocking metallic percussion orchestras from just about everywhere but Indonesia on this New Sounds show.

episodesByNumber.title: #3465: World Music From Europe
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to world music from Europe, much of it involving northern European musicians looking south towards the Mediterranean, North Africa, and the Near East for this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #3467: Music from Central Asia
episodesByNumber.tease: On this New Sounds, hear music from the steppes of central Asia, featuring Mongolian group Hanggai, the overtone singing of Huun Huur Tu together with Brooklyn's Hazmat Modine, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3468: With Ludovico Einaudi
episodesByNumber.tease: The Italian keyboardist and composer Ludovico Einaudi joins John Schaefer to present selections from his record, "In a Time Lapse," and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3469: Link to the Old Style Via Donnacha Dennehy
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, John Schaefer catches up with the Irish composer Donnacha Dennehy, who speaks about his musical theatre piece, "the Hunger," based on the events of the Irish famine.

episodesByNumber.title: #3470: New Music Based on Gospel, Spirituals & Folk Hymns
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to works inspired by gospel, early folk hymns, spirituals, and shape note singing, including music by Jaimeo Brown and Colin Stetson on this New Sounds program.

episodesByNumber.title: #3471: Music from the Armenian Diaspora
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to works from the Armenian diaspora on this New Sounds program. There's lots of music for the duduk, the plaintive reed instrument made of apricot wood, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #3472: New Music from Bass Players
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music by bass players for orchestral double bass, electric bass guitar, and Michael Manring's hyperbass for this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #3473: New Music for Thumb Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to new music using various forms of the African thumb piano for this New Sounds, featuring works by Dutch cellist Ernst Reijseger, and the Norwegian Karl Seglem, among others.

episodesByNumber.title: #3475: Music Based on East Asian Stories
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds listen to ambitious works inspired by East Asian storytelling, including music based the classic Chinese epic tale – "Monkey," as retold and done up by Damon Albarn.

episodesByNumber.title: #3476: Dowland's Tears
