episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Americans recreating sounds from elsewhere: Arab music, Indonesian music, Moroccan music, or Ethiopian music by Anbessa Orchestra, Innov Gnawa, and David Yazbek.

episodesByNumber.title: #4102: With Japanese Vocal Performer and Producer Hatis Noit
episodesByNumber.tease: Get to know Japanese vocalist and producer Hatis Noit, whose record, "Illogical Dance," explores the visceral power of the human voice (recorded on location at Erased Tapes, in London.)

episodesByNumber.title: #4103: With Julianna Barwick & Jacqueline Horner-Kwiatek
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works by female voices that go to extremes of western music, with Jacqueline Horner-Kwiatek (Anonymous 4)  &  founder of ModernMedieval along with composer/vocalist Julianna Barwick.

episodesByNumber.title: #4104: Altered Piano Sounds
episodesByNumber.tease: From strummed piano strings and hitting the piano body, to prepared piano  &  electronically altered sounds, hear music by George Crumb as well as works by Kelly Moran and Poppy Ackroyd.

episodesByNumber.title: #4105: Something Is Happening with Shabaka Hutchings
episodesByNumber.tease: Recorded in London, meet reed player, composer, and bandleader, Shabaka Hutchings (Sons of Kemet, The Comet Is Coming, and Shabaka and the Ancestors) who will not be limited to "jazz."

episodesByNumber.title: #4106: With Pianist And Composer Ed Pastorini, In-Studio
episodesByNumber.tease: New York singer/pianist Ed Pastorini has an unusual songwriting approach which falls between pop  &  art song, jazz,  &  improvisation. He plays some wonderfully strange new songs in-studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #4107: Suspending Time With Drones
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music recorded on location in recent years from the annual 24-hour Drone at Basilica Hudson featuring Arone Dyer's Dronechoir, guitar layers of drone from Noveller,  &  Iva Bittova.

episodesByNumber.title: #4108: New Releases, April 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear April new releases with music by cellist/composer Clarice Jensen, Belgian composer Christina Vantzou, and music by Kokoroko Afrobeat Collective from the "We Out Here" compilation.

episodesByNumber.title: #4109: New Sounds Live: ModernMedieval and Julianna Barwick
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live/Ecstatic Music Festival series, hear a premiere of new works for vocal super-group called ModernMedieval, and music by Julianna Barwick, separately and together.

episodesByNumber.title: #4110: "Sleep," with Max Richter
episodesByNumber.tease: Max Richter joins us to discuss his ambitious, yet intimate project, "Sleep," for string quartet, piano, voices, and computer. It's about sleep, and is meant to be slept through.

episodesByNumber.title: #4111: From New Sounds Live, Margaret Leng Tan Premieres George Crumb
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear George Crumb's modern take on Mussorgsky's "Pictures At An Exhibition"- Metamorphoses (Book 1) Ten Fantasy-Pieces (after celebrated paintings), for pianist Margaret Leng Tan.

episodesByNumber.title: #4112: Folk-Inspired Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to an hour of music that moves in the sound world of folk guitars with music by 12-string guitarist Sarah Louise, UK-based artist Seabuckthorn, and the duo Anna  &  Elizabeth.

episodesByNumber.title: #4113: From the New Sounds Live/Ecstatic Music Festival 2018 Concerts
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live 2018 Concert Series, Margaret Leng Tan performs a work for prepared piano  &  toy piano by Kelly Moran  &  ModernMedieval sings Julianna Barwick and Caleb Burhans.

episodesByNumber.title: #4114: Extended Folk Music From the UK
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by folk singer Eliza Carthy, folk band Lau, and folk singer/song-collector Sam Lee - all on the ambitious side of UK folk, since all the pieces are for extended ensembles.

episodesByNumber.title: #4115: Echoes of Ethiopop and Jazz
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music with the lingering echo of the "Golden Age" of Ethiopian pop in addition to classics, from Mahmoud Ahmed, Minyeshu, Anbessa Orchestra, Debo Band, Mulatu Astatqe, and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4116: New Electronic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new electronic music from Moscow-based Kate NV, Swiss-Nepalese-Tibetan Aisha Devi, Montreal–based composer Kara-Lis Coverdale, and music by UK-producer Rival Consoles.

episodesByNumber.title: #4117: Signal-To-Noise: The Sounds of Decay
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the sounds of deterioration and decay with disintegrating and layered works by William Basinski, Grant Cutler, Annie Gosfield, Prefuse 73, and a classic by Alvin Lucier.

episodesByNumber.title: #4118: Piano, Plus...
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear piano-centric works open to additions by pianist/composer Vijay Iyer, Dutch pianist Saskia Lankhoorn playing music by Australian Kate Moore, and ritual groove by Nik Bartsch.

episodesByNumber.title: #4119: Tales From the Folk Tradition
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some tales from the folk tradition from American artists Sam Amidon, Bruce Greene and Kore Loy McWhirter, and English folk from Emily Portman, and Sam Lee.

episodesByNumber.title: #4120: Music in the Harmonic Series - Loud, Louder, Muted
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music in the harmonic series on this New Sounds in works by the late Glenn Branca, producer Chris Hughes, after Steve Reich, and Michael Harrison for cellist Clarice Jensen.

episodesByNumber.title: #4121: New Releases, May 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music by guitarist/composer Marisa Anderson, work by multi-instrumentalist Leila Abdul-Rauf, and a new work by accordionist Guy Klusevcsek for Pauline Oliveros. Plus, Brian Eno.

episodesByNumber.title: #4122: Music from Guitarist-Composers
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from composer/improviser Mary Halvorson, fingerstyle players Shana Cleveland and Marisa Anderson, Tuareg guitarist Bombino, New York guitarist/composer Rafiq Bhatia, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4123: Norwegian Vocalist Susanna and Friends, from Big Ears 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: From the 2018 Big Ears Festival, Norwegian singer Susanna Wallumrød along with baroque harp, accordion, and fiddle, plays spellbinding arrangements of songs by AC/DC to Leonard Cohen.

episodesByNumber.title: #4124: New Music/Baroque Dances
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music based on baroque dances, by Pulitzer Prize-winning composer Caroline Shaw, Seattle's big band Zubatto Syndicate, pianist Henrique Eisenmann, and string quintet Sybarite5.

episodesByNumber.title: #4125: Music from Greece
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from Greece by composer Eleni Karaindrou, by the lute and drums duo of Xylouris White, and by electroacoustic composer Tasos Stamou from his latest, Musique con Crète.

episodesByNumber.title: #4126: “Simple Answers” with Charlie Looker
episodesByNumber.tease: Singer, composer, and guitarist Charlie Looker joins us to discuss his album, 'Simple Answers', its roots, his process, and the fascism he is trying to combat with his music.

episodesByNumber.title: #4127: Idiosyncratic Chamber Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Chamber ensembles have been around for centuries, but on this episode of New Sounds, we will hear chamber ensembles that are testing the limits of what this kind of group can sound like.

episodesByNumber.title: #4128: New Releases, June 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music from Duo Noire by Mary Kouyoumdjian, work by Chicago-based composer Marc Mellits and New Music Detroit, plus music by The Dreebs, Big Red Machine, and Donna McKevitt.

episodesByNumber.title: #4129, From the 2018 Big Ears Festival
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to (more) music recorded at the 2018 Big Ears Festival: a film score featuring Knoxville-based new music group Nief Norf, music by Steve Reich, and a work by Susan Alcorn.

episodesByNumber.title: #4130: West African Blues
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the kora and blues-rock of Kaira Ba, the late Malian singer Khaira Arby, and guitar masters: Ali Farka Touré, his son, Vieux Farka Touré, and his protégé Samba Touré.

episodesByNumber.title: #4131: Electronic Music for Spatial Contemplation
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear electronic and electronically-altered music that creates space by cellist Zoe Keating, zither-based work by Laraaji, a work by Joanne Forman, and installation music by Brian Eno.

episodesByNumber.title: #4132: Guitarists Susan Alcorn and Marisa Anderson
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music by pedal steel guitarist and innovator Susan Alcorn, recorded at the 2018 Big Ears Festival and music by electric guitarist Marisa Anderson, recorded in our studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #4133: Music for Trumpet, Mostly
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music for trumpet, mostly, in old and new works by Jon Hassell, Christian Scott from New Orleans, music by Arve Henriksen from Norway, and UK-based Laura Jurd's band, Dinosaur.

episodesByNumber.title: #4134 Cross-Cultural Musical Meetings
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to musical meetings across cultures and continents including new music by Taiwanese pipa master Chung Yufeng, lap tapping guitarist and kalimba-player Yasmin Williams, and Junun.

episodesByNumber.title: #4135: Early Interactive Computer Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works by electronic music pioneers who were interested in and specifically developed techniques for interactivity like Pauline Oliveros, Morton Subotnick, and David Behrman.

episodesByNumber.title: #4136: New Releases, July 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to brand-new music by Resina, pedal steel layers by Post Moves, vibraphone-based work by Masayoshi Fujita, and Yoruban spiritual music by the group Okonkolo.

episodesByNumber.title: #4137: Music From the South Pacific
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from or about the region of the South Pacific from Australia and New Zealand to as far away as Easter Island, featuring music by Gurrumul, Stewart Copeland, and Telek.

episodesByNumber.title: #4138: Sky Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that looks to the sky from John Luther Adams, Jane Antonia Cornish, Polish cellist Resina, a work of dark and light from Baird Hersey, and moonlit music from Colleen.

episodesByNumber.title: #4139 Echoes of Oum Kalthoum
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Oum Kalthoum and composer Mohamed Abdel Wahab and echoes of that music with Jerusalem In My Heart, Ibrahim Maalouf, Natacha Atlas, and Senegalese singer Youssou N'Dour.

episodesByNumber.title: #4140 Echoes of John Fahey
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music with echoes of John Fahey (1939-2001), the American fingerstyle guitarist and composer, with works by guitarists Gwenifer Raymond, Glenn Jones, Yasmin Williams, and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4141: Keyboard Studies
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to number of works - perhaps "Keyboard Studies" for piano and prepared piano by Terry Riley, Kelly Moran, Alex Mincek for Yarn/Wire, and Irwin Schmidt of the band Can.

episodesByNumber.title: #4142: Music for Duos and Trios
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music by the smallest possible ensembles - duos and trios - from the London-centered band Szun Waves, Mary Halvorson and Robbie Lee, and Shadi Fathi and Bijan Chemirani.

episodesByNumber.title: #4143: New/Old Music from South America
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Brazil by Elza Soares, music with Colombian roots by Combo Chimbita, music by Argentinian producer Chancha via Circuito, and Andean music by Chile's Inti-Illimani.

episodesByNumber.title: #4144: Native American and First Nations Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Native American or First Nations voices in music by Chickasaw composer Jerod Impichchaachaaha Tate, the Canadian group A Tribe Called Red, and Inuk throat singer Tanya Tagaq.

episodesByNumber.title: #4145: New Releases, August 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new releases (or those new to us), including Taarab music from Zanzibar, piano-based music by Icelandic composer Ólafur Arnalds, and Afro-funk by Brazilian big band Bixiga70.

episodesByNumber.title: #4146: Inspired by John Cage
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music inspired by the radical, mischievous, inventive, and influential John Cage, including works by Michael Nyman, Annie Gosfield, David Lang, Florent Ghys and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4147: Stories of Mental Illness and Rehabilitation
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music that addresses mental illness and mental rehabilitation. Hear works by Michigander Nina Shekhar, Utah-based Philip Bimstein, and English composer Jocelyn Pook.

episodesByNumber.title: #4148: Modern Monteverdi
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music based on much older works of Italian composer Claudio Monteverdi, by Italian Gianluigi Trovesi, and from American composers David Garland, Wendy Carlos, and Huck Hodge.

episodesByNumber.title: #4149: Ambient Minimalism
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to ambient minimalism for piano and electronics by Christina Vantzou from Belgium, Poppy Ackroyd from England, Canadian composer Sarah Davachi, and a little music by Brian Eno.

episodesByNumber.title: #4150: From Russia With...New Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to new music from Russia, featuring works by sound artist Lovozero, electronic music by Moscow-based Kate NV, and arrangements of Russian choral works for Kronos Quartet.

episodesByNumber.title: #4151: West Meets West Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works by North Carolina-based Senegalese kora master Diali Cissokho and Kaira Ba, Cuban pianist Roberto Fonseca and Malian singer Fatoumata Diawara, and the Alba Griot Ensemble.

episodesByNumber.title: #4152: New Music from Denmark
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from Danish-American sax player Sonja LaBianca, Gambian-born Danish-based Dawda Jobarteh, sound artist Ragnhild May, and music by accordionist Bjarke Mogensen.

episodesByNumber.title: #4153: Music from the Black Sea
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to instruments and musicians from Bulgaria, Turkey, Georgia, Armenia, including music by Ilhan Ersahin (who owns Nublu), vocal trio Black Sea Hotel, and music for duduk.

episodesByNumber.title: #4154: With Tyshawn Sorey, from the 2018 Music Now Festival
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by and an interview with composer, improviser, drummer, and educator Tyshawn Sorey recorded at the Music Now Festival in Cincinnati. Plus, music by drummer Makaya McCraven.

episodesByNumber.title: #4155: New Releases, September 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to collaborative Indian and Irish music by Nirmala Ragasekar-led group Maithree, Norwegian spiritual blues by Tord Gustavesen Trio, and 'organic beat music' by Makaya McCraven.

episodesByNumber.title: #4156: Four Millers And A Stone
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Paul D. Miller/DJ Spooky, and chamber jazz by Allison Miller. Listen to work by Minnesota's Scott L. Miller, New Yorker Scott D. Miller, and computer music by Carl Stone.

episodesByNumber.title: #4157: Music Rooted in the British Isles
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that grows out of the folk traditions of the British Isles from the Martin Hayes Quartet, Emily Portman, London composer Tunde Jegede, Welsh guitarist Toby Hay, and SANS.

episodesByNumber.title: #4158: Voices Out of Context
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music built around pre-existing recordings of voices by drummer/producer Jaimeo Brown, Argentine producer Chancha via Circuito, Canadian composer Jeremy Dutcher, and Jocelyn Pook.

episodesByNumber.title: #4159: Ted Hearne's 'Place'
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer Ted Hearne previews his latest work, "Place," a fiery meditation on gentrification, in which he personally addresses privilege, boundaries, immigration, and land in America.

episodesByNumber.title: #4160: Processed Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear processed music by Montreal-based composer and sound-manipulator Tim Hecker, violinist and sound artist Jessica Moss, and from Irish-led, New York-based super-group Spirit Spout.

episodesByNumber.title: #4161: Theme and Variations: 'Warszawa'
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear variations on "Warzsawa" from David Bowie and Brian Eno's "Low" (1977.) Hear music from Geir Sundstøl, Philip Glass, and music from Donny McCaslin, who led Bowie's final band.

episodesByNumber.title: #4162: Savina Yannatou's 'Wandering Stories'
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Greek composer and vocalist Savina Yannatou's multimedia work, 'Wandering Stories', combining folk melodies, interview, and sound design from the 2018 Ultima Festival in Oslo.

episodesByNumber.title: #4163: Featuring the Violin
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music featuring the violin, solo, and coupled with keyboard, looping, field recordings, and the voice. Listen to works by Jessica Moss, Abraham Brody, Iva Bittova, and Maarja Nuut.

episodesByNumber.title: #4164: Songs of Protest and Resistance, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to contemporary songs of protest and resistance from Ambrose Akinmusire, Matana Roberts, Laurie Anderson, Marc Ribot featuring Meshell Ndegeocello and a vocalise from Hanna Benn.

episodesByNumber.title: #4165: Songs of Protest and Resistance, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to contemporary songs of protest and resistance from Nicole Mitchell, Ambrose Akinmusire, Emily Wells, Wadada Leo Smith, and Marc Ribot with Sam Amidon and Fay Victor.

episodesByNumber.title: #4166: New Music From Chicago
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Chicago by composer Renée Baker and CMOP, trumpeter Ben LaMar Gay, cellist Shannon Hayden, drummer Makaya McCraven, post-rockers Tortoise, and the quintet Dos Santos.

episodesByNumber.title: #4167: Shine a Light
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that brings the light by electronic composer Alvin Curran, American composer Joanne Metcalf,  Norwegian guitarist Stian Westerhus, and Icelandic composer Anna Thorvaldsdottir.

episodesByNumber.title: #4168: New Releases, October 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the newest sounds for the month of October, including music by Baba Commandant And The Mandingo Band, London-based band Vula Viel, and Estonian duo Maarja Nuut and Ruum.

episodesByNumber.title: #4169: New Music From Iceland
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Bjork, and fellow Icelandic composers Daniel Bjarnasson, Hildur Gudnadottir, Gyda Valtysdottir, Ólafur Arnalds and Australian-born, but Iceland-based Ben Frost.

episodesByNumber.title: #4170: Music Inspired by Franz Schubert
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music based on or inspired by Franz Schubert's songs and song cycles from composer Douglas Cuomo, Kate Simko  &  London Electronic Orchestra, Penguin Cafe, and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4171: Music About Climate Change
episodesByNumber.tease: From John Luther Adams' "Become Ocean" to music for the duo Transient Canvas about a volcanic eruption in Indonesia, hear music inspired by climate change for this New Sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #4172: Music Inspired by the Sciences
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music inspired by the sciences – physics, astronomy, neuroscience- featuring music from the composers' lab called Golden Hornet, Bjork, and work by pianist Dan Tepfner.

episodesByNumber.title: #4173: Music for Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some music for bowed strings from inside of a piano by Vincent Plush, to layers of cellist Julia Kent and a work for Paul Dresher's Quadracord, and the string quartet ETHEL.

episodesByNumber.title: #4174: All in the Harp and Guitar Families
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music featuring guitars, harps, and other plucked string instruments, featuring guitarist Meg Baird and harpist Mary Lattimore and the oud-playing brothers, Le Trio Joubran.

episodesByNumber.title: #4175:  Kate & Yuki, from MusicNOW Festival, 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new works woven together with J.S. Bach as played by Dublin-based Irish cellist, Kate Ellis, and American violinist, Yuki Numata Resnick, recorded at the 2018 MusicNOW festival.

episodesByNumber.title: #4176: With Sarah Davachi
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer Sarah Davachi visits the studio to present sacred-seeming works from her latest record, 'Gave In Rest', inspired by cathedral-like spaces of European churches she has known.

episodesByNumber.title: #4177: Jazz Without Borders
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works by musicians rooted in "jazz" but not bound by it. There's music by drummer Andrew Cyrille, trumpeter Wadada Leo Smith, and guitarist Bill Frisell, Dinosaur, and Omar Sosa.

episodesByNumber.title: #4178: New Releases, November 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music from November by Shara Nova (My Brightest Diamond) for the Brooklyn Youth Chorus and ICE, Toronto sax player Joseph Shabason, and new music from Dead Can Dance.

episodesByNumber.title: #4179: William Kentridge Performs Schwitters' Ursonate, from Ultima Fest 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: South African artist William Kentridge performs Ursonate at the 2018 Ultima Fest in Oslo, Norway and sits with host John Schaefer for an interview about the work and his approach

episodesByNumber.title: #4180: Music for Piano, Plus...
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that starts with piano and goes beyond, including music by Kelly Moran for prepared piano, a piece by Dan Tepfer, and music from pianist Sophia Subbayya Vastek.

episodesByNumber.title: #4181: Between Art and Pop Song
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from the musical netherworld between art song and pop song with works by Alev Lenz with Roomful of Teeth, Julia Holter, Berlin's Barbara Morgenstern, and ANOHNI.

episodesByNumber.title: #4182: Spiritual Jazz, Old and New
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that draws on music of Africa, India, and ancient Egyptian mythology by drummer Makaya McCraven, percussionist Sarathy Korwar, and pianist and harpist Alice Coltrane.

episodesByNumber.title: #4183: Music For the Liberation of Household Items
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that takes stuff out of the home into the studio: be it tea cups, flower pots, or wine glasses in works by David Lang, Stephan Micus, and Paula Matthusen and Olivia Valentine.

episodesByNumber.title: #4184: Harps Around the World
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music for harps: West African kora and ngoni, East African litungu, acoustic, Celtic and Finnish harps from Catrin Finch and Seckou Keita, Zeena Parkins, and Dawda Jobarteh.

episodesByNumber.title: #4185: Jazz-Adjacent Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music with a connection to the world of improvised music from Cuban percussionist Brenda Navarette, tabla player Sarathy Korwar, Japanese producer Yoshinori Hayashi, and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4186: Best of Soundcheck 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: Live performances you may have missed from 2018 from a Cuban orchestra to ancient Norse ritual music, from mountain music to the great South African choir Ladysmith Black Mambazo.

episodesByNumber.title: #4187: New Music from Los Angeles
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to new music from Los Angeles, largely revolving around the new music band wild Up with works by Zola Jesus, William Brittelle, Ellen Reid, Jodie Landau, and Julia Holter.

episodesByNumber.title: #4188: David Bowie Week, Part 1 - Berlin Trilogy Inspirations
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Wordless Music Orchestra play arrangements of music from Brian Eno's trailblazing record, "Another Green World," plus Eno's "Discreet Music," recorded at Brookfield Place in 2018.

episodesByNumber.title: #4189: David Bowie Week, Part 2 - 'Low' from New Sounds Live
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear an all-star cast of musicians led by Shearwater's Jonathan Meiberg as they offer their rendition of David Bowie's 1977 record, "Low", as recorded at Brookfield Place.

episodesByNumber.title: #4190: Bowie Week part 3 - "Heroes" from New Sounds Live
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear "Heroes" from David Bowie's 'Berlin Trilogy' as performed by an expanded version of Shearwater, led by Jonathan Meiberg, recorded at Brookfield Place in October 2018.

episodesByNumber.title: #4191: David Bowie Week, Part 4 - 'Lodger' from New Sounds Live
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear an all-star cast of musicians led by Shearwater's Jonathan Meiberg as they offer their rendition of David Bowie's 1979 record, "Lodger", as recorded in 2018 at Brookfield Place.

episodesByNumber.title: #4192: David Bowie Week, Part 5 - Inspirations and Related Works
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Wordless Music Orchestra perform music of the Berlin school by Klaus Schulze, recorded at Brookfield Place. Plus, hear music by Philip Glass inspired by Bowie's Berlin Trilogy.

episodesByNumber.title: #4193: John Schaefer's Top Ten of 2018
episodesByNumber.tease: John Schaefer presents his overdue annual top 10 list of notable new music releases from 2018. Hear music by Red Baraat, Julia Holter, Bombino, David Garland, and Sons of Kemet.

episodesByNumber.title: #4194: Theme & Variations: Idumea
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear variations on the theme of the American shape note tune, "Idumea," with versions from Sufjian Stevens, guitarist Gwenifer Raymond, the women's choir, Kitka, and many others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4195: A Jazzy Suggestion
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that joins multiple streams: jazz, hip hop, funk, groove, and world music by drummer Kassa Overall, trumpeter Steph Richards, and the London-based group Ezra Collective.

episodesByNumber.title: #4196: Music With Arab Roots
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to works that combine the sounds of Arabic music with sounds of Western jazz, rock, and/or electronics, like Maurice Louca, Sabry Mosbah, Brickwork Lizards, and Epichorus.

episodesByNumber.title: #4197: New Sounds Live 2019: wild Up, Zola Jesus and William Brittelle from Merkin Hall
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by electro-goth songwriter Zola Jesus and 'post-genre' composer William Brittelle in collaboration with the Los Angeles-based new music collective wild Up, from Merkin Hall.

episodesByNumber.title: #4198: Hidden Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to "hidden voices" – works where there is, or was, a voice as source material, in music by Irene and Linda Buckley, Paul Lansky, and Paul De Marinis.

episodesByNumber.title: #4199: Guitar and Guitar-Based Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music with guitar as its sound source from North Carolina guitarist Sarah Louise, Sardinian guitarist and inventor Paolo Angeli, and Dutch artist Machinefabriek.

episodesByNumber.title: #4200: New Releases, January 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music by by Lebanese violinist and composer Layale Chaker, German keyboardist Nils Frahm, Greek composer Eleni Karaindrou, and Texas-based D.J. Sparr for this new releases show.

episodesByNumber.title: #4201: Music From Human Speech
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music drawn from the process of finding the music of human speech with works by minimalist Steve Reich, vocalist and composer Olga Bell, Phillip K. Bimstein, and Scott Johnson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4202: The Egyptian Project
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music inspired by contemporary Egypt for this New Sounds with works from the cross-continental musical collective One Beat, Cypress Hill with Sadat  &  50, and the Nile Project.

episodesByNumber.title: #4203: Musical Landscapes
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear musical landscapes - both outdoor and indoor - from Anna Thorvaldsdottir, John Luther Adams, Qasim Naqvi, and a duet by harpist Mary Lattimore and musician Mac McCaughan.

episodesByNumber.title: #4204: Music for Altered Keyboards
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works for altered and re-tuned keyboards, with prepared piano music by keyboardist/composer Kelly Moran and the German composer Hauschka, plus music for retuned pianos by Kyle Gann.

episodesByNumber.title: #4205: Soundcheck Sessions With Kaia Kater and Leyla McCalla
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Canadian-Grenadian folk singer and songwriter Kaia Kater as well as music by multi-instrumentalist Leyla McCalla, a New York–born Haitian-American living in New Orleans.

episodesByNumber.title: #4206: Works That Deal With Snow
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works that deal with snow by guitarist Sarah Louise, Tanya Tagaq, Icelandic bassist Skúli Sverrisson, cellist Zoe Keating, and Japanese vibraphonist and drummer Masayoshi Fujita.

episodesByNumber.title: #4207: Songs and Stories of the African American Experience
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music and stories from the band Algiers, songwriter Rhiannon Giddens, and the collaborative supergroup Our Native Daughters. Plus, music by India.Arie and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4208, More Musical Landscapes
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear more musical landscapes for this New Sounds with works by New York-based Lithuanian composer Zibuokle Martinaityte, Breton composer Yann Tiersen, and English composer Pete M. Wyer.

episodesByNumber.title: #4209: Jazz, Plus...
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear jazz that draws on Ethiopian music, or the South Indian Carnatic tradition, or that which weaves in Gnawan trance music of Morocco, psychedelics, and Western chamber music.

episodesByNumber.title: #4210: Hot Jazz and Blues from Soundcheck Sessions
episodesByNumber.tease: From our Soundcheck Podcast series, listen to funky jazz from the Hypnotic Brass Ensemble, Nashville guitarist and poet Adia Victoria, and dance-party jazz from London's Ezra Collective.

episodesByNumber.title: #4211: New Releases, February 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Morocco, Norway, New Zealand, and London by guembri player Houssam Gania, saxophone player Bendik Giske, composer Gemma Peacocke, and tuba player Theon Cross.

episodesByNumber.title: #4212: It's About Time
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear pieces about time and works that deal with the passage of time from cellist Julia Kent, composer Poppy Ackroyd, and by multi-instrumentalist David Garland.

episodesByNumber.title: #4213: From New Sounds Live Silent Films 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series, listen to new music for silent films: Irene and Linda Buckley's score for "Nosferatu" and Marc Ribot's score for "The Kid" from the 2019 season.

episodesByNumber.title: #4214: Art Pop Song Cycles
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear work by Gemma Peacocke which sets Afghan women's folk poems, landays, to electro-acoustic music. Also, hear music from song cycles by Donna McKevitt, and Sarah Kirkland Snider.

episodesByNumber.title: #4215: From New Sounds Live Silent Films 2019, Part II
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts, listen to new music for silent films: Marc Ribot's score for Chaplin's "The Kid" and Irene and Linda Buckley's score for F.W. Murnau's "Nosferatu."

episodesByNumber.title: #4216: From the New Sounds Live Concerts
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new works by Mexican-born composer and guitarist Josué Collado Fregoso, and New Jersey-based Barbadian-American Trevor Weston, along with works featuring the Brooklyn Youth Chorus.

episodesByNumber.title: #4217: Music About Spring
episodesByNumber.tease: Late in coming, and early to depart, listen to unsettled spring-themed music from composer Emily Doolittle, electronic music pioneer Wendy Carlos, and German composer Heiner Goebbels.

episodesByNumber.title: #4218: From New Sounds Live, with Bang On A Can
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts, hear the Bang on a Can All-Stars play music in alternate tunings and "period" instrumentation by Annie Gosfield, Arnold Dreyblatt, and Glenn Branca.

episodesByNumber.title: #4219: New Releases, March 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new releases of music from Korea, Mali, Syria by way of Paris, the D.R.C., and music with Ethiopian roots. Plus, new work by Indian-American composer Reena Esmail, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4220: Music By and For Steve Martland
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music by the late British composer and educator Steve Martland, as well as music paying homage to him for electric guitar quartet by Canadian composer Scott Godin.

episodesByNumber.title: #4221: With Bryce Dessner
episodesByNumber.tease: Guitarist and composer Bryce Dessner (of the rock band The National), presents music from his latest record, El Chan, a collaboration with the piano duo of Katia  &  Marielle Labeque.

episodesByNumber.title: #4222: With Steve Reich
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to the latest music by and an interview with influential composer Steve Reich, plus contrasting and complimentary works by Caroline Shaw, Daniel Thorne, and Emily Wells.

episodesByNumber.title: #4223: With Makaya McCraven from Big Ears 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that is a hybrid of production and live performance by Chicago-based drummer, composer, and producer Makaya McCraven, plus an interview with him recorded at Big Ears 2019.

episodesByNumber.title: #4224: West Meets Near East
episodesByNumber.tease: Take a tour of music around the world with a work by Taiwanese pipa player Yufeng Chung and Indonesian gamelan Sambasunda, German jazzers Web Web meet Moroccan Gnawa music, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4225: With Žibuoklė Martinaitytė
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, New York-based Lithuanian composer Žibuoklė Martinaitytė takes us on the sonic journey through her recent hour-long audiovisual project 'In Search of Lost Beauty.'

episodesByNumber.title: #4226 Northern Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear arrangements of traditional Irish songs by The Gloaming, along with music from Norway, Sweden, Finland, and Iceland for a whole program of Northern songs.

episodesByNumber.title: #4227: With Kristín Anna, From Big Ears 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music recorded at Big Ears 2019 from the Icelandic musician and artist Kristín Anna Valtýsdóttir, music by her sister Gyða, and work by Canadian composer Kara-Lis Coverdale.

episodesByNumber.title: #4228: "Supergroups" of All Kinds
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music by supergroups, including all-star lineups from the African-American tradition in Our Native Daughters, African acoustic music trio 3MA, and music from the British Isles.

episodesByNumber.title: #4229: Poetry and Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a number of poems by Emily Brontë, Lord Byron, and Emily Dickinson set to music by The Unthanks, English composer Donna McKevitt, and by New York-based composer Alex Weiser.

episodesByNumber.title: #4230: New Sounds Live with Wye Oak and the Brooklyn Youth Chorus
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live/Ecstatic Music Festival Concerts, the Brooklyn Youth Chorus performs music by the band Wye Oak, along with new work by Owen Pallett, recorded at Merkin Hall.

episodesByNumber.title: #4231: Music to Change Your Mind
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music for altering the mind, in Rodrigo y Gabriela's Pink Floyd cover, trance ritual music from Iranian mystic and composer Ostad Elahi, or the clouds and drones of LaMonte Young.

episodesByNumber.title: #4232: New Releases, April 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music that reached our earholes for April, including work by keyboardist/composer Kelly Moran, cellist Caitlin Sullivan, and new music from PUBLIQuartet.

episodesByNumber.title: #4233: From Soundcheck - Avi and Omer Avital, Kinan Azmeh and The Knights
episodesByNumber.tease: From the Soundcheck Podcast series, hear performances from mandolinist Avi Avital and bassist Omer Avital (no relation), and The Knights play music by Syrian clarinetist Kinan Azmeh.

episodesByNumber.title: #4234: New Works By Composers Who Happen to Be Women
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to new music by saxophonist/composer Shelley Washington and songs by German composer Alev Lenz, featuring the Brooklyn Youth Chorus. Plus works by Kelly Moran and Nicole Lizée.

episodesByNumber.title: #4235: Tangled Musical Roots
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear tangled roots music from North America, the British Isles, the near East, West Africa, and Central Asia in music from Rhiannon Giddens, Robert Plant, and the Silk Road Ensemble.

episodesByNumber.title: #4236: Music for Percussion
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music for percussion, from the mighty battery of the NYU Percussion Ensemble, to the motoric quartet work of Third Coast Percussion, or soloists Evelyn Glennie and Eli Keszler.

episodesByNumber.title: #4237: Music Inspired by the Sea
episodesByNumber.tease: Take a plunge into music inspired by the sea, with works from French chamber band astrïd, Jonsi and Alex, and multi-instrumentalist Jherek Bischoff. Plus works from 'Black Inscription.'

episodesByNumber.title: #4238: The Roedelius Effect
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that might be under the influence of Roedelius, like Tim Story's Roedelius Cells, or those with an indirect association, like music by bassist and composer Josephine Wiggs.

episodesByNumber.title: #4239: The New Sounds of West Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the new sounds of West African music that combines traditional n'goni and kora together with hiphop production and electric guitars from Bassekou Kouyate, Tartit, and Mdou Moctar.

episodesByNumber.title: #4240: Chamber Techno
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear minimalist ambient techno done up as classical chamber orchestrations for this New Sounds with music by Detroit DJ and producer Carl Craig and Barcelona pianist Francesco Tristano.

episodesByNumber.title: #4241: A Touch of Jazz
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works that can't be easily classified - some with a touch of jazz - featuring Damon Locks' Black Monument Ensemble, jazz pianist Romain Collin, and Portuguese trio The Selva.

episodesByNumber.title: #4242: The New York Guitar Festival's First 20 Years
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music for the New York Guitar Festival's 20th anniversary, featuring music from Toshi Reagon, Cindy Cashdollar, Michael Manring, Dominic Frasca, and Derek Gripper.

episodesByNumber.title: #4243: Balkan Music, American-Style
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to Balkan music, American-style, like Brooklyn-based Slavic Soul Party!, San Francisco-based Brass Menažeri, and the New York-based Zlatne Uste Balkan Brass Band.

episodesByNumber.title: #4244: New Releases, May 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music by Barcelona pianist Francesco Tristano, Spanish percussionist Alejandro Coello, and French guitarist/composer David Chalmin. Plus music by the late Jóhann Jóhannsson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4245: The Reich Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Steve Reich and music that carries traces of Reich's work by Montreal harpist Sarah Pagé, guitarists David Chalmin and Bryce Dessner, and percussionist David Skidmore.

episodesByNumber.title: #4246: Voices from Around the World
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear voices from many different parts of the world: Algeria, Tuva, Sudan, Taiwan, Norway, and Sardinia, including music by Norwegian singer Marja Mortensson, Huun Huur Tu, and Lemma.

episodesByNumber.title: #4247: Music and Spoken Word
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the combination of spoken word with music, featuring work by London-based artist Kate Tempest, Scottish folk singer James Yorkston, and poet Will Burns with composer Hannah Peel.

episodesByNumber.title: #4248: Pop/Chamber Orchestra Meetings
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear musicians from pop/rock worlds together with chamber orchestral from in-studio performances by Emily Wells and Metropolis Ensemble, along with music by POLIÇA and s t a r g a z e .

episodesByNumber.title: #4249, John Luther Adams, Become Desert
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear "Become Desert", an entire musical landscape by John Luther Adams, for this New Sounds. The composer himself visits the studio to present the work, the third in a trilogy.

episodesByNumber.title: #4250, New Releases, June 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some of the new music that reached our earholes for June 2019. There's music across centuries and continents from South America, the eastern Mediterranean, and Los Angeles.

episodesByNumber.title: #4251, More Spiritual Jazz
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear "spiritual jazz" from bassist William Parker, sax player Pharoah Sanders, harpist-turned koto player Dorothy Ashby, drummer/composer Makaya McCraven, and the German group Web Web.

episodesByNumber.title: #4252: Pattern-Based Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music derived from patterns in data from electrical monitoring of plant leaves, music for a game of go, plus music by Julia Wolfe, Joseph C. Phillips Jr., and music by Flow State.

episodesByNumber.title: #4253, Small Acoustic Ensembles
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to small acoustic ensembles from Mali, South Africa, Rwanda, Argentina, and Turkey along with music from the flamenco tradition by Pedro Soler and Gaspar Claus.

episodesByNumber.title: #4254, Music Inspired by Post-Rock and Metal
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music inspired by the cinematic sounds of post-rock or metal from Korean band Jambinai, Japanese band Mono, Norwegian pagan band Wardruna and Finnish band Oddarang.

episodesByNumber.title: #4255, Unexpected Duos
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to unexpected duos for this New Sounds, including unlikely pairings of marimba and marimba-like instruments with harp, guitar, or piano, along with cello and kora, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4256, North Africa and the Levant
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music with roots in North Africa and the Levant from Mauritania's Noura Mint Seymali, Niger's Mdou Moctar, Tunisia's Sabry Mosbah, Egypt's Maryam Selah, and TootArd (Golan Heights.)

episodesByNumber.title: #4257, Inspired by Bach
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to re-imaginings of music by J.S. Bach from Víkingur Ólafsson, Max Richter, Princeton University professor Dan Trueman, and So Percussion. Plus, electronic music of Tom Hamilton.

episodesByNumber.title: #4258, Piano, From the Insides
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music made with the insides of the piano – bowed, prepared, retuned, and/or processed - by Kelly Moran, Donnacha Dennehy for Lisa Moore, and Stephen Scott's Bowed Piano Ensemble.

episodesByNumber.title: #4259, New Releases, July 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear cosmic psych-jazz from The Quiet Temple, music from Irish fiddler Martin Hayes and Brooklyn Rider, and new music for modified 12-string guitar from David Garland and Kenji Garland.

episodesByNumber.title: #4260: Processed Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music with altered voices from Guatemalan cellist and vocalist Mabe Fratti, American composer Pamela Z, and the AI-enhanced vocal layering of electronic composer Holly Herndon.

episodesByNumber.title: #4261: New Versions of Old Folk Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new and newer versions of traditional folksongs of the British Isles from Martin Hayes and Brooklyn Rider, Sam Lee and Friends, the Irish band Planxty, and Traffic.

episodesByNumber.title: #4262, The Qawwali Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Sufi devotional music known as Qawwali from the late, great Pakistani singer, Nusrat Fateh Ali Kahn, along with music by Sarathy Korwar, the Sachal Ensemble, and Riyaaz Qawwali.

episodesByNumber.title: #4263, Music with Traditional Japanese Instruments
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to traditional Japanese instruments in music from shakuhachi player Goro Yamaguchi, jazz clarinetist Tony Scott, and guitarist Pete M. Wyer with shakuhachi player Ralph Samuelson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4264, with Qasim Naqvi
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by composer, drummer, and modular synth experimenter Qasim Naqvi, created live in-studio, and from his recent record, Teenages and from his work with Dawn of Midi.

episodesByNumber.title: #4265, The Mighty Duduk
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music made with the Armenian oboe called the duduk as used by musicians from Poland, Germany, Lithuania, the Republic of Georgia, and from England – Peter Gabriel.

episodesByNumber.title: #4266: Modern Versions of Early and Medieval Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to works by composers Ambrose Field, Bora Yoon and Alejandro Viñao who transform music from the Medieval and Renaissance eras into sweeping vistas of electronic sounds.

episodesByNumber.title: #4267: Music for Keyboards
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear all kinds of keyboard music in works by percussionist/producer Julian Loida, pianist/producer Kelly Moran, Canadian pianist Lubomyr Melnyk, and German pianist/producer Nils Frahm.

episodesByNumber.title: #4268: New Music with a Social Conscience
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, listen to three works with social or political ideas in mind. There's music by the gifted composer Julius Eastman, along with music by Rzewski and Andriessen.

episodesByNumber.title: #4269, Song Cycles
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from song cycles - by Christopher Cerrone and wild up, a collaboration between Will Oldham, Bryce Dessner, and eighth blackbird, and by Richard Einhorn with Anonymous 4.

episodesByNumber.title: #4270, New Releases, August 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from London vocal group Shards, acoustic quartet Che Apalache, Icelandic duo Hugar, American/Irish duo Caoimhín Ó Raghallaigh and Thomas Bartlett, and work by Cassie Wieland.

episodesByNumber.title: #4271, Music That Looks to the Skies
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to works that look to the skies in music by Terry Riley for Kronos Quartet and sounds collected by NASA, a piece by Annie Gosfield, and computer music by Morton Subotnick.

episodesByNumber.title: #4272: Sonic Cathedrals
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to massive cathedral-like pieces of sonic architecture in music by Estonian Arvo Pärt, English composer Thomas Tallis, and Johannes Ockeghem as reworked by Pauline Kim Harris.

episodesByNumber.title: #4273, Electronic Music From the Mid-1970's
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear electronic music from the 1970's, with music by Paul Lansky, Irish composer Roger Doyle, Swedish-born Berlin-based Catherine Christer Hennix, and New York composer Laurie Speigel.

episodesByNumber.title: #4274: “Fire In My Mouth” by Julia Wolfe
episodesByNumber.tease: The Pulitzer Prize-winning composer Julia Wolfe talks us through her riveting and intense work "Fire In My Mouth," inspired by the 1911 Triangle Shirtwaist Fire, written for the NY Phil.
tags: young peoples chorus of new york city

episodesByNumber.title: #4275: Music Inspired by the Gobi and Taklamakan Deserts
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music inspired by the Gobi and Taklamakan Deserts, with music not only from Chinese and Mongolian musicians, but also musicians from Turkey, Japan, Germany and America.

episodesByNumber.title: #4276: Crash Ensemble's 20th Anniversary
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music written for the Dublin new music group Crash Ensemble by Donnacha Dennehy, Irish composer Amanda Feerey, as well as Bang on a Can's Michael Gordon and Julia Wolfe.

episodesByNumber.title: #4277: Western Music Built on Field Recordings
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Western music built on field recordings from Java, Ethiopia, Australia and Jamaica by Gregory Taylor, Patti Smith and the Soundwalk Collective, Steve Roach, and K. Leimer.

episodesByNumber.title: #4278: Africa Acoustic
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear mostly acoustic music from Africa: The Good Ones from Rwanda, Cameroonian guitarist Francis Bebey, Lazarus from Malawi, and Malian fingerstyle guitarist Boubacar "Badian" Diabaté.

episodesByNumber.title: #4279: Trumpet-based New Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the latest work by composer and inventor of the mutantrumpet, Ben Neill, along with new trumpet-based music from Laura Jurd/Dinosaur, Yazz Ahmed, and the band Sex Mob.

episodesByNumber.title: #4280: Laments and Sad Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear an hour of sad songs with  laments from Armenia and Ireland, Greece, Mali, and the U.S.A. from M. Lamar, Marisa Anderson, Savina Yannatou, and Donnacha Dennehy's "The Hunger."

episodesByNumber.title: #4281: With Martin Kohlstedt
episodesByNumber.tease: German pianist and composer Martin Kolstedt presents music from his record, "STRÖME," made in collaboration with Leipzig's Gewandhaus Chorus, and performs in-studio as well.

episodesByNumber.title: #4282: New Releases, Sept. 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new work by computer music composer Carl Stone, Ekhodom (an offshoot of Thievery Corporation), electroacoustic work by Philadelphia-based Nina Keith, and music from Penguin Café.

episodesByNumber.title: #4283: New Music with Harpsichord
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear an hour of new music that features the harpsichord, with works from Polish musician Jacaszek, Norwegian musician Stephan Meidell, and British pianist and composer Poppy Ackroyd.

episodesByNumber.title: #4284: From the Soundcheck Podcast
episodesByNumber.tease: From the Soundcheck Podcast series, listen to country music from Rwanda, Balkan-Klezmer music by Danish outfit Mames Babegenush, and a folk song about a song from Devendra Banhart.

episodesByNumber.title: #4285: Music for Clarinet
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to new music with clarinet, including works by UK composer Anna Meredith, Chicago-based Black Monument Ensemble, American minimalist Steve Reich, and New York's Ken Thomson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4286: Voices and Electronics
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to voices from around the world with electronics with work from computer music composer Carl Stone, Sámi singer Wimme Saari, and American composer Ingram Marshall.

episodesByNumber.title: #4287: From New Sounds Live at Brookfield Place
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from the New Sounds Live concerts recorded at Brookfield Place over the years, with work by Pulitzer Prize winner Caroline Shaw, guitarist Vernon Reid, and Missy Mazzoli.

episodesByNumber.title: #4288: Guitar and Percussion Quartets
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music for percussion quartet by Devonté Hynes in collaboration with Third Coast Percussion, along with new music featuring NY-based electric guitar quartet, Dither.

episodesByNumber.title: #4289: Cross-Cultural Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new cross-cultural music including pieces by Go: Organic Orchestra with Brooklyn Raga Massive, Swedish-South Indian group Nordic Raga, and music by Jamie Branch.

episodesByNumber.title: #4290: Unusual Approaches to the Harp
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to an hour of music for harp, featuring Montreal harpist Sarah Pagé, Joanna Newsom, music by Björk featuring Zeena Parkins, music for kora by Toumani Diabate and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4291: A New Sounds Primer, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to New Sounds from really recently but also as far back as the 12th Century, in works by Brian Eno, Laurie Anderson, Hildegard von Bingen, Anonymous 4, and Poppy Ackroyd.

episodesByNumber.title: #4292: A New Sounds Primer, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear New Sounds with roots in the 12th Century by Qawwali singer Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan, Balinese gamelan-like work by Steve Reich, spiritual music by Alice Coltrane, and Meredith Monk.

episodesByNumber.title: #4293: New Music From Korea
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music from Korea, much of it built around the traditional court instruments like geomungo, piri, and haegum, from Park Jiha, Bora Yoon, Jambinai, and Jin Hi Kim.

episodesByNumber.title: #4294: New Releases, October 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the choicest, newest sounds with enhanced folk by Dublin-based band Lankum, floating soundscapes by vocalist Penelope Trappes, and ensemble work by guitarist/composer Joel Harrison.

episodesByNumber.title: #4295: Dark, Ambient, and Spooky
episodesByNumber.tease: Revel in the sounds of ghosts, vampires, and fake Satanists with music by Valgeir Sigurdsson, Irene and Linda Buckley, and Lustmord. Plus, unsettling music by Jocelyn Pook and Ben Frost.

episodesByNumber.title: #4296: Music for Cello
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music for cello, where Ashley Bathgate plays music by Ted Hearne and Christopher Cerrone, Kate Ellis plays Donnacha Dennehy, and Mariel Roberts plays Mario Diaz de Leon.

episodesByNumber.title: #4297: New Electro-Acoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample an original dance score by Angélica Negrón and French vocalist/composer Muriel Louveau, new music by London-based composer Anna Meredith, and music by French producer Malibu.

episodesByNumber.title: #4298: With Dessa
episodesByNumber.tease: The singer, rapper, and songwriter Dessa visits with the studio to talk about her recent Sound The Bells, with the Minnesota Orchestra, where her songs take on a grand and organic flow.

episodesByNumber.title: #4299: Cross-Cultural Electro-Hybrids
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from around the world by Sami vocalist Mari Boine, Mongolian folk-rockers Hanggai, Ivorian singer and percussionist Antoinette Konan, Syrian singer Omar Souleyman, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4300: Women's Voices, Unsilenced
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music where women reclaim voices lost, with works by Frances White, Shelley Washington, and Eve Beglarian. Plus, Lucy Dhegrae sings Caleb Burhans' "No."

episodesByNumber.title: #4301: New Music for Accordions
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear an accordion-based hour with music by Kepa Junkera from Basque country, Serbian folk-jazz, Norway's Frode Haltli, music by Pauline Oliveros, and Sámi yoik with Finnish accordion.

episodesByNumber.title: #4302: Beyond Chamber Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that goes beyond chamber music with both acoustic and electroacoustic works for keyboard and strings by Shida Shahabi, Mario Diaz de Leon, and Missy Mazzoli with Victoire.

episodesByNumber.title: #4303: New Releases, November 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music from the global duo Farafi, German cellist and composer Anne Müller, New York's Anbessa Orchestra, and works with flow by Mae.Sun and Chicago-based bassist Junius Paul.

episodesByNumber.title: #4304:﻿ Music for the Anthropocene
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works by Shara Nova, Pascal le Boeuf, Paola Prestini, Philip Glass, Mike Sayre, and Emily Wells that all respond to climate change and humanity's effect on Planet Earth.

episodesByNumber.title: #4305: Bach Meets Bollywood in Latest by Steve Reich
episodesByNumber.tease: Steve Reich, one of the most influential composers of the past half century, makes a return visit to the studio to introduce his latest work, "Music For Ensemble And Orchestra."

episodesByNumber.title: #4306: Mystical Meets Modern
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear contemporary responses to the Abrahamic traditions: Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, plus tanbur music from Iranian musician Ostad Elahi and Shona mbira music from Zimbabwe.

episodesByNumber.title: #4307: Southern Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a new folk opera by composer and pianist Rachel Grimes based on generations of Kentucky women (1775-present), along with music by Rhiannon Giddens, and the late William Duckworth.

episodesByNumber.title: #4308: Jazz Meets Indian Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music where Western jazz and Indian classical music come together in work by drummer Adam Rudolph, guitarist Joel Harrison, drummer Brian Shankar Adler, and harpist Alice Coltrane.

episodesByNumber.title: #4309: With Laurie Anderson
episodesByNumber.tease: New York-based composer-artist Laurie Anderson holds forth on the spiritual and transporting "Songs From the Bardo," an offering of sound and words for foreground listening.

episodesByNumber.title: #4310: Acoustic-Electronic Hybrids
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear cello, voices, violin, guitars and drums, in hybrid electro-acoustic settings by supergroup Whistling Arrow, Norway's Lumen Drones, Julianna Barwick, and cellist Ashley Bathgate.

episodesByNumber.title: #4311: Steve Reich: Music for 18 Musicians, New Sounds Live 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live Concerts, recorded in October 2019 at Brookfield Place, Ensemble Signal and Brad Lubman perform Steve Reich's masterwork Music for 18 Musicians.

episodesByNumber.title: #4312; A Different Kind of Christmas Carol
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that may come as a relief from the usual holiday soundtrack by sound artist Tim Story, guitarists Shane Parish and Gwenifer Raymond, and music by Bonny Light Horseman.

episodesByNumber.title: #4313: The Top 10 of 2019
episodesByNumber.tease: John Schaefer presents his annual top 10 list of new music from 2019. Hear music by Rhiannon Giddens and Francesco Turrisi, Kate Tempest, Matana Roberts, Lankum, and Julia Wolfe.
tags: young peoples chorus of new york city

episodesByNumber.title: #4314: New Approaches to Folk Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new takes on old folk traditions - whether from the British Isles or Appalachia - including music by Lankum, Windborne, Bonny Light Horseman, and Irish singer Dàibhidh Stiùbhard.

episodesByNumber.title: #4315: Steve Reich: Works, from NSL at Brookfield Place
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concerts, recorded at Brookfield Place in October 2019, hear music for multiples by Steve Reich, played by Ensemble Signal, and other music inspired by Reich.

episodesByNumber.title: #4316: Music for Cello
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Icelandic cellist-composer Hildur Guðnadóttir, along with cellist Maya Beiser taking on Bowie's final record. Plus, cellist Ashley Bathgate plays Jacob Cooper, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4317 Music with AI and Interactive Electronics
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music with artificial intelligence or interactive electronics from Berlin-based Holly Herndon, Iranian-born Ash Koosha, pianist Dan Tepfer, and producer Floating Spectrum.

episodesByNumber.title: #4318: Composer-Led Ensembles
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from composer-led ensembles, from works by Penguin Café, Missy Mazzoli/Victoire, Laura Jurd and Dinosaur, Shards, NOW Ensemble, Anna Meredith, and Matt McBane/Build.

episodesByNumber.title: #4319: Minimalism Meets Jazz
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the juxtaposition of minimalism's rhythmic riffs and the groove of jazz in music by Alexis Cuadrado's Nonet, and Numinous, the 20-player group led by Joseph C. Phillips, Jr.

episodesByNumber.title: #4320: Electroacoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to work that exists in the spaces between electronic and acoustic in music by Montreal-based cellist Rebecca Foon, Vernon Reid and Laraaji, and saxophonist Jonah Parzen-Johnson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4321: Variations on Koyaanisqatsi
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, hear some of the Philip Glass score for Godfrey Reggio's silent film Koyaanisqatsi – along with alternative soundtracks from GoGo Penguin and Courtney Hartman.

episodesByNumber.title: #4322: Extending the Folk Tradition
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear modern extensions of the folk tradition with new music by Dublin-based Varo, Danish musician Myrkur, UK-based Sam Lee, American guitarist Rafiq Bhatia, and Bonny Light Horseman.

episodesByNumber.title: #4323: Marimbas and Xylophones Around the World
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music for xylophone and marimba by Mexican garage-cumbia-marimba-punk band Son Rompe Pera, Basque band Oreka Tx, UK's Vula Viel, and Vienna-based Mamadou Diabate  &  Percussion Mania.

episodesByNumber.title: #4324: New Releases, Jan. 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new releases from the UK folk singer Sam Lee, Cuban pianist-composer Roberto Fonseca, and from banjo master Bela Fleck together with kora master Toumani Diabate.

episodesByNumber.title: #4325: Music Inspired by Nature
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works inspired by or related to the natural world by the Icelandic composer María Huld Markan Sigfúsdóttir, Apollo Chamber Players, big dog little dog, and John Luther Adams.

episodesByNumber.title: #4326: Bands Led by Sax Players
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from bands led by sax players like London-based Collocutor (Tamar Osborn), The Comet Is Coming (Shabaka Hutchings), and Alabaster de Plume, and one-man band Colin Stetson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4327: Stateless Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by people without a homeland, with music from the Hazaras of Central Asia by Hamid Sakhizada, Uighurs of western China by Qetiq, the Wulu Bunun (Taiwan), and Kurdish melodies.

episodesByNumber.title: #4328: Joseph Shabalala, In Memoriam
episodesByNumber.tease: For this New Sounds, celebrate the life and music of singer, songwriter, leader, and founder Joseph Shabalala and the a cappella group he founded, South Africa's Ladysmith Black Mambazo.

episodesByNumber.title: #4329: The New Prog-Rock
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that plays with rhythm, form, and genre with music from trumpeter Kate Amrine, guitarist Jeff Parker (Tortoise), composer Anna Meredith, London duo Tomaga, and early Battles.

episodesByNumber.title: #4330, Musicians From the 1980s (New Sounds-Style)
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a look back at where the show once was with music by Algerian trio Djur Djura, Syrian singer Abed Azrie, Norwegian pianist Ketil Bjørnstad, and Pat Metheny with the late Lyle Mays.

episodesByNumber.title: #4331: NS Live/Ecstatic Music - Bang on a Can PCF 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear world premieres inspired by dance by sound artists Amanda Berlind and Alvin Curran, Icelandic cellist Hildur Guðnadóttir and drummer Qasim Naqvi - played by Bang on a Can All-Stars.

episodesByNumber.title: #4332: Contemporary and Secular Prayers
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear contemporary and secular prayers by New York composers Kitty Brazelton, Missy Mazzoli, Son Lux, and electric violist Martha Mooke. Plus, music by Colin Stetson and Sarah Neufeld.

episodesByNumber.title: #4333: From New Sounds Live 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music from the New Sounds Live 2020 Concerts from both the Bang on a Can All-Stars PCF Concert at Merkin Hall and Vernon Reid's film score to Frankenstein, at Brookfield Place.

episodesByNumber.title: #4334: New Releases, February 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear voices deployed in music by Berlin's Lyra Pramuk, Brooklyn's Alex Dowling, and sound designer Katie Gately. Plus new work from string quintet Sybarite5 and Polish composer Jacaszek.

episodesByNumber.title: #4335: West Meets India, Again
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear collaborative music from the Indian-Scottish-English folk trio Yorkston/Thorne/Khan, Baltimore-based Ami Dang, and South African guitarist Guy Buttery with sitarist Kanada Narahari.

episodesByNumber.title: #4336: Okwui Okpokwasili and Peter Born
episodesByNumber.tease: Multidisciplinary artist Okwui Okpokwasili and director Peter Born talk with John Schaefer about their new album, plus some "hocket" music from Meredith Monk and Meara O'Reilly.

episodesByNumber.title: #4337: Music for Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: Plucked, bowed and strummed: hear unusual music for strings from composers Peteris Vasks, Christopher Cerrone, Oliver Leith, and Anna Thorvaldsdottir.

episodesByNumber.title: #4338: Music for Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear ye, hear ye! Hear music for the voice by Eriks Esenvalds, Lyra Pramuk, Jessica Meyer and James MacMillan.

episodesByNumber.title: #4339: New Sounds Live 2020– Kelly Moran and Missy Mazzoli, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: From New Sounds Live 2020, Part 1: Composers and keyboardists Missy Mazzoli and Kelly Moran join John Schaefer at Merkin Hall to play new works for pianos and prepared piano.

episodesByNumber.title: #4340: New Sounds Live 2020 – Kelly Moran and Missy Mazzoli, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: From New Sounds Live 2020, Part 2: Composers and keyboardists Missy Mazzoli and Kelly Moran join John Schaefer at Merkin Hall to play new works for pianos and prepared piano.

episodesByNumber.title: #4341: Pop Meets Classical
episodesByNumber.tease: When pop meets classical - Hear music by Dessa, Emily King and yMusic, Martin Kohlstedt, Efterklang, and Yasiin Bey and Brooklyn Philharmonic.

episodesByNumber.title: #4342: Music of Calm
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music of calm by British composer Poppy Ackroyd, Italian guitarists Pino Forastiere and Paolo Angeli, and music by Norwegians Nils Petter Molvær and Trond Kallevåg Hansen.

episodesByNumber.title: #4343, with Theo Bleckmann Trio, From On Air Fest 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample music by vocalist and new music composer Theo Bleckmann, both from his live trio set at On Air Fest 2020, and from his collaborative work with Kneebody and Joseph Branciforte.

episodesByNumber.title: #4344, Songs of the Apocalypse
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to London-based cosmic electro-jazz from The Comet Is Coming, along with Shabaka and the Ancestors, Peter Gabriel, Vikingur Olafsson repurposing Bach, and bluesman Son House.

episodesByNumber.title: #4345, Music in Motion
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to Japanese pianist Hiromi, German composer Daniel Brandt, and Australian trio The Necks, and music by two Swiss composers, Maja Nydegge with Blaer, and Nik Bärtsch's Ronin.

episodesByNumber.title: #4346, New Sounds Live: Silent Films/Live Music 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to world premieres from the Silent Films/Live Music series by Alexis Cuadrado and Vernon Reid, recorded in January 2020 at Brookfield Place.

episodesByNumber.title: #4347, New Releases, March 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music from Sandbox Percussion by David Crowell, South African guitarists Guy Buttery and Derek Gripper together in concert, and work by Molly Joyce for GVSU New Music Ensemble.
tags: grand valley state university new music ensemble

episodesByNumber.title: #4348, Pete M. Wyer's 'The Sky Beneath Our Feet'
episodesByNumber.tease: British composer Pete M. Wyer presents The Sky Beneath Our Feet, a new 72-channel work written for an outdoor installation at Descanso Gardens. Pete joins John remotely from London.

episodesByNumber.title: #4349, with Lankum from the Soundcheck Podcast
episodesByNumber.tease: The band Lankum, "Dublin folk miscreants," infuses traditional folk songs with the dark drone of psychedelia and an underlying punk rawness. Back in early 2020, they played in-studio.

episodesByNumber.title: #4350: Celebrating Ravi Shankar
episodesByNumber.tease: To celebrate the 101st birthday of the late sitar master Ravi Shankar (1920-2012), hear rare archival in-studio performances  &  collaborations, including one with his daughter, Anoushka.

episodesByNumber.title: #4351, Music Drawn from Jewish Traditions
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that draws from various Jewish mystical traditions, including work by Galeet Dardashti and Divahn, Frank London, Basya Schecter, Andy Statman, and John Zorn.

episodesByNumber.title: #4352, Remembering Hal Willner
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to a musical tribute to Hal Wilner, the American music producer and SNL music supervisor, who died this week. Hear some of his brilliant compilation records and a 2013 interview.

episodesByNumber.title: #4353, NSL Silent Films - Gogo Penguin Scores Koyaanisqatsi
episodesByNumber.tease: From the New Sounds Live concert series from January 2020, the Manchester trio GoGo Penguin plays their original score to the 1982 Godfrey Reggio film Koyaanisqatsi, at Brookfield Place.

episodesByNumber.title: #4354, Mediterranea
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music rooted in ancient Mediterranean traditions by Occitan trio Cocanha, Sardinian trumpet player Paolo Fresu, Spanish guitarist Efren Lopez, Croatian band Kries, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4355, The Qawwali Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the Sufi devotional music of Pakistan by Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan, the "Queen of Qawwali," Abida Parveen, clarinetist Arun Ghosh, NYC-based Falsa, Siti Muharam of Zanzibar, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4356, Broadcasting From Home
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by Argentine singer-producer Juana Molina, Russian sound sculptor Kate NV, fingerstyle guitar from Senegal by Tidiane Thiam, and music from the Penguin Cafe Orchestra.

episodesByNumber.title: #4357, Music for Earth Day
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear work inspired by America's National Parks from the GVSU New Music Ensemble, by the Mojave Desert from Floating Points, and by Alaska's arctic vistas from John Luther Adams and ACME.
tags: grand valley state university new music ensemble

episodesByNumber.title: #4358, Guitars and Other Machines
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear guitars and other machines by Alex de Grassi on sympitar, 12-string adapted guitar by the Garlands, oud from Gordon Grdina, and guzheng and banjo by Wu Fei and Abigail Washburn.

episodesByNumber.title: #4359, Music of Trees
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear various music of trees in works by Berlin producer Pantha Du Prince, drummer Susie Ibarra for Ethos Percussion, and music from the Palestinian oud-playing brothers of Trio Joubran.

episodesByNumber.title: #4360, John Henry's Hammer
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music about steel drivin' man John Henry - specifically music about his hammer. Listen to works from Mississippi John Hurt, Julia Wolfe, Odetta, Our Native Daughters, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4361, New Releases, April 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some music made during quarantine, as well as what was made in the before times with works by Clarice Jensen, Sarathy Korwar, Frode Haltli, and New York saxman Steve Lehman.

episodesByNumber.title: #4362, A Tribute to Reverend Gary Davis
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a New York Guitar Festival tribute to bluesman Reverend Gary Davis with music from Fantastic Negrito, Larkin Poe, Rosanne Cash, singer/songwriter Amythyst Kiah, and Bill Frisell.

episodesByNumber.title: #4363, Music for Brass
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear mystical brass music from Messiaen, music for mutantrumpet by Ben Neill, and music from underground – a huge reverberant cistern in Washington, featuring trumpet from Daniel Barry.

episodesByNumber.title: #4364, Twisted Drones
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to drones, bagpipe and banjo by French band Super Parquet, music by Brooklyn cellist Clarice Jensen, and drone music built around the sounds of Indiana bats from Field Works.

episodesByNumber.title: #4365, Music for Layered Voices
episodesByNumber.tease: For this edition of New Sounds, listen to music for layered voices, by Canadian Sarah Davachi, UK's Collectress, New York's Lesley Flanigan, Brooklyn's Julianna Barwick, and Brian Eno.

episodesByNumber.title: #4366, Music for Multiples
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear flute multiples in music by Steve Reich featuring Claire Chase, Donnacha Dennehy's "Tessellatum" for multiple violas, and violas da gamba, and harp multiples by Mary Lattimore.

episodesByNumber.title: #4367, Music With Small String Instruments
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear small stringed instruments, perhaps folkloric, like mandolin, Greek bouzouki, Argentinian ronroco, and the cuatro - in music by Penguin Café, Son Lux, and Gustavo Santaolalla.

episodesByNumber.title: #4368, Musical Crossings
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from the Garifuna people of Central America, Occitan trio Cocanha from Toulouse, and the Canadian-Iranian-Senegalese collaboration of Constantinople and Ablaye Cissoko.

episodesByNumber.title: #4369, In This Garden
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to ostensibly garden-themed works, with several settings of William Blake poetry, Sam Lee's folk-song reworking, and beauty and dread in a work by trumpeter Ambrose Akinmusire.

episodesByNumber.title: #4370, Baroque Meets Contemporary
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample musical meetings between Baroque and new music with takes on Vivaldi by Sophie Tassignon and Max Richter, plus Baroque ensembles in  new music by Richard Einhorn and Marc Mellits.

episodesByNumber.title: #4371, Western Instruments Playing Ragas
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear raga-based music on Western classical instruments from Sharon Isbin and Amjad Ali Khan, pianist Sophia Subbayya Vastek, and sax player Jan Garbarek with Ustad Fateh Ali Khan.

episodesByNumber.title: #4372, New Releases, May 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: It's new music for May 2020, with works from Manchester trio GoGo Penguin, Dublin-based Australian flute player Lina Andonovska, eclectic chamber band Endangered Quartet, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4373, Music for Asian Gardens
episodesByNumber.tease: We're back to nature with music inspired by or using the sounds of temple gardens in Kyoto, and themed around other Asian gardens, in works by Evan Ziporyn, John Cage, and Tôsha Suihô.

episodesByNumber.title: #4374, It's About Justice
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music by bass player Vic Wooten, composer Shelley Washington, pianist Vijay Iyer with spoken word artist Mike Ladd, and clarinetist Don Byron with bassist Robert Black.

episodesByNumber.title: #4375: New Versions of 19th Century American Songs
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear contemporary versions of songs of the 19th Century by Henry Clay Work and Stephen Foster, as well as hymns and traditional folksongs that criss-cross the oceans and the centuries.

episodesByNumber.title: #4376, Music About Homelessness and Gentrification
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music that deals with gentrification and homelessness by Brooklyn-based iT Boy, Michael Gordon and The Crossing, Gabriel Kahane, and Ted Hearne with poet Saul Williams.

episodesByNumber.title: #4377, Music for Didjeridoo
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music for and inspired by didjeridoo - the indigenous Australian drone wind instrument - from Trance Mission, David Hudson, Stuart Dempster, and Lester Bowie's Brass Fantasy.

episodesByNumber.title: #4378,  Music with Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to new music for guitar by Kaki King, Gyan Riley, Noveller, and the California Guitar Trio, with processed and altered guitar, modified guitar, and classical and electric guitars.

episodesByNumber.title: #4379, With Pedal Steel Guitarist Luke Schneider
episodesByNumber.tease: Nashville-based pedal steel guitarist Luke Schneider plays with Margo Price and Orville Peck, but his latest is an ambient atmospheric album of pedal steel guitar. Hear that, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4380, Juneteenth
episodesByNumber.tease: To mark Juneteenth, a recast spiritual by Lara Downes, Black roots music from Jake Blount and Rhiannon Giddens, a multimedia work by Vernon Reid, and guitar wizardry by Yasmin Williams.

episodesByNumber.title: #4381, New Releases, June 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: For June, hear new music from an Afro-Brazilian quartet based in London called Let Drum Beat, Nigerian bass player Michael Olatuja, and Norwegian guitarists Stein Urheim and Kim Myhr.

episodesByNumber.title: #4382, Celebrating Birdsong
episodesByNumber.tease: Get back to nature with the sound of birdsongs, featuring music by Monte, aka Simón Mejía, founder and co-leader of Bomba Estereo. Plus music by Jocelyn Pook and John Luther Adams.

episodesByNumber.title: #4383: New Music For Guitar
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample from inventive recordings for guitar, and the interesting ways that one can extend the guitar in music by Yasmin Williams, Kaki King, Buck Curran, Pino Forastiere, and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4384, Ennio Morricone, In Memoriam
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample music by the the influential Italian composer Ennio Morricone, and music from those who were influenced by him, including John Zorn, Tin Hat Trio, and SUSS. Morricone was 91.

episodesByNumber.title: #4385, Recent Art-Pop
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear "art-pop" from songwriters who also work in contemporary classical circles, with music by Hanna Benn, Montreal's Thanya Iyer, Chicago-based OHMME, Molly Joyce, and Owen Pallett.

episodesByNumber.title: #4386: Just Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music in the tuning called just intonation from La Monte Young, Christopher Cerrone for the Argus Quartet, Michael Harrison for Roomful of Teeth, Pauline Oliveros, and Terry Riley.

episodesByNumber.title: #4387: New Music, Old Instruments and Bardcore
episodesByNumber.tease: Who doesn't love a lute, or a cittern, or a vielle? Hear new music made on old instruments, along with some "Bardcore" - or contemporary pop music re-worked on medieval instruments.

episodesByNumber.title: #4388: Music Inspired by Shakespeare
episodesByNumber.tease: It's a literary edition of the show, featuring music inspired by Shakespeare's plays and sonnets - by Jocelyn Pook, Caroline Shaw, Michael Nyman, Hans Abrahamsen, and Andrew Norman.

episodesByNumber.title: #4389, With David Moore of Bing & Ruth
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer David Moore, leader of the band Bing  &  Ruth, plays music from the brand new record, Species, an exercise in trance and suspended time built around 1960s-vintage Farfisa organ.

episodesByNumber.title: #4390, Music About Birds
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music where birds serve as omens, with songs about ravens, crows, and magpies, by folks singing on both sides of the Atlantic from Adrian Crowley, HITE, Lankum, and Mount Eerie.

episodesByNumber.title: #4391, New Sounds of Morocco
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music ranging from Andalusian classical, electronic works, and pieces built on hypnotic Gnawa rhythms. Plus, a German-Moroccan collaboration, and Moroccan-Jewish music as well.

episodesByNumber.title: #4392, Roots Music, Old and New
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music with roots in the folk from both sides of the Atlantic, in traditional and/or original songs from Cinder Well, Tiny Leaves, Bonny Light Horseman, and the Unthanks.

episodesByNumber.title: #4393, New Music, Old Rhythms
episodesByNumber.tease: Traditional rhythms meet modern sounds in contemporary production, drawing on music from Haiti, Croatia, Southern Italy, Tunisia, Chad, Uganda, and an Israeli-Indian collaboration.

episodesByNumber.title: #4394, Music About Machines
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to many machine-inspired works by Marc Mellits, along with music from factory samples and heavy machinery by Annie Gosfield. Plus, music by Dan Román, Leah Kardos, and Kraftwerk.

episodesByNumber.title: #4395, July New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new work by pianist and producer Thomas Bartlett, aka Doveman, the world premiere of music by composer David Cieri for carillon, and new music for lever harp from Lauren Scott.

episodesByNumber.title: #4396, Music From and About the African Diaspora
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from the African Diaspora for this show by the supergroup project Keleketla!, Shabaka  &  the Ancestors, and work from the Art Ensemble of Chicago, featuring Moor Mother.

episodesByNumber.title: #4397, Musical Journeys
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear meetings of musical traditions in work by Silk Road tabla player Sandeep Das and the HUM Ensemble, a Punjabi and Welsh song hybrid, and a Persian and Indian classical combination.

episodesByNumber.title: #4398: Commemorating Hiroshima
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music to mark the 75th anniversary of the bombing of Hiroshima, by Japanese composer Toshiya Sukegawa, by John Adams from his opera, Doctor Atomic, and work by Robert Een.

episodesByNumber.title: #4399, Rock me Amadeus, Part 4  , Mostly Mozart (Fringe) Festival -
episodesByNumber.tease: As part of our week-long Mostly Mozart fringe festival to augment Mostly Mozart on WQXR, listen to Part 4 of the multi-part series "Rock Me Amadeus."

episodesByNumber.title: #4400, Rock Me Amadeus, Part 5, Mostly Mozart (Fringe) Festival -
episodesByNumber.tease: Mozart meets glissandos of Gloria Coates, plays with Southern Italian folk and traditional Arab classical music for this fifth and final episode in the Mostly Mozart "Fringe" Festival.

episodesByNumber.title: #4401, New Music: The Next Generation
