episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music featuring Brooklyn Youth Chorus, Young People's Chorus, and 10th-graders at Kaufman Music Center's Special Music School collaborating with Nathalie Joachim.
tags: grand valley state university new music ensemble
young peoples chorus of new york city

episodesByNumber.title: #4402, New Releases, August 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample music from South African cellist Abel Selaocoe, London sax player Nubya Garcia's debut record, Source, Irish composer Dave Flynn and Dan Deacon's music for extreme dog grooming.

episodesByNumber.title: #4403, New Music for Flutes
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear flute in different contexts in recent music by Nicole Mitchell and Christopher Cerrone, along with a classic Steve Reich work for multiple layers of flute featuring Claire Chase.

episodesByNumber.title: #4404 Earth, Seen From Above
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to songs with the perspective of watching Earth, with works by Meredith Monk, Kate Bush, and from harpist Mary Lattimore, a work in tribute to the astronaut Scott Kelly

episodesByNumber.title: #4405, Drone-Folk
episodesByNumber.tease: Focus on the implied drones of folk music in tunes by French quartet Super Parquet and Irish quartet Lankum, along with doom folk by Cinder Well, and electroacoustic folk by Tunng.

episodesByNumber.title: #4406, Strings and Things
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to works built around strings, mostly without voices, and one involving crystal goblets as drone, featuring J. Pavone String Ensemble, Galax Quartet, and Gyða Valtýsdóttir.

episodesByNumber.title: #4407, Tributes to Pete Seeger, Woody Guthrie, and Leadbelly
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear contemporary takes on songs associated with American folk singers Pete Seeger, Woody Guthrie, and Leadbelly as performed by Kronos Quartet, Wenzel, and Last Forever.

episodesByNumber.title: #4408: With or Without Electronics: Piano Edition
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear piano etudes by Philip Glass, as played by Simone Dinnerstein, and piano with electronics by Irish composer Linda Buckley, London-based Theo Alexander, and Icelandic duo Hugar.

episodesByNumber.title: #4409: Music Bridging Conflict and Cultures
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music bringing together Greek and Turkish musicians from SYNERGIA, a new record curated by Dmitri Psonis. Also, music by Norwegian improvisers, baroque players and North Africans.

episodesByNumber.title: #4410, Good Vibes (and Other Mallet Percussion)
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music with good vibes -erm, for vibraphone - and music based around other mallet percussion by Australian band Tangents, London-based Vula Viel, and Ethiojazz legend Mulatu Astatke.

episodesByNumber.title: #4411, Alt-Latinx Music from South America
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works combining old and new, where traditional folk and environmental sounds of South America come together with electronics, in music by Monte, Chancha via Circuito, and La Yegros.

episodesByNumber.title: #4412, Mystical Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear mystical works inspired by the Sufi tradition and/or by the Abrahamic faiths of Judaism, Christianity and Islam by Sarathy Korwar, Jozef van Wissem, and the Soundwalk Collective.

episodesByNumber.title: #4413, Music About Climate Change
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear climate crisis-inspired music by Kazakh-British Galya Bisengalieva, along with music from Montreal's Saltland, Norway's Marja Mortensson and Daniel Herskedal, and John Luther Adams.

episodesByNumber.title: #4414, New Releases, Sep. 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new releases by the Father of Ethiojazz, Mulatu Astatke, with the Black Jesus Experience, work by sound artist Joshua Van Tassel for Ondea, and a new mass by Sarah Kirkland Snider.

episodesByNumber.title: #4415: Anna Clyne, Irene Buckley, Linda Buckley
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear two unconventional violin concertos, music for film, and a sound installation for this New Sounds by London-born Anna Clyne, and Irish sibling composers Irene and Linda Buckley.

episodesByNumber.title: #4416, New Music for Saxes
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music featuring the saxophone - inspired by West African rhythms and Ethiojazz - by World Saxophone Quartet, London-based Nubya Garcia, Jesse Wilms, and Norwich trio Mammal Hands.

episodesByNumber.title: #4417, Echoes of Thomas Tallis
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Thomas Tallis' hit motet for 40 voices and a modern-day reflection by James MacMillan. Plus, music by Caroline Shaw for cello, and The Tallis Scholars sing work by Sir John Tavener.

episodesByNumber.title: #4418, Inventive Piano Trios
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear reinventions of the piano trio  -that piano, bass, and drums format- for this New Sounds with work from GoGo Penguin, Soojin Suh Coloris Trio, Neil Cowley Trio, and The Bad Plus.

episodesByNumber.title: #4419: Recent Recordings From Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some recent recordings from Mauritania's Veyrouz Mint Seymali, Somaliland's Sahra Halgan Trio, Nigerien guitarist Bombino, Rwanda's The Good Ones, and South Africa's Vusi Mahlasela.

episodesByNumber.title: #4420, Three Influential American Composers: Cage, Harrison, Feldman
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works from 20th Century American "maverick" composers John Cage, Morton Feldman and Lou Harrison, on this show for piano, violin and piano, and violin, piano, and percussion.

episodesByNumber.title: #4421, Music Made During Quarantine
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some music made in quarantine by Anglo-Polish musician Alice Zawadzki, Anglo-Indian composer/drummer Sarathy Korwar, and London-based Syrian kanun player and composer Maya Youssef.

episodesByNumber.title: #4422, The Tale of Fair Margaret and Sweet William
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to some of the many versions of the Tale of Fair Margaret and Sweet William – a doomed love affair –from Sam Amidon, Rhiannon Giddens, Robert Plant, and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4423, Ethiopian Music Around the World
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample Ethiopian music from around the world – from Addis Abbaba and the "Golden Age" of Ethiopop, and music from France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Israel, Australia, and the U.S.A.

episodesByNumber.title: #4424, New Releases, Oct. 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: There's new music by Belgium's Echo Collective involving magnetic resonator piano, orchestral music from Sigur Ros, and mathy work by Swiss composer Stephan Thelen for Kronos Quartet.

episodesByNumber.title: #4425, Hope
episodesByNumber.tease: Lend thine ears to songs of hope in fingerstyling guitar by Yasmin Williams, chamber-jazz by Chicago pianist Ryan Cohan, and work by the Neil Cowley Trio. Plus, music by Tiny Leaves.

episodesByNumber.title: #4426, A World of Brass
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a Swiss brass band take on Indonesian gamelan music, Afrobeat from Antibalas, and brass music from both North and South India courtesy of Red Baraat and Aditya Prakash Ensemble.

episodesByNumber.title: #4427, Lucky Sevens
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music in sevens featuring Serbian jazzers EYOT, Taiwanese pipa player Yufeng Chung with an Indonesian gamelan, Greek band Trio Tekke, and east coast big band, Wing Walker Orchestra.

episodesByNumber.title: #4428, Violin, Plus...
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music for violin, with the possible addition of voice, electronics, resonant spaces, and/or inventive bowing techniques by Laura Cannell, Mari Kimura, Iva Bittova, and Jessica Moss.

episodesByNumber.title: #4429, Wish I Were There...
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Albanian accordion on a trip to Japan, Japanese band Minyo Crusaders takes on Colombian music, and a now-classic collaboration between Malian and Cuban musicians, Afrocubism.

episodesByNumber.title: #4430, Vintage Music for Analog Synths
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to vintage works for analogue synthesizers by three pioneering composers: sound artist Alvin Curran, minimalist composer Terry Riley, and electronic music pioneer Laurie Spiegel.

episodesByNumber.title: #4431, Three Musical Tales
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear three recent musical tales featuring a woman's voice: 'The Grey Land' by Joseph C. Phillips Jr., 'A Cockroach's Tarantella' by Du Yun and 'The Anchoress' by David Serkin Ludwig.

episodesByNumber.title: #4432, The Indian Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear several works influenced by Indian ragas, like Brooklyn Raga Massive's "In D," percussionist Rajna Swaminathan's group RAJAS, and jazzy-sounding raga by Boston's Natraj.

episodesByNumber.title: #4433, Music From the Dark Forest
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music about the cursed wood with its seductive dangers by Finnish folk violinist and vocalist Meriheini Luoto, Ukraine's Mariana Sadovska, and Brussels/Paris-based band Lolomis.

episodesByNumber.title: #4434: Homespun Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: There's homespun charm, electronics, and real world sounds in piano music by Iceland's Ólafur Arnalds, German composer Martin Kohlstedt, and Brighton, UK-based Poppy Ackroyd.

episodesByNumber.title: #4435, Songs of Thanksgiving
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music by Pete M. Wyer based on a Mohawk thanksgiving ceremony, a Thanksgiving song by one-woman band, Grouper, and large ensemble music of gratitude by guitarist Joel Harrison.

episodesByNumber.title: #4436, New Releases, November 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear work by harpist Brandee Younger and bassist Dezron Douglas, string quartet music based on Tuvan throat singing and actual throat singing from Mongolia by Khusugtun. And more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4437, Music for Islamic Voices and Western Instruments
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Islamic and Arabic voices with western instruments in work by Norwegian Jon Balke and Moroccan singer Amina Alaoui, Anglo-Egyptian singer Natacha Atlas, and Sir John Tavener.

episodesByNumber.title: #4438, With Eric Chasalow
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer, professor, and multi-instrumentalist Eric Chasalow talks us through the sweep of his new electro-acoustic, folky,  rockenroll sonic memoir, "Ghosts of our Former Selves."

episodesByNumber.title: #4439, Harold Budd, Magos Herrera & Paola Prestini
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music that celebrates female voices by Magos Herrera and Paola Prestini from their new record, 'Con Alma,' as well as music by Harold Budd, who has died, at age 84.
tags: young peoples chorus of new york city

episodesByNumber.title: #4440: Max Richter’s ‘Voices’ On Human Rights Day
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Max Richter's "Voices," for orchestra, chorus, electronics, and taped voices in many languages reading the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, Dec. 10 at 10PM on 93.9FM WNYC.

episodesByNumber.title: #4441: Beethoven Immortal Part 1: Riffing on Beethoven
episodesByNumber.tease: For Beethoven Immortal, Pt. 1, hear electronic and electroacoustic works based on or inspired by Beethoven from Wendy Carlos, Christian Löffler, Christopher Tignor and Hollas Longton.

episodesByNumber.title: #4442: Beethoven Immortal, Part 2: Contemporary Reflections of Beethoven
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear variations on and rearrangements of Beethoven in works by Bang on a Can Co-Founder Michael Gordon, Grammy Award-winning John Corigliano, and California minimalist Ingram Marshall.

episodesByNumber.title: #4443, With Pete M. Wyer: iForest - For Love and Only for Love
episodesByNumber.tease: London composer Pete M. Wyer joins Schaefer from London to present "For Love and Only for Love," opening at the NYBG. Plus, works by British composers Errollyn Wallen and Alison Cotton.

episodesByNumber.title: #4444, Musical Kaleidoscopes
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music that takes an anything goes approach from Rob Mazurek's Exploding Star Orchestra, a boisterous piece from Tyondai Braxton, work by JG Thirlwell and Simon Steenland, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4445, Music With Wine Glasses
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to pieces featuring wine glasses by Paula Matthusen, George Crumb, Joseph Schwantner, Daniel Lentz, and Canadian composer Gordon Fitzell.

episodesByNumber.title: #4446: The Top 10 of 2020
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to John Schaefer's annual top ten show featuring music about gentrification, Icelandic epics, an opera about being Black in America, and reworkings of traditional folk music.

episodesByNumber.title: #4447, Music For Rivers, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: From the Niger River in Mali in music by Bassekou Kouyate  &  Ngoni Ba to the Magdalena River in Colombia in music by Monte, hear music about specific rivers and rivers in general.

episodesByNumber.title: #4448, Music For Rivers, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music of forced migration up the Mississippi River by Charles Lloyd and Jason Moran, and the work, "Yellow River" from Korean cellist Okkyung Lee et al, and more music about rivers.

episodesByNumber.title: #4449,  Indian Voices With Western Ensembles
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Indian vocalists (North and South India) together with western musicians and instruments with music from playback singer Asha Bhosle to Anglo-Indian singer Najma, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4450, Music Made of Natural Sounds
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music by composers who use natural sound as source material with work by Portland-based Amanda Berlind, Minnesota-born, NYC-based Elori Saxl, and Philadelphia-based Nina Keith.

episodesByNumber.title: #4451, Music by Sax Player/Composers (Mostly)
episodesByNumber.tease: Matthew Evan Taylor creates music for layers of saxophone, Lea Bertucci uses an empty grain silo for layers of processed alto sax, and Viet Cuong writes glides for PRISM Sax Quartet.

episodesByNumber.title: #4452, So Percussion, Angélica Negrón, and Darian Donovan Thomas via Brookfield Place
episodesByNumber.tease: From New Sounds Live, recorded (and filmed) in fall 2020 at the Winter Garden of Brookfield Place, hear works by Sō Percussion and guests Angélica Negrón and Darian Donovan Thomas.

episodesByNumber.title: #4453, New Sounds Live: Yasmin Williams and Kaki King in Brookfield Place
episodesByNumber.tease: From New Sounds Live at Brookfield Place, recorded in fall 2020, guitarists/composers Kaki King and Yasmin Williams create wordless songs using the 6-string guitar in innovative ways.

episodesByNumber.title: #4454, New Releases, January 2021
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the newest sounds from January with music from Montreal's Bell Orchestre, percussionist Michael Wimberly, vibraphonist Patricia Brennan, and London-based experimental duo Tomaga.

episodesByNumber.title: #4455, Music With Brass
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear original brass music by Seattle quartet The Westerlies with Theo Bleckmann, new songs by CARM, aka CJ Camerieri of yMusic, and Thelonious Monk arranged for brass quintet.

episodesByNumber.title: #4456, Music for Harp and Bass and Caroline Shaw's 'Narrow Sea'
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music for harp and bass, featuring Brandee Younger and Dezron Douglas, the River Town Duo in a work by Caroline Shaw, and Shaw's "Narrow Sea," for soprano, piano, and percussion.

episodesByNumber.title: #4457, Inspired by Films of Wim Wenders
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music inspired by films of Oscar-nominated German filmmaker Wim Wenders, and vice versa, from French pianist Gregory Ott, guitarist Ry Cooder, and the Buena Vista Social Club.

episodesByNumber.title: #4458, Music With Bowed Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: We're serving up new music made with bowed strings from New York composer Tristan Perich, Georgian composer Gio Janiashvili, London-based Oliver Leith and Belgian band, Echo Collective.

episodesByNumber.title: #4459, New Music For Flute(s)
episodesByNumber.tease: Get into new music for flute and electronics by Du Yun and Marcos Balter for Claire Chase, part of her Density 2036 commissioning project. Plus, Frances White's music for shakuhachi.

episodesByNumber.title: #4460, Music From the Francophone Diaspora
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music with French-based singing, in Occitan by vocal sextet San Salvador, in French Creole from Haiti by Nathalie Joachim, as well as songs in Cajun and Quebecois dialects.

episodesByNumber.title: #4461, Musical Landscapes,
episodesByNumber.tease: Immerse the ears in musical landscapes from electro/acoustic composer Kirsten Volness, California pedal steel guitarist Chuck Johnson, Minnesota band IE, and Laraaji's zither and piano.

episodesByNumber.title: #4462, Featuring the Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music based on Philip Glass, along with new work by Polish pianist Hania Rani, tunes inspired by Toni Morrison by NY pianist Jason Moran, and adventurous music by Matthew Shipp.

episodesByNumber.title: #4463, Three Trance Traditions
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music of three ecstatic traditions - Qawwali music from Pakistan, Sufi singing from Egypt, and Amhara wedding music from Ethiopia - all of which rely on deep rhythmic groove.

episodesByNumber.title: #4464, Processed Horns
episodesByNumber.tease: From Jon Hassell's trumpet to the sax of Jack Wyllie (Portico Quartet) and Tom Heasley's big sky tuba, marvel at the sounds of processed horns that might be situated in a 'fourth world'.

episodesByNumber.title: #4465, New Releases, Feb. 2021
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample works from Nonclassical's pandemic compilation featuring sax player Lara Jones, Robert Bentall's nyckelharpa, and new music group Ret Frem Ensemble. Plus, Icebreaker, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4466, Voices and Percussion
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music for voice- the original instrument- along with percussion in songs by South African choir Ladysmith Black Mambazo, French group San Salvador, and composer Bobby McFerrin.

episodesByNumber.title: #4467, Music for Guitars
episodesByNumber.tease: Get into guitar music by New York's Diego Barber, LA-Via-Istanbul Film Composer Deniz Cuylan, Welsh guitarist Gwenifer Raymond, and songwriter Ben Harper on lap steel guitar.

episodesByNumber.title: #4468, Run the World: Women in World Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear trailblazing musicians who happen to be women from around the world - Waed Bouhassoun on the oud, Rajna Swaminathan on mridangam (a two-headed drum), and Sona Jobarteh on the kora.

episodesByNumber.title: #4469, Native American and First Nations Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works by U.S. Poet Laureate and sax player Joy Harjo (Muscogee Creek), musician Leanne Betasamosake Simpson (Michi Saagiig Nishnaabeg), and sound artist Casey Koyczan (Tlicho Dene).

episodesByNumber.title: #4470, Songs About Climate Change
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear work by Kazakh-British Galya Bisengalieva, along with music by New York trio Son Lux, Norway's Marja Mortensson and Daniel Herskedal, and New Orleans-based band Blato Zlato.

episodesByNumber.title: #4471, African Experimentalists
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample works by African experimentalists and pioneers Dumama + Kechou (South Africa), the Pan-African Orchestra (Ghana), Fela Kuti (Nigeria), and the late Janka Nabay (Sierra Leone).

episodesByNumber.title: #4472, Orpheus and Eurydice and Hades and Persephone, Part 1
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds goes to hell and back in two parts in works centered on the Orpheus myth - including Eurydice's perspective - by Majel Connery, Jóhann Jóhannsson, and Anais Mitchell.

episodesByNumber.title: #4473, Orpheus and Eurydice and Hades and Persephone, Part 2
episodesByNumber.tease: New Sounds goes to hell and back in works by Anais Mitchell, Illuminine, and poet Craig Arnold centered on the Orpheus myth - including how Persephone and Hades figure into the drama.

episodesByNumber.title: #4474, Music For Bowed Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear bowed piano works which turn the insides of the grand piano into a chamber orchestra by the late Stephen Scott. Plus, music by Kelly Moran, Australia's Vincent Plush, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4475, Music From Mills College
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from alumni and/or faculty at Mills College in Oakland, from the AI-influenced work of Holly Herndon to gamelan music by Lou Harrison to legendary sax player Roscoe Mitchell.

episodesByNumber.title: #4476, Music From Documentaries
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear film scores for the documentaries Hemingway and Toni Morrison: The Pieces I Am, and for UPRIZE!, a film documenting the 1976 protests against apartheid in South Africa.

episodesByNumber.title: #4477, International Piano Day
episodesByNumber.tease: Celebrate Piano Day with music from Nils Frahm, Polish composer Hania Rani, New York pianist Jason Moran, Swiss pianist Nik Bartsch, and Iranian-American sax player Hafez Modirzadeh.

episodesByNumber.title: #4478, New Releases, March 2021
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new releases for March 2021, including music by Iraqi-born singer and oud player Natik Awayez, pianist Neil Cowley, and the 'desert blues' of Niger's Les Filles de Illighadad.

episodesByNumber.title: #4479, Pharaoh Sanders and Floating Points
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear most of "Promises," a work by the legendary sax player Pharoah Sanders and electronic musician Floating Points, a collaboration which also includes the London Symphony Orchestra.

episodesByNumber.title: #4480, Bryce Dessner: 'Impermanence/Disintegration'
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to sections of Impermanence/Disintegration, the latest by Bryce Dessner, in partnership with the Australian String Quartet and Sydney Dance Company. Plus, music by Noveller.

episodesByNumber.title: #4481, Fantas Variations
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Italian composer Caterina Barbieri's pattern-based electronic work, "Fantas," and new acoustic and electronic collaborative variations on that piece by friends and colleagues.

episodesByNumber.title: #4482, With Jake Blount Via The Soundcheck Podcast
episodesByNumber.tease: Jake Blount, a singer, fiddler, banjoist, scholar of old time music, and board member of Bluegrass Pride, interprets traditional tunes and digs into their origins in this 2020 session.

episodesByNumber.title: #4483, Recent Electronic/Electroacoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample recent electronic and electroacoustic music by Yvette Janine Jackson along with Deantoni Parks and Hanna Benn in the U.S., the U.K.'s Hannah Peel, and Christine Ott in France.

episodesByNumber.title: #4484, Piano Solo, Duos, Trios
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear piano solos, duos and trios, like Vijay Iyer with Tyshawn Sorey and Linda May Han Oh, Swedish-Iranian pianist Shida Shahabi and cellist Linnea Olsson, and pianist Brad Mehldau.

episodesByNumber.title: #4485, With ETHEL, Remotely via The Greene Space
episodesByNumber.tease: New music string quartet ETHEL plays work ranging from Hildegard von Bingen to noise-pop/electro-rocker Dan Friel for a remote New Sounds Live hosted by The Greene Space.

episodesByNumber.title: #4486, Music Inspired by the Jacobite Rebellion(S)
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear tribal Scottish band Clann An Drumma, Dublin-based duo Varo, British folk-rockers Steeleye Span, and an ARP improvisation on the "Skye Boat Song," by New York's Daniel Palkowski.

episodesByNumber.title: #4487, Spiritual Music Where East Meets West
episodesByNumber.tease: East meets West in Sufi devotional poetry and Celtic harp from Arooj Aftab, bassist Esperanza Spalding together with versatile vocalist Ganavya, and cellist Mike Block with Sandeep Das.

episodesByNumber.title: #4488, Mostly Keys and Sax
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music for mostly sax and keyboards by JJJJJerome Ellis and Lea Bertucci, along with new music from Ken Field in collaboration with Erdem Helvacioglu. Plus, music by Colin Stetson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4489, Poetry and Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear contemporary poetry enhanced by music, with work by Joy Harjo, Ross Gay with Justin Vernon and harpist Mary Lattimore, and work by psych-soul artist Nick Hakim and Roy Nathanson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4490, New Releases, April 2021
episodesByNumber.tease: Heal the spirit with Moroccan trance band Innov Gnawa (NY), and South African vocal group Afrika Mamas. Plus, work from Iceland by Eydís Evensen and from Berlin by violinist Simon Goff.

episodesByNumber.title: #4491, A Tony Allen Tribute
episodesByNumber.tease: Innovative drummer Tony Allen's unique, propulsive, funky drum patterns helped to define the style called Afrobeat with Fela Kuti. Listen to the late Allen's work and collaborations.

episodesByNumber.title: #4492, New Music From Mexico
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear traditional horns and strings from regions of Mexico in new ways that veer more experimental, in music by cellist Mabe Fratti, singer Lila Downs, and composer Felipe Perez Santiago.

episodesByNumber.title: #4493: Irish and Irish-American Music
episodesByNumber.tease: There's Irish and Irish-American music from Shrines (aka Carrie Erving), fiddler Dan Trueman, Dublin-based Varo, song collector Peia, and the Irish-American supergroup The Gloaming.

episodesByNumber.title: #4494, Pedal Steel and Lap Steel
episodesByNumber.tease: Baltimore-based virtuoso Susan Alcorn, California composer Chuck Johnson, and Norwegian player Geir Sundstøl are among the guitarists offering new approaches to pedal and lap steel.

episodesByNumber.title: #4495, Music and Poetry
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear poetry and music from Carl Hancock Rux with Meshell Ndegeocello and The Baptism, Marianne Faithfull with Warren Ellis reciting Keats, and composer Hannah Peel with poet Will Burns.

episodesByNumber.title: #4496, Fast Movement/Slow Motion
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music with lots of movement, but slower harmonic motion by Lithuanian composer Ziboukle Martinaityte, Iceland's Gunnar Andreas Kristinsson, and California-based John Adams.

episodesByNumber.title: #4497, London's New-Jazz Scene
episodesByNumber.tease: Take a tour of London jazz, including music by Sons of Kemet and its members, drummer Moses Boyd, trumpeter Yazz Ahmed, the Afrobeat collective Kokoroko, and spiritual jazz by Maisha.

episodesByNumber.title: #4498, Music for Piano
episodesByNumber.tease: Piano is up front for this New Sounds program with music by Chinese-American composer Thomas Oboe Lee, Anglo-Malaysian musician Lucinda Chua, and Japanese-American pianist Erika Dohi.

episodesByNumber.title: #4499, Dance Music from the Soundcheck Podcast
episodesByNumber.tease: Get into those gold lamé hotpants for some dance music from the Soundcheck Podcast by Colombian one-man band Monte, German-Swiss duo Grandbrothers, and Krautrock-y American band LNZNDRF.

episodesByNumber.title: #4500, Women's Voices From the South Asian Diaspora
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music featuring women's voices from the South Asian Diaspora, with Indian songwriter Priya Darshini, Pakistani-American composer Arooj Aftab, and Kirtan singer Manika Kaur.

episodesByNumber.title: #4501, Songs and Instrumentals With Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear songs and instrumentals by violinist Gwen Laster and New Muse 4tet, Brazilian cellist/singer Dom La Nena, Finnish experimental folk duo Akkajee, and Czech cello duo Tara Fuki.

episodesByNumber.title: #4502, May 2021 New Releases
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from Senegalese singer Oumar Ndiaye with Smokey Hormel, Ivorienne singer Dobet Gnahore, guitarist Shane Parish, and music for kantele by Norwegian artist Sinikka Langeland.

episodesByNumber.title: #4503, Brass Songs and Instrumentals
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear brass-forward songs and instrumentals, featuring works by Conrad Tao and the Westerlies, David Karsten Daniels and Fight the Big Bull, and Hypnotic Brass Ensemble with Moses Sumney.

episodesByNumber.title: #4504, Voices in Collaboration
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Japanese vibraphonist Masayoshi Fujita with vocalist Hatis Noit, Sardinian prepared guitarist Paolo Angeli, with Omar Bandinu of Tenores di Bitti, and Orchestra di Piazza Vittorio.

episodesByNumber.title: #4505, African Collaborations
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear cross-cultural music with roots in Sub-Saharan Africa, or with a Caribbean-African connection by Cuban pianist Omar Sosa, Canadian-Malian Djely Tapa, and France-based David Walters.

episodesByNumber.title: #4506, Inspired by Exotica!
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear contemporary music inspired by the style known as "exotica" from Norwegian composer Øyvind Torvund and BIT20 Ensemble, John Zorn, Kronos Quartet, and Italian trio Hobocombo.

episodesByNumber.title: #4507, With Maria Schneider, 2021 Pulitzer Prize Finalist
episodesByNumber.tease: Composer/bandleader Maria Schneider has worked with everyone from Dawn Upshaw to David Bowie. Hear her Grammy-winning 'Data Lords,' for which she was also a Pulitzer Prize finalist.

episodesByNumber.title: #4508, The Turkish/Balkan Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: It's an hour of music that blends traditional music from Turkey and the Balkans with contemporary instruments and sounds in works by Altin Gün, Balkan Taksim, and trumpeter Ben Holmes.

episodesByNumber.title: #4509, The Mallet Instrument Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear pattern-based work by Japanese composer/percussionist Midori Takada, which in turn influenced both vibraphonist Masayoshi Fujita and Portico Quartet. Plus, music by Steve Reich.

episodesByNumber.title: #4510, Music for Vocal Ensembles
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear vocal ensembles, whether acoustic or electronic virtual choirs in music from Roomful of Teeth, composers Arooj Aftab and Meredith Monk, and the band Briars of North America.

episodesByNumber.title: #4511: With Caroline Shaw and Eric Cha-Beach of So Percussion
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample music in the zone between classical and pop by vocalist/composer Caroline Shaw and the musicians of So Percussion from their collaborative album Let the Soil Play Its Simple Part.

episodesByNumber.title: #4512, The Jon Hassell Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Celebrate the late trumpeter and composer Jon Hassell's musical legacy, from his work with Brian Eno to his recent 2018 record, along with work by the musicians he inspired.

episodesByNumber.title: #4513, Hamza El Din, Live In-Studio, 1992
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a 1992 in-studio performance from the Archives by Egyptian Nubian composer, oud player, tar player, and vocalist, Hamza El Din, plus music he recorded with Kronos Quartet.

episodesByNumber.title: #4514, Electronic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to electronic music by Brooklyn-based guitarist/composer Rachika Nayar, Washington DC-based guitarist and funeral director Tristan Welch, and London-based Isambard Khroustaliov.

episodesByNumber.title: #4515, A Tribute to Julian Bream
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music from late classical guitarist and lutenist Julian Bream and a lot of his influence, including new works written and recorded especially for the 2021 New York Guitar Festival.

episodesByNumber.title: #4516,  A North African Dance Party
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Moroccan trance, desert rock of Niger, and East African pop by L.A. producer Dexter Story, Niger's Les Filles de Illighidad, Paris-based Gnawa Youmala, and Belgian band Azmari.

episodesByNumber.title: #4517, From the Soundcheck Podcast: Priya Darshini and Ólafur Arnalds
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample music from the Soundcheck Podcast series of live performances by the Icelandic composer and pianist Ólafur Arnalds, and the Mumbai-born, Brooklyn-based singer Priya Darshini.

episodesByNumber.title: #4518, Electroacoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear electroacoustic music with improvisation and a sense of space by London's cosmic jazz trio The Comet Is Coming, Texas combo Olsen St. Clair, and NY sax player/composer Lea Bertucci.

episodesByNumber.title: #4519: 'Femenine' by Julius Eastman, Played by Wild Up
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear a generous portion of Julius Eastman's 1974 work Femenine, an album-length piece built around a minimalistic ritualistic groove, as played by L.A. based new music group Wild Up.

episodesByNumber.title: #4520, Inspired By Tony Scott's Music For Zen Meditation
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear music inspired by the slowed-down-to-ambient 1960s approach of jazz clarinetist Tony Scott, before "ambient/new age" was a term. Plus, music by Charles Lloyd and Jeremiah Cymerman.

episodesByNumber.title: #4521, Nuevo and Neo Tango
episodesByNumber.tease: From Astor Piazzolla to brand new music by Los Tangueros del Oeste, hear Tango, Neuvo Tango, and Neo Tango from Serbia, England, Finland, France, U.S.A, Uruguay, and Argentina.

episodesByNumber.title: #4522, New Releases, July 2021
episodesByNumber.tease: There's composed and improvised music by cross-coastal composer Danielle Eva Schwob for PubliQUARTET, PRISM Quartet with Joe Lovano, and Girls in Airports with Aarhus Jazz Orchestra.

episodesByNumber.title: #4523, Contemporary Muwashshahat
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to contemporary Muwashshahat, flowing Arab poetry with music, including work by Syrian cellist and composer Kinan Abou-afach, Canadian trio Diar, and Jon Balke with Amina Alaoui.

episodesByNumber.title: #4524, Musical Sunsets
episodesByNumber.tease: It's music for the end of the day, with works by the late British composer David Bedford, guitarscapes by Noveller, and an AI-generated piece by composer-vocalist Julianna Barwick.

episodesByNumber.title: #4525, Drone Folk
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear folk songs with a drone, whether acoustic or electric, audible or implied, in work by Dublin-based Lankum, first lady of folk Shirley Collins, and from Marion Cousin and Kaumwald.

episodesByNumber.title: #4526, New Music for Harp ,
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music for harps as spiritual jazz, ambient music, eerie electronics, and a work by John Cage in music from Brandee Younger, Mary Lattimore, Zeena Parkins, and Lauren Scott.

episodesByNumber.title: #4527, Music from Afghanistan
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear Khorasani folk adapted by the duo Badieh, rubâb music from Homayun Sakhi with Kronos Quartet and Afghan-American Quraishi's solo rubâb, and music from the Hazara by Hamid Sakhizada.

episodesByNumber.title: #4528, From Soundcheck: Erika Dohi, Gary Lucas
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music from NYC-based pianist/composer Erika Dohi and guitarist/songwriter Gary Lucas from their remote sessions for the Soundcheck Podcast.

episodesByNumber.title: #4529, New Music Built On Old Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear how composers Molly Herron (USA), Ryan Molloy (Ireland), Ambrose Field (England), and Judith Berkson (USA) take old songs and use them as materials for their own works.

episodesByNumber.title: #4530, Choral Music,
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear mostly sacred choral music including Christian and prayers from Arvo Pärt and Caleb Burhans, along with Buddhist prayer set by Lou Harrison and Philadelphia composer Robert Moran.

episodesByNumber.title: #4531, New Releases, August 2021 ,
episodesByNumber.tease: There's new music by German keyboardist, composer, and producer Max Richter, by Oslo/Berlin-based sax player Bendik Giske, and from the NY-based experimental chamber ensemble 9 Horses.

episodesByNumber.title: #4532, Music for Guitar and Strings
episodesByNumber.tease: Listen to music for guitar and strings, from Guatemalan cellist Mabe Fratti, Douglas J. Cuomo's work for Aizuri Quartet and Nels Cline, and a piece by Norway's Terje Rypdal.

episodesByNumber.title: #4533, With Molly Herron ,
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear new music where Minimalism and the Renaissance overlap by New York-based composer Molly Herron from her new record, 'Through Lines: New Music for Viola da Gamba,' and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4534, Remembering Terezín, With Jocelyn Pook
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear some of the song cycle/theatre piece by English composer and violist Jocelyn Pook called "Drawing Life, Remembering Terezín," which uses archived voices, live singing and ensemble.

episodesByNumber.title: #4535, Works Commemorating 9/11
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works commemorating the 9/11 attacks, by Pulitzer Prize-winning composers Julia Wolfe, Steve Reich, and John Adams, and a choral requiem by Robert Moran.

episodesByNumber.title: #4536, Music for Cello, and Voice,
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music for cello and voice from Guatemalan Mabe Fratti, Brazilian Dom La Nena, Anglo-Malaysian Lucinda Chua, American Maya Beiser, German Anne Müller, and Scotsman Peter Gregson.

episodesByNumber.title: #4537, Electronic, Acoustic, and Electroacoustic Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Is it electronic music, acoustic music, or both? Hear works by Canadian Kara-Lis Coverdale, the group Contemporaneous, sound art from composer David Bird and pianist Ning Yu, and more.

episodesByNumber.title: #4538, Music from Southern Africa
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music from southern Africa by Zambian-Scottish artist Namvula, Rwanda's The Good Ones, and the Kasai Allstars from Kinshasa. Plus, music from Omar Sosa's East African Journey.

episodesByNumber.title: #4539, A Little Night Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear nocturnal music by Uzbek composer Dmitri Yanov-Yanovsky, New York composer Kelly Moran, Serbian-born Aleksandra Vrebalov for Kronos Quartet, and North Carolina-based Sarah Louise.

episodesByNumber.title: #4540, A Post-Jazz Playlist
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear "post-jazz" music for this show from Burnt Sugar The Arkestra Chamber, sax player Caroline Davis leading a quintet with strings, and jazz and Moroccan trance meet in Ensemble Fanaa.

episodesByNumber.title: #4541, Cosmopolitan Cairo
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music by Cairo-based producer/musician Maurice Louca and oud player Natik Awayez, along with 1970's Egytian pop composer Baligh Hamdi and legendary singer Oum Kalthoum.

episodesByNumber.title: #4542, Songs Without Words
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear works featuring the voice as instrument by vocalist Lesley Flanigan with percussion group Recap, multi-instrumentalist Peter Broderick, and Dutch sound artist Rutger Zuydervelt.

episodesByNumber.title: #4543, African and Pan-African Brass
episodesByNumber.tease: There's brass music from Africa and the African Diaspora with works by London's Balimaya Project, Benin's venerable Orchestre Poly-Rythmo, and veteran of Ghanaian highlife, Ebo Taylor.

episodesByNumber.title: #4544, New Releases, Sept. 2021
episodesByNumber.tease: Sample new ambient music from The Klezmatics and Korean duo Dal:um; plus the avant-folk of Cyprus trio Monsieur Doumani and the Scandinavian-Southeast African collaboration Monoswezi.

episodesByNumber.title: #4545, Sounds of the Subcontinent
episodesByNumber.tease: There's vocal music from Pakistani surti master Ustad Saami, and instrumentals by sarod virtuoso Amjad Ali Khan with Joe Walsh (The Eagles), and with classical guitarist Sharon Isbin.

episodesByNumber.title: #4546, Ambient and Post-Classical Music
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear ambient and post-classical works by Belgian violinist/violist Catherine Graindorge, Norwegian bassist Jo Berger Myhre, French composer Odalie, Berlin-based Nils Frahm, and others.

episodesByNumber.title: #4547, The Folk Influence
episodesByNumber.tease: Hear the influence of folk music associated with Appalachia and the British Isles, in music from Ireland's Dave Flynn, Michigander Laurel Premo, and New York-based bassist Devin Hoff.

episodesByNumber.title: #4548, The Other Georgia
episodesByNumber.tease: There's music by polyphonic choir Zedashe Ensemble, microtonal jazz by Giorgi Mikadze with Georgian choir Ensemble Basiani, and Georgian songs arranged by Evan Ziporyn and Kate Bush.
